<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Honduras-Power     03-23 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-Power,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Still A Political Force In Honduras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the farmworkers union failed
to persuade civilian officials to remove Mario Espinal as head of
the National Agrarian Institute, it took its case to the armed
forces chief.
   In going to Gen. Humberto Regalado and the military high command
the National Association of Honduran Campesinos made plain its
feeling, shared by others, that real power in Honduras does not lie
with the civilian government of President Jose Azcona Hoyo.
   The union is seeking Espinal's ouster from the Cabinet-level
post on grounds that he was stalling on agrarian reform.
   Espinal, nevertheless, remains in his post, confirmed once again
by Azcona Hoyo, and so far as is known Regalado has not acted.
   The campesinos' tactic was also used in the past few years by
bus drivers, teachers, business leaders and other sectors. It
underscores the powerful, even dominant, role still exercised by
the armed forces six years after Honduras restored civilian
government.
   Honduras has a long history of military governments, most
recently in the 1972-82 period.
   ``The people know where the source of power lies,'' said Anibal
Puerto, vice president of the Independent Human Rights Commission
and a critic of Azcona Hoyo's administration. Even government
supporters acknowledge the imbalance of power.
   ``Longstanding vices are not gotten rid of from the night to the
morning,'' said Joaquin Luna Mejia, president of the Honduran
Council on Private Enterprise.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, he said consolidation
of civilian power ``is coming along well.'' But he also observed,
``Here, as in all countries, interests are managed according to the
real powers. And if those powers are ambitious, we could fall again
into old vices.''
   ``No Honduran politician is going around saying, `We've got to
put the military back in the box,' because here the military never
has been in the box,'' said a Western diplomat.
   Compared to its neighbors, Honduras has enjoyed a degree of
stability and peace during a decade of regional conflict. But the
civil wars surrounding it have caused big problems.
   ``We have become a sanctuary,'' said Luna Mejia of Honduras'
tens of thousands of refugees from El Salvador, Nicaragua and
Guatemala, all torn by guerrilla wars. ``We are victims of the
entry into our country of irregular forces.''
   He referred to the Contras, who since 1982 have been trying to
topple the Sandinista government in Nicaragua. Until last year, a
Contra force estimated at 6,000 to 12,000 men had waged the better
part of the campaign from base camps in Honduras along the
Nicaraguan border. The rebels say most of their forces are now
inside Nicaragua.
   By congressional vote, the United States has cut off further
military aid, damaging prospects for long-term effectiveness inside
Nicaragua.
   ``There is a great concern that the Contras, if defeated, will
try to come back here,'' said Luna Mejia.
   Gen. Regalado told journalists in February he hoped the Contras
would be able to keep up their fight but said if they cannot, they
are not welcome back in Honduras.
   ``We have instructed immigration authorities along the border to
ensure that they do not return,'' he said.
   Puerto sees a connection between the Contra problem and
continued military preponderance in Honduran politics. Citing
Honduras' very strong alliance with Washington, he said: ``To whom
does the Honduran army owe its allegiance? Everything indicates it
owes its allegiance to the United States, and not to its own
people.''
   He said civilian government and close alignment with the United
States had done little to alleviate the poverty of hundreds of
thousands in this mainly agricultural country of 4.5 million people.
   ``People expected something different from civilian government,
but they got more of the same,'' Puerto said. ``If things continue
like this, people may lose faith in so-called democracy and look
for other less desirable forms of struggle.''
   Azcona Hoyo is past the midway point in the four-year term to
which he was inaugurated in January 1986. Elections are scheduled
in November 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
