<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 3rdLd-Writethru a0895 03-23 1075</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0895,1103</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arizona Senate Now on Second Charge in Mecham Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `A Mecham...', with 6 grafs to UPDATE with
quotes from Mecham radio interview vowing to appeal to Supreme
Court if convicted, fire chief accuser. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
`Deputy Maricopa...'. SUBS 25-27th gravs pvs, bgng `Leonard,
promising...', with 1 graf to tighten, picking up 28th graf,
`Meanwhile, a...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor told the Arizona Senate on
Tuesday that Gov. Evan Mecham's $80,000 loan from a protocol fund
to his car dealership was an ``intentional and wrongful act,''
while the defense acknowledged it was ``not politically smart.''
   The statements came as the Senate turned to the second of three
charges against Mecham at his impeachment trial _ misusing state
funds.
   Mecham, who has not attended the trial except when he testified
last week, said Tuesday in a radio interview that he probably will
appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court if the state Senate convicts him
in his impeachment trial.
   The governor also said that if he is acquitted and allowed to
resume his job, he will fire state Department of Public Safety
Director Ralph Milstead, one of his chief accusers in the trial.
   ``They'll probably say this is another one of those gaffes, but
a lot of the rats have come out of their holes that's been after
me, and now we know a lot more who they are,'' Mecham said. ``Quite
frankly, I'll be a lot wiser governor from here on out.''
   Mecham said if he is convicted by the Senate, ``It will
certainly not be on the basis of evidence and on that we'll go and
appeal it, of course ... probably direct to the U.S. Supreme
Court.''
   ``If they were to try to forbid me from holding office without
showing that there was some justification, I don't think they could
prevail.''
   At the trial, a Mecham campaign adviser and a deputy county
attorney testified that the $80,000 was raised by Mecham's
inaugural ball and put into a protocol fund to be used for gifts
such as Indian dolls and ashtrays for visiting dignitaries.
   Deputy Maricopa County Attorney Howard Schwartz, who helped
draft the agreement to place the money in the protocol fund, said
that when he heard about the loan, ``I personally was shocked and
initially felt betrayed.''
   ``I was very surprised and disappointed and saddened by the
entire situation ...,'' said Warner Lee, a former state attorney
general who advised the Mecham inaugural committee. ``Such an
application of the funds was never anticipated by anyone involved.''
   Schwartz and Lee acknowledged Mecham's defense lawyer's
suggestion that everyone expected the money to be invested.
   ``I don't think anyone assumed the money would be placed in a
cigar box somewhere,'' said Lee.
   Later, Mecham's former chief of staff, Jim Colter, who signed
the $80,000 check, testified that Mecham asked him not to record a
document securing the loan. Colter did not explain why Mecham would
not have wanted it recorded.
   ``I asked the governor, `Do you want this deed of trust
recorded?'' Colter recalled. ``He said, `I would rather you
wouldn't.' I don't think anything more was said.''
   Colter said he felt that the loan was ``politically unwise'' but
did not feel that any law was being broken. ``Such a thought never
entered my mind or I would have objected,'' he said.
   Earlier, after a heated debate, a senator withdrew a motion
consider the first-term Republican's expulsion from office merely
on the first count _ obstruction of justice. Sentiment in the
Senate was clearly against the move.
   ``It would be our everlasting disgrace if we do not consider all
of the evidence from both sides in such a historic and important
case,'' said Republican Sen. Jon Hays.
   Democratic Sen. Carolyn Walker said she was withdrawing the
motion because ``it appears I will be accused of depriving Gov.
Mecham of his rights.''
   Had Mecham been convicted on the first charge, the trial would
have ended because he would no longer be governor.
   The first of three broad impeachment charges alleges that Mecham
obstructed justice by trying to thwart an investigation into an
alleged death threat. The final testimony on that charge was heard
Tuesday.
   Mecham, the first U.S. governor to face an impeachment trial in
six decades, also is charged with concealing a $350,000 campaign
loan.
   Mecham is scheduled for an April 21 criminal trial on felony
charges of concealing the $350,000 loan. He also faces a May 17
recall election.
   In a low-key, 15-minute opening statement, House prosecutor
William French told senators: ``The $80,000 loan to Mecham Pontiac
was wrong.''
   Defense attorney Jerris Leonard responded that the loan broke no
law.
   ``It was not politically smart, there's no question about that
...,'' said Leonard. ``But I think the evidence will establish it
certainly wasn't evil.''
   French said Mecham's inaugural committee planned to use the
$92,000 raised by the ball to reduce Mecham's campaign debt, but
learned that a state campaign spending law might forbid it and
agreed to the protocol fund instead.
   In July 1987, French said, an $80,000 check was written on that
account to Mecham's car dealership.
   French scoffed at Mecham's oft-stated contention that he helped
the state by paying higher interest than the money would get from a
bank.
   ``The evidence will show it was not a good loan,'' said French.
``It was a bad loan because of the financial condition of Mecham
Pontiac. ... The money was loaned to Mecham Pontiac because they
had a desperate need for it.''
   Leonard, promising a return appearance to the witness stand from
Mecham, said the governor would stand by his contention that the
loan was fiscally wise and noted the loan was repaid before the
charges were filed.
   Meanwhile, a lawyer defending Mecham on the criminal charges
sought dismissal on grounds that the governor has been singled out
for prosecution because he is unpopular.
   Other Republican politicians _ including Attorney General Bob
Corbin, whose office sought the indictment _ oppose Mecham and
``they believe that the party would be better if he is out of
there,'' defense lawyer Michael Scott told Judge Michael Ryan of
Maricopa County Superior Court.
   However, prosecutor Michael Cudahy said, ``It's a crazy
allegation and there is no support for it.''
   Ryan did not immediately rule on the motion to dismiss the
charges on grounds of selective prosecution.
</TEXT>
