<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0642EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Vetoes     03-23 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Vetoes,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veto Override Ninth of Reagan's Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Civil Rights Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From copyrights to civil rights, Congress has
overridden nine of the 63 vetoes President Reagan has exercised
since he took office in 1981.
   This gives Reagan a better batting average than his last
Republican predecessor, President Ford but not as good a one as
President Carter, who had Democratic majorities in both houses of
Congress.
   Ford, with the opposition party controlling both the House and
Senate, sent up 66 vetoes and had 12 of them, or 18 percent,
knocked down.
   Carter vetoed 31 bills and had only two of them overridden, well
under 10 percent.
   Counting Tuesday's override of his civil rights bill veto,
Reagan has struck out 14 percent of the times he has used his
constitutional power to disapprove legislation.
   Reagan has faced Democratic control in the House throughout his
more than seven years in office. The Senate, however, was under
Republican control from 1981 until last year.
   It takes a two-thirds majority of both houses to overcome a
presidential veto.
   Records of the White House executive clerk's office show that
five Reagan vetoes have been sustained. In the other 49 cases, the
question of an override was not put to a vote.
   Once, Reagan squeaked through by one vote. That was on June 5,
1986, when the Senate sustained a presidential veto allowing a
weapons sale to Saudi Arabia to proceed. The count was 66-34, just
shy of the 67 votes needed for a two-thirds majority with all
senators voting.
   On another occasion, it took nearly eight months to round up the
votes to block the House from overriding the president's veto of
trade legislation curbing textile, apparel and shoe imports. Reagan
vetoed the bill on Dec. 17, 1985. The House put off action until
next year and it was not until Aug. 6, 1986, that it voted. The
count was 276-149, or eight votes short of the two thirds needed to
override.
   Tuesday's House and Senate votes marked the 101st time in U.S.
history that a presidential veto has been overridden. There have
been 2,452 vetoes, beginning with the administration of George
Washington.
   Andrew Johnson had the worst veto record in history. The
post-Civil War president vetoed 29 bills and was overridden 15
times.
   The bills previously put into law over Reagan's veto were:
   _An act to amend the manufacturing clause of the copyright law,
vetoed July 8, 1982.
   _A $14.2 billion supplemental appropriation for the fiscal year
ending Sept. 30, 1982, vetoed on Aug. 28, 1982.
   _An act authorizing a transfer of federal land in Lane County,
Ore., vetoed Oct. 19, 1983.
   _An act to authorize continuation of a program of water
resources research, vetoed Feb. 21, 1984.
   _An act revising authorization laws governing the National
Institutes of Health and National Research Institutes, vetoed Nov.
8, 1985.
   _An act providing economic sanctions against the white minority
government of South Africa, vetoed Sept. 26, 1986.
   _The Water Quality Act of 1987, a $20 billion anti-pollution
measure, vetoed Jan. 30, 1987.
   _The Federal Aid Highway Act of 1987, an $88 billion highway and
mass transit measure, vetoed March 27, 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NativePress Bjt   03-23 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Native Press, Bjt,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Native American Newspapers Struggling To Establish Independence
From Tribes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It has been more than 160 years since the first
American Indian newspaper was published and its editor clashed with
tribal leaders, and newspapers on the reservation still struggle
for their independence today.
   Elias Boudinot opened the Cherokee Phoenix on Feb. 21, 1828, in
New Echota, Ga., and resigned four years later rather than accept
censorship from the Cherokees' primary chief.
   Things haven't changed much in 160 years, journalists reported
at a meeting of the Native American Press Association. Tribal
leaders still are not convinced of the value of objective reporting
on tribal politics and other news.
   Although some tribal constitutions had free press provisions as
early as the mid-1800s, the U.S. Constitution's First Amendment
rights did not extend to the reservations until 1968, when Congress
passed the Indian Bill of Rights.
   Today's Indian journalists, the first generation to try to
exercise those rights on the reservation, are hampered by
reservation poverty that limits advertising revenue and forces
tribal governments to underwrite the newspapers.
   Ten financially self-sufficient newspapers are operating, most
begun in the last decade ``precipitated by the need for editorial
independence,'' said Richard LaCourse, a Yakima Indian writing a
book on the Native American press.
   The rest of the 464 Indian newspapers and bulletins on
reservations and in urban Indian communities are owned by the
tribes _ and controlled by tribal leaders who often interfere with
news operations, LaCourse said.
   Tribal leaders have fired editors for taking opposing sides in
elections or in editorials; cut off newspaper funds; forced the
hiring of their unqualified relatives; excluded reporters from
meetings and suppressed stories by threatening editors and
reporters, LaCourse said.
   At the NAPA meeting last week, one editor reported being ordered
by tribal leaders not to report the conviction of one leader on a
child molestation charge.
   The editor said she agreed because, as a single parent, she felt
she could not risk losing what was one of the few full-time jobs
she could find on the reservation.
   A reporter for one of 25 Indian-owned radio stations said her
tribal leaders once took over the station for several hours to air
their views on a subject they thought the station had not covered
sufficiently.
   Tim Giago, a co-founder of NAPA who owns two independent tribal
newspapers, says the interference will continue until journalists
buy their publications from the tribes and operate them as
profit-making businesses.
   ``If the tribe is paying your salary, why should they let you
say anything that is going to undermine their position?'' he asked
in a telephone interview from his offices in Rapid City, S.D.
   Because his LaKota Times of Martin, S.D., and Ojibwe Times of
Bemidji, Minn., rely on advertising revenue, Giago said, ``We have
the freedom to criticize the tribal government. My responsibilities
are to my readers. I'm not beholden to the tribal government.''
   An example of tribal leaders' influence was the Navajo Times
Today, a one-time weekly that became the first and only daily
Native American newspaper in 1984 and was closed in 1987.
   Shortly after his election, tribal Chairman Peter MacDonald
ordered an audit that found the newspaper was $750,000 in debt. He
shut it down and fired its 49-member staff.
   The Times reopened as a weekly with a new, mostly non-Indian
staff several months later.
   ``The main reason the Times was killed was because we couldn't
be controlled,'' former editor and publisher Mark Trahant, who made
the Times a daily newspaper, said in a speech to about 150 NAPA
members.
   Trahant, an investigative reporter for the Arizona Republic in
Phoenix, said the Times apparently caused animosity when it
sponsored a tribal election campaign debate that degenerated into a
name-calling shouting match.
   MacDonald did not return a telephone call to tribal headquarters
in Window Rock, Ariz., seeking comment.
   The first Indian publisher, Boudinot, clashed with Cherokee
chief John Ross, who wanted to fight the relocation law that
eventually forced the Cherokees and four other tribes to give up
their East Coast lands and move West.
   Ross tried to fire him but Boudinot resigned first, in the
summer of 1832, and moved his family to Oklahoma in 1838 in advance
of the ``Trail of Tears,'' when 4,000 Cherokees died on a forced
march from Appalachia.
   On June 23, 1839, in Park Hill, Okla., Boudinot was stabbed and
hacked to death in what was described then as a revenge killing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0321EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmExports     03-23 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Exports,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Beef And Citrus Curbs Criticized by American Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese curbs on beef and citrus imports are
costing consumers in Tokyo two to four times what their American
counterparts pay and should come down, U.S. farm and trade
officials say.
   ``It seems to us the Japanese consumer should have a right to
choose the products at a price that is much better, and they would
if the quotas were eliminated,'' Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng
said Tuesday.
   Lyng and U.S. Trade Representative Clayton K. Yeutter said at a
news conference, however, that thus far the Japanese have not
budged on quotas that limit imports of American beef and citrus.
   ``We still have to hear from the Japanese on their willingness
to liberalize beef and citrus,'' Lyng told the session, called to
spotlight the March 31 expiration date of a beef and citrus
agreement with the Japanese.
   Under the 4-year-old agreement, the United States has not
challenged the quotas. But officials are now saying that it is time
for them to end.
   In response, Japanese officials say that lowering the barriers
would bring on a torrent of low-priced American products that would
wipe out their home country's beef and citrus sector.
   The two American officials produced charts showing that American
navel oranges that sold for 33 cents each in Washington on March 1
were selling for 65 cents each in Tokyo.
   Grapefruits selling for 32 cents each in Washington sold for 73
cents in Tokyo on the same day, they said. They said consumers in
the nation's capital were paying $4.99 a pound for strip sirloin
while consumers in Japan's capital were paying $20.56 a pound for
comparable steak.
   It remains unclear whether eliminating the import curbs would
bring on unemployment among Japanese cattle ranchers and citrus
growers, Yeutter said. He said it would depend ``on whether our
Japanese friends are resilient'' enough to cope with intensified
competition.
   ``If it did mean some structural adjustment, that's the price we
pay for a free and open trading system,'' Yeutter said. ``We've had
some adjustment, too.''
   One option open to the United States would be to seek a ruling
against the Japanese for unfair trade practices under the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the officials said. They said
another would be to start action possibly leading to retaliation
against the Japanese barriers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0028 </DOCNO>
