<HEAD>Simon Pushes For Workers' Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST ALLIS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon, calling himself an
``underdog fighting for the underdog,'' says he hopes Wisconsin's
progressive political tradition can carry him to victory in the
state's April 5 primary.
   Simon, who won the Democratic primary in his home state of
Illinois last week, needs another victory to keep his candidacy
alive. While he did not predict a win here, he said he expects a
strong finish.
   ``I grew up in the progressive tradition,'' said Simon. ``I'm an
underdog who's fighting for the underdog.''
   Simon appeared at a news conference at a shopping center built
adjacent to the Allis-Chalmers Corp. plant, a once-mighty farm
equipment company which filed for bankruptcy reorganization last
year.
   ``We have to restore and revitalize our manufacturing base,''
Simon said, noting how high paying jobs at the factory have
disappeared while low paying service jobs at the shopping center
have grown.
   The senator sprinkled his comments with references to former
Wisconsin Sen. Robert LaFollette, founder of the Progressive Party,
who Simon said ``stood up to individual and corporate greed.''
   Simon said he would try to stop the erosion of the manufacturing
sector by offering tax breaks for companies that create jobs while
removing tax incentives for companies that move production overseas.
   Simon flew to Washington earlier in the day, where he joined the
successful majority in the Senate in voting to override President
Reagan's veto of a sweeping civil rights bill.
   ``It's another indication of the insensitivity of the
administration to women, to people with disabilities, to
minorities,'' Simon said of the veto.
   Simon has criticized the Reagan administration's sending of
troops to Hnduras.
   ``We should use tools of diplomacy rather than weapons of war,''
Simon said. ``Both sides should concentrate on working out their
differences at the negotiating table, not on the battlefield.''
