<HEAD>Dole Says Wisconsin Just The Place To Launch Comeback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole, all but knocked out of the
Republican presidential running by Vice President George Bush, says
he needs a comeback _ and Wisconsin is just the place to start it.
   ``This is a very important state,'' Dole told the Milwaukee
Rotary Club Tuesday. ``Voters in this state are going to have an
impact. In my case, I've got a big comeback to make _ it may as
well start here.''
   The Kansas senator made his remarks while wrapping up a
three-day visit to the state, which will hold its presidential
primary April 5.
   Vice President George Bush has an overwhelming lead in the
delegate totals, but Dole said he hopes voters in Wisconsin will
look past those numbers and examine the issues.
   ``I hope people will take a hard look at all of us,'' he said.
``I'm prepared to answer all the hard questions.''
   In his speech to the business people, Dole stressed his campaign
theme of a spending freeze to curb the federal deficit.
   ``When that's in place, then we can go down program by
program,'' he said. ``I believe I'm the one candidate who can sit
down with members of both parties and hammer out a deficit
reduction package.''
   Dole outlined similar themes earlier in a speech to students and
teachers at Oak Creek High School.
   ``We're not voting for momentum,'' he said. ``We're voting for
candidates.''
   ``One thing I've learned in politics over the years is that
nobody's certain what's going to happen from one day to the next. I
know some in the media have already written my obituary,'' he said.
``I've read it. Sounds pretty good _ I made a gallant fight but
lost.''
   ``The last time I looked, the people in this state hadn't even
voted,'' he said. ``So I don't think we should write anything off.''
   Dole also repeated his request for a debate with Bush, a
challenge the vice president declined in Illinois.
   ``I would say to my chief opponent: You name one thing you've
done that's affected anybody in the state of Wisconsin, one thing
in the past seven years, and I'll buy you lunch.''
</TEXT>
