<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Bush-Poll     03-23 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Bush-Poll,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Only Democrat To Beat Bush In Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was the
only Democratic presidential contender to outpoll Vice President
George Bush in a Washington Post-ABC News poll, the newspaper
reported today.
   Dukakis led Bush, 50 percent to 45 percent, when voters were
asked which of the two they would vote for if the election were
held today.
   In other matchups, Jesse Jackson was outpolled by Bush 58
percent to 34 percent; Sen. Albert Gore Jr. lost out 53 percent to
40 percent; and Rep. Richard Gephardt was behind 53 percent to 40
percent, the Post said.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, who is not a candidate, also lost to
Bush, 53 percent to 38 percent.
   The nationwide telephone survey of 775 registered voters had a
margin of error of 4 percentage points, the newspaper said. It was
conducted Thursday through Monday.
   Dukakis did about the same against Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas,
whose prospects of gaining the Republican nomination are seen as
slim. Dukakis polled 48 percent to Dole's 44 percent, according to
the survey.
   In the survey, Bush had the highest favorable ratings of any
contender of either party, the newspaper said. More than three out
of five registered voters, including nearly half of the Democrats,
said they had a generally favorable impression of the vice
president. That represents an increase of 11 percentage points
since an ABC News-Washington Post survey in January.
   The poll suggested the popularity of Dukakis and Jackson has
also risen. A total of 57 percent of all voters had a favorable
impression of Dukakis, the newspaper said, _ about double the
January figure.
   Fifty-three percent of all voters said they had a favorable
impression of Jackson, up from 42 percent in the January survey,
the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
