<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pentagon-AIDS 520   03-23 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pentagon-AIDS, 520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Department To Test Civilian Workers Drawing Overseas
Assignments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Defense has decided to begin
AIDS testing on civilian workers destined for overseas assignments,
with an estimated 8,000 men and women to be affected during the
first year, officials said Tuesday.
   No date for the start of civilian screening has yet been
established, said the Pentagon, which already operates the world's
largest AIDS testing program.
   The AIDS blood test will be administered to civilian workers
during a complete physical examination, which will become mandatory
for those drawing overseas assignments.
   The approach is similar to that now used by the State
Department, the Pentagon officials said.
   In another move, Deputy Defense Secretary William H. Taft IV has
authorized the Army to draft a legislative proposal that would make
it easier to discharge service members on a medical disability if
they test positively for the AIDS virus.
   Such legislation, if ever enacted, could provide the military
with a means of discharging servicemen as soon as they test
positively for exposure, regardless of whether they're showing any
symptoms yet of the deadly disease itself.
   One way to do that, the sources explained Tuesday, is to broaden
the legal definition of a military disability.
   Currently, no individual on active duty who tests positively for
AIDS on a blood test can be discharged without showing other
medical symptoms of the disease.
   The decisions involving AIDS policies were first disclosed early
this month by defense sources who requested anonymity. The Defense
Department subsequently confirmed the actions, while insisting in a
written statement to The Associated Press that Taft had issued
``preliminary guidance'' without yet signing any final directives.
   ``The decision has been made even if a directive hasn't been
signed,'' countered one source. ``He was presented options and made
up his mind.''
   AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ attacks the body's
immune system and its ability to resist infection. No cure has been
found for the disease, which can be spread through sexual contact
and tainted blood.
   The Pentagon, citing the need to protect military blood
supplies, routinely tests all 2.1 million men and women on active
duty as well as all recruit applicants. A service member who tests
positively _ but who is not disabled by the disease _ is restricted
to duty inside the United States and may be limited in job
assignments.
   A recruit who tests positively is denied admission to the
military.
   Despite the massive commitment to AIDS screening, which began in
October 1985, the Pentagon has until recently focused only on
military personnel.
   According to sources, the Army has repeatedly urged AIDS testing
for all Defense Department workers as well as automatic discharge
or dismissal for those testing positively. Defense health officials
have always rebuffed those suggestions, saying they were too
far-reaching.
   The sources said Taft had finally decided to take the middle
road when it came to civilians, focusing only on those who draw
assignments outside the United States.
   The new program is expected to cost roughly $1.6 million a year,
one official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Salvador Bjt   03-23 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador, Bjt,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Politicians Talk Conciliation; Guerrillas Vow More
Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
and the rightists who defeated his party in legislative and
municipal elections have declared a willingness to work together on
this country's tremendous problems.
   But the leftist guerrillas waging an 8-year-old war against the
U.S.-backed government said Tuesday the result of Sunday's vote
would make the nation ``ungovernable.'' A rebel commander said the
electoral result _ an outright majority for the rightist opposition
in the national legislature _ favors the guerrillas by giving the
people ``a clear alternative.''
   In addition to the war, El Salvador has crippling economic
problems.
   The Central Elections Council has not yet announced the
apportionment of seats in the unicameral, 60-seat National Assembly.
   But the council president, Mario Samayoa, said on Monday the
rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, known by the Spanish
acronym Arena, got a majority of votes cast nationwide, which
assured it of a legislative majority. Local media projected Arena
would get 33 or 34 seats. The party said it had 35.
   The governing Christian Democrats had 33 seats in the outgoing
legislature. They were expected to win about 22 seats, with the
remainder going to small rightist parties. Arena also won the
mayoralties and town councils of about 200 of the country's 262
municipalities, including San Salvador.
   ``Arena is ready to work with the other parties, and with
President Duarte, so that together we might achieve the solution to
the national crisis,'' Alfredo Cristiani, president of Arena and a
legislator, said at a news conference. ``It is time to work
together on behalf of the heroic people who cast their votes
despite threats and terrorist acts.''
   The guerrillas had called for a boycott of the elections and had
stepped up urban and rural violence in the two weeks prior to the
vote. In what they called repudiation of the ``electoral farce,''
they set off three car bombs, sabotaged power lines in large parts
of the country and ordered a nationwide transport ban that they
enforced by burning more than a dozen vehicles.
   The rebels contended the elections were part of an
American-imposed counterinsurgency plan, and that they were
illegitimate in wartime.
   Despite the boycott call, about 70 percent of the 1.6 million
registered voters cast ballots. Many of them walked long distances
to do so.
   ``In the same way we have made this effort to strengthen the
democratic process, let us contribute our will and capacities to
find together the road to peace,'' Duarte told the nation in a
radio and television address Monday night.
   He said the parties in the legislature were, along with the
executive branch, ``co-responsible'' for governing. Duarte said
once final results were known, he would meet with party leaders to
search for consensus on how to solve the nation's pressing problems.
   Besides the war, which has killed 65,000 people and made
refugees out of 500,000, El Salvador's economy is crippled. Both
inflation and unemployment are estimated at about 40 percent.
   ``What is coming is that we're on the road to a power void,''
guerrilla commander Joaquin Villalobos said Tuesday on Radio
Venceremos, the clandestine rebel station. ``The country will
become ungovernable with this composition of forces.
   ``The big loser is the counterinsurgency project and the big
winner is the people, which has before it a clear alternative _ the
FMLN, organization and struggle.'' The alliance of five rebel
armies is the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or FMLN.
   ``We must prepare to struggle decisively because today we
confront a weakened enemy and we must take advantage of that,'' he
said.
   Despite the politicans' conciliatory words, there were those who
speculated Arena would use its position in the assembly to further
erode popular support for the Chistian Democrats by opposing
government initiatives.
   Presidential elections are set for March 1989, and Arena could
benefit from making the Duarte administration appear even more
ineffectual than it has been in addressing the national crisis.
</TEXT>
