<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NuclearWaste     03-23 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Waste,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DOE Says It Will Limit Placement of Nuclear Waste In Pilot Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only enough nuclear waste to carry out
experiments will be placed in the repository planned as the
nation's first resting place for defense-related radioactive
wastes, the Department of Energy says.
   The department said Tuesday it was following the National
Academy of Sciences' recommendations to test whether WIPP, the
Waste Isolation Pilot Plant in underground salt beds near Carlsbad,
is suitable as a permanent repository.
   The department also said that by June it would meet the
academy's request for a detailed five-year plan for its
experimental waste disposal program for the repository, which was
designed to contain low- and intermediate level wastes.
   Both recommendations were made in report of the WIPP Panel of
the academy's Board of Radioactive Waste Management on March 3,
about four months after scientists told Congress that water seeping
into the repository threatened its ability to safely store wastes
that would remain radioactive for hundreds of thousands of years.
   The academy panel, however, concluded that technical
uncertainties regarding brine seepage at the plant were not serious
enough to halt research at the site. Shipments of waste are to
begin arriving in October.
   Energy Department officials said Tuesday the academy report will
assist in resolving the issue of brine accumulation at the site and
will be useful in burying waste in a manner that protects of the
environment.
   About 25,000 barrels of waste will be delivered to the site in
the first 1{ years of the test, the department's Albuquerque office
said Tuesday. The department originally had planned to entomb
125,000 barrels of wastes during the next five years.
</TEXT>
