<DOCNO> AP880323-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Strategy     03-23 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Strategy,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Observers Say Bush Unlikely To Break With Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Party figures say George Bush is
unlikely to break with President Reagan on a major issue, even
though Bush is trying to appeal to some groups Reagan has not
attracted.
   Bush's statement that he supports Reagan's veto of a major civil
rights bill, some observers say, reinforces the view of some that
Bush is incapable of showing any independence from Reagan.
   But Bush's top campaign spokesman, Pete Teeley, called this a
non-issue, and said the vice president's loyalty to Reagan is more
important than a show of independence.
   ``The fact is, six months ago everybody was writing that George
Bush had to disagree with the president in order to get the
nomination,'' Teeley said Tuesday. ``Everyone now sees that that
was a myth.''
   Teeley's assessment came a day after Bush, when pressed to say
whether he agreed with Reagan's veto of the sweeping civil rights
bill, told reporters that ``I'm not going to start differing'' with
Reagan after seven and a half years as vice president.
   ``I don't think that you're going to see the vice president be
critical of the president,'' Teeley said. ``I do think you are
going to see him lay out his own programs and proposals.''
   But two former GOP national chairmen said they think Bush,
sooner or later, will have to show some differences between his
views and Reagan's.
   ``The vice president is in a box,'' said one-time chairman
Richard Richards. ``If he deviates one iota, there are some
right-wing nuts out there who will say he cannot carry on the
Reagan revolution.''
   Another former chairman, Howard ``Bo'' Calloway, said that ``at
some time, there will be something pretty big where the vice
president will say, `Hey, I love the man, but I just have to
disagree.'''
   Said Mitchell Daniels, a former White House political director
for Reagan: ``It points up what you could call the veep's disease.
That is to say that every vice president must confront this
problem, especially if you're No. 2 to a very popular No. 1.
   ``With the (Republican presidential) nomination in hand and
loyalty to the president no longer the dominant or most powerful
theme, he can try his hand at establishing his own identity,''
Daniels said. ``But he must be careful that that comes through
extension, rather than exception'' to Reagan programs and policies.
   The civil rights bill, which had support from Republicans as
well as Democrats in Congress, was seen by some as a chance for
Bush to break with Reagan on an issue that Reagan was going to lose
anyway on Senate and House override votes.
   Some also saw a Bush break as necessary, given statements by
Bush and his top aides indicating that the vice president was going
to try to reach out to blacks and minorities _ groups that Reagan
failed to win in any substantial numbers in his two presidential
election victories.
   Arthur Fletcher, a black and one-time assistant secretary of
labor during the Nixon administration, said it was not essential
that Bush disagree with Reagan's veto of legislation to overturn
the Supreme Court's so-called Grove City ruling that limited
federal protection for many groups.
   He said that Bush, during an appearance before a black group
Monday night ``made a commitment that he is going to enforce all
civil rights legislation. ... The bottom line is that he was not
elected by the delegation to be the vice president, he was picked
by the president to be the vice president.''
   Bush has said on occasion that he would speak out on ``my own
vision'' of America, or ``how I would do things.'' But he also has
steadfastly insisted he would say nothing that could be taken as a
direct criticism of the president.
   Last October, for instance, Bush seemed to have gone back to his
1980 position on abortion. He said, in Iowa, that he supported
allowing the procedure to be performed in cases where the mother's
life was in danger, or in cases of rape or incest. This was a
departure from Reagan's position, which is that abortion should be
allowed only to save a mother's life.
   The Bush campaign heatedly denied that the vice president was
reverting to his position of 1980. Bush had muted his differences
with Reagan on this issue in 1984 when they ran for re-election
together.
   Richards said Tuesday that ``I think the time may well come when
he takes a different position. I'm sure that George Bush doesn't
agree 100 percent with everything that this administration does.
... He's in a tough spot.''
   Calloway agreed that Bush has been faced with ``a very real
problem from the day he announced his candidacy.'' But he said ``I
don't think he ought to go out of his way and find differences''
with Reagan.
   ``I'll bet a nickel the president has told him, `Look, George,
you're running now. You've got to be your own man,''' Calloway said.
</TEXT>
