<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Assess     03-23 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Assess,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electoral Victory Moves Salvadoran Rightists Into A Strong
Position</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After gaining control of the
National Assembly, the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance
could block the president's program and mount a strong challenge in
the 1989 presidential race.
   The stinging defeat in Sunday's election left President Jose
Napoleon Duarte and his Christian Democrats on the defensive.
   Duarte will be unable to enact economic reforms and the
opposition will be able to put its stamp on the national budget and
other legislation.
   The rightist party, known by its Spanish acronym Arena, is
trying to polish its image with an eye to next year's presidential
race.
   Former army Maj. Robert d'Aubuisson, the party's founder who has
been accused of links to El Salvador's death squads, is being kept
out of the limelight as much as possible. Party chairman Alfredo
Cristiani, a U.S.-educated businessman and coffee grower, now
speaks for Arena.
   Arena is trying to project an image of a conservative
organization that wants to safeguard the country's traditional
values and restore law and order. The party once was notorious for
its diatribes against the dangers of communism and alleged
interference by the United States in Salvadoran affairs.
   Both messages are still there, but the tone is more low key.
   Shortly before the elections, Cristiani told reporters: ``The
most important change the party has made was the decision to make
Arena a true political institution rather than a movement revolving
around an individual, and without the traditional `boss-ism' of
Salvadoran politics.''
   The strategy seems to have paid off, striking a chord among
Salvadorans tired of eight years of civil war with leftist rebels
that has killed about 65,000 people and devastated the
once-prosperous economy.
   Arena on Sunday wrested control of the 60-member National
Assembly away from Duarte's Christian Democrats and won a majority
of the 262 city and town mayors nationwide, including the
traditional Duarte stronghold of San Salvador.
   Final returns are not in, but projections show Arena is assured
of at least 30 seats in the new legislature. And Arena has as its
ally the National Conciliation Party, which may hold on to most of
its 12 seats.
   The Christian Democrats are expected to lose most of their
33-seat majority to Arena, which had only 13 seats in the old
assembly.
   The outcome will make Duarte's last year in office extremely
difficult, similar to his first year when the rightist opposition
also controlled the assembly. In 1984, Duarte defeated d'Aubuisson
in a presidential race and he has governed with a Christian
Democratic-controlled assembly since 1985.
   On Monday, Duarte called on all parties to act responsibly to
solve the nation's serious problems.
   D'Aubuisson lost the 1984 election, mainly because of his
reputation of having been linked to the death squads that killed
thousands of people in the first years of the war. He has denied
the accusations, including one that he masterminded the March 1981
slaying of Archbishop Oscar Arnulfo Romero, the Roman Catholic
prelate.
   D'Aubuisson, a fiery orator, held on to his seat in the
assembly, and seems sure to play a role in party councils.
   ``If we get the majority in the assembly, the next thing you'll
hear from the `fish' will be from behind bars, because that's where
we're going to put the corrupt sons of their mothers,'' d'Aubuisson
told a crowd last week. The fish is the Christian Democratic party
symbol.
   Cristiani _ a graduate of Georgetown University in Washington,
D.C. _ also won a seat in the new assembly. He promised he would
seek a consensus in the legislature on how to deal with the leftist
rebels.
   He said the rebels would be approached with a proposal for
ending the war and, if they refused, then the legislature would
back the government in declaring an offensive to wipe them out.
   Cristiani's idea is that if only a military solution is left,
then the war should be pushed to the hilt, instead of conducting it
with a series of small confrontations like now.
   ``This low intensity conflict idea should be erased,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas Grant Mine, AP correspondent in San
Salvador, formerly worked as news editor in Buenos Aires.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
