<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EPA-NaziData     03-23 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EPA-Nazi Data,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Chief Bars Use Of Data From Nazi Camps In Agency Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Environmental Protection
Agency plans to look at the ethics of using scientific data from
Nazi concentration camp experiments but is banning use of such
information in a report on a toxic gas, an agency official says.
   EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas learned in a letter from about
20 EPA employees Friday that data from experiments on concentration
camp prisoners were included in an outside consultant's draft
report on phosgene gas, Thomas' chief of staff Craig DeRemer said
Tuesday.
   ``As soon as we got the letter ... the administrator said,
`There's no reason to proceed with that information in the report.
We don't need this data. Let's just not use this and then let's
look at the broader issue,''' DeRemer said.
   Thomas plans a broad review ``to look at the ethical issues on
using this kind of data,'' DeRemer said. ``It's sort of a new issue
that we haven't dealt with before.
   ``There may be some arguments on the other side,'' he added.
``If there is data available, no matter if it was raised in
questionable means, some people might argue that if it's for the
good of humanity we should use it.''
   The consultant's study was designed to determine whether EPA's
computer-generated predictions on how phosgene gas would affect
humans were in line with what would actually happen due to exposure
to the toxic chemical.
   Phosgene gas in high concentrations was used as a weapon in
World War I and 52 prisoners were exposed to it in 1943 and 1944 by
the Nazis to test a possible antidote, The New York Times reported
in today's editions.
   Four of the prisoners exposed at Fort Ney near Strasbourg,
France, died and many others who already were weak and
undernourished developed pulmonary edema, which causes extreme
irritation in the lungs, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
