<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Rea Award,0121</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Donald Barthelme Wins $25,000 Short Story Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Humorist Donald Barthelme was named the winner
of the $25,000 Rea Award, given annually to an outstanding writer
of short stories.
   ``No richer _ or funnier _ discourse exists in contemporary
American fiction,'' the jury said in giving the 1988 award Tuesday
to Barthelme, a 57-year-old English professor at the University of
Houston.
   The jurors, including one of the two previous Rea Award winners,
Cynthia Ozick, praised Barthelme for blending ``mockery and
exaltation'' in his stories. Robert Coover won the award last year.
   Barthelme's short story collections include ``Forty Stories,''
``Overnight to Many Distant Cities,'' ``Great Days,'' ``City Life''
and ``Unspeakable Practices, Unnatural Acts.''
</TEXT>
