<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     03-23 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fuel Economy Standards Cost Lives, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the government was reporting a slight
increase in auto fuel efficiency last year, two researchers said
federal fuel-economy standards will cause thousands of traffic
deaths in the next decade by discouraging the use of safer, larger
cars.
   ``Fuel economy regulation inevitably leads to smaller, lighter
cars that are inherently less safe than the cars that would be
produced without a binding fuel-economy constraint,'' said a study
released Tuesday by Robert W. Crandall of the Brookings Institution
in Washington and John D. Graham of the Harvard School of Public
Health in Boston.
   They estimated the standards applied to 1989 cars during 10
years of road use would cause 2,200 to 3,900 traffic deaths.
   Also Tuesday, the Transportation Department told Congress that
passenger cars sold in the United States got 28.2 miles per gallon
last year overall, up 0.2 miles per gallon from the previous year.
   Despite the good news on auto fuel economy, Transportation
Secretary Jim Burnley used the report to reiterate his support for
elimination of the fuel-economy requirement, saying it placed U.S.
manufacturers at a disadvantage against their foreign competition.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Votes To Continue Incentives For Rare-Disease Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has voted to continue and expand a
program to encourage private companies to develop drugs for
combating rare diseases.
   The bill was passed on a 401-1 vote Tuesday and sent to the
Senate. It extends the so-called ``orphan drug'' program through
fiscal 1990. It would also expand the program, which is overseen by
the Food and Drug Administration, to include special devices and
foods needed to help people with unusual maladies.
   Under the program, companies are given tax credits and
seven-year exclusive marketing rights if they develop products for
rare diseases. Without incentives, the companies would not pursue
development of those products because the small number of
beneficiaries would not make it profitable, according to supporters
of the legislation.
   The revised statute, while expanding the program, would triple
its cost in the next few years. The current annual authorization of
$4 million would grow to $14 million in fiscal 1990.
   The Reagan administration has said it has no objection to the
legislation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Funds For Reagan And President-Elect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee says it will cost $3.5
million in transitional expenses for President Reagan's successor
to move into the White House and cost Reagan $1 million to move to
retirement in California next January.
   The Government and Operations Committee Tuesday approved a bill
authorizing the funds although the Democratic-controlled panel
rejected a Republican move to increase the expense allowance to
offset the effects of inflation for the outgoing president to $1.5
million from $1 million, the level in effect since 1976.
   The proposed boost was opposed by Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, the
panel's chairman, who said the budget squeeze requires Congress to
``make some hard choices'' on spending cuts.
   The panel approved raising the president-elect's allowance for
transitional expenses to $3.5 million from $2 million, the level in
effect for the past 12 years. It also rejected, 24-9, a move by
Rep. Robert S. Walker, R-Pa., to forbid the president-elect from
accepting private donations to supplement federal transitional
funds.
   The $1 million for Reagan's initial retirement expenses, if
approved by the House and Senate, would cover his moving expenses
from the White House to California and the costs of establishing an
office for six months, until funds for former presidents become
available under a separate law.
</TEXT>
