<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NorthwestAgreement     03-23 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Agreement,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest, Flight Attendants Reach Tentative Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines flight attendants are
likely to ratify a tentative contract that forestalled a walkout by
6,500 workers, a union official said.
   ``We're optimistic the agreement will be ratified or we wouldn't
be submitting it to the membership,'' Marvin Griswold,
secretary-treasurer of the Teamsters' Los Angeles-based airline
division Local 2707, said Tuesday after the carrier and the union
announced the tentative pact.
   Flight attendants had continued working through a Feb. 26 strike
deadline, but set a March 29 deadline that threatened a walkout
during the airline's busy Easter season.
   The tentative pact reached Tuesday first must be approved by the
rank and file flight attendants negotiating committee, which meets
today or Thursday. Then, it must then be approved by the workers,
which could take about 30 days.
   Major details of the proposed contract were not released.
   Both sides acknowledged that the March 29 strike deadline
provided the impetus to reach an agreement.
   ``We wanted to see an agreement reached before the 29th ... The
29th is a sincere and serious deadline,'' Griswold told a news
conference.
   ``It gave us a target,'' said Terry Erskine, Northwest's vice
president of law and labor relations. ``It gave us a focus.
   ``If it (a strike) had occurred, we would have been ready and
would have operated the airline,'' Erskine said.
   The talks for the last two days were conducted with the help of
Joshua Javits, a member of the National Mediation Board, and
federal mediator Robert Brown, Northwest said.
   Javits said the mediators provided a framework for the two sides
to reach a settlement, but ``the parties really did it themselves.''
   Erskine said that, pending ratification, Northwest would suspend
the contract it was set to impose on April 1. The Teamsters agreed
not to engage in any job action during the ratification process.
   The key issue in the dispute was Northwest's two-tier wage
structure, of which the airline had proposed extending the
lower-paid scale to eight years from the current five years.
   B-scale flight attendants argued that the airline was trying to
break a promise that they would earn higher, A-scale wages after
five years.
   The issue had intensified since Northwest acquired Republic
Airlines in 1986. About a third of the 2,600 former Republic
attendants are on the lower scale, and the others said Northwest's
previous wage offer was inadequate.
   Jeff Musto, a Teamsters spokesman in Eagan, said only one detail
of the contract has been disclosed: that all flight attendants
hired by Northwest will be required to join the union.
   Erskine said Northwest found no evidence of ``guerilla warfare''
tactics the union had threatened as a way to keep the company off
balance.
   He also said Northwest did not see its traffic diminish during
the dispute, although he acknowledged that some people may have
booked flights on other airlines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
