<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0600EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrokeTown     03-23 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Broke Town,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copperhill Files For Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four years after a big mining company
decided to phase out its operations in Copperhill, the village
tucked in the Appalachian mountains of southeast Tennessee has
filed for bankruptcy protection.
   ``I don't know where else to scratch,'' Copperhill Mayor Sylvan
Green said in a telephone interview, calling Tuesday's Chapter 9
federal court filing a last resort for the town of about 400 people
about 60 miles east of Chattanooga.
   Much of the problem for Copperhill derives from a long-standing
dispute over a sewer and water service deal with neighboring
McCaysville, Ga. The dispute began when Tennessee Chemical Co. said
it was bailing out.
   Back in 1979, Copperhill's mining operations were owned by
Cities Service Co., the town decided to buy extra water from
McCaysville to supply what was easily Polk County's largest
employer.
   That prompted McCaysville to float a bond issue on a new water
plant and agree to pay Copperhill for sewer service.
   Then in 1982, Tennessee Chemical Co. bought the mining
operations. Two years later, it said it couldn't compete with cheap
imported copper and announced plans to lay off 900 workers by 1987.
   Suddenly, Copperhill no longer needed extra water, and when it
stopped paying for it, McCaysville began withholding its $3,000
monthly payments for sewer service. That was about two years ago.
   ``They were to purchase ... almost 50 percent of our water,
depending upon the Tennessee Chemical Company,'' said McCaysville
Mayor Barbara Thomas.
   ``Of course, the Tennessee Chemical Company did not come through
with their part of the bargain,'' she said. ``But that was not the
contract we had. We had the contract with Copperhill.''
   McCaysville claims Copperhill owes $255,000 in back water
payments. Copperhill wants payment for sewer service. Negotiations
failed and lately, said Mrs. Thomas, they haven't even been able to
agree on when to talk.
   The loss of the sewer payments put such a dent in Copperhill's
budget that Green told officials last year that the city could not
finish building its new police station.
   In the petition filed in U.S. Bankruptcy Court, Copperhill
listed debts to 12 creditors totaling $302,355.49.
   A Chapter 9 bankruptcy is designed to allow a municipal
government to maintain necessary levels of service while it
implements a plan to adjust its debts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
