<DOCNO> AP880323-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0602EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoCalQuake     03-23 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SoCal Quake,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquake Jolts People Awake In Santa Barbara</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal residents were jolted awake
by a moderate earthquake and aftershock today, prompting worried
calls to police. There were no reports of injury or damage,
officials said.
   The first shock, measuring 3.9 on the Richter scale, hit at
12:42 a.m. and was centered 11 miles southeast of downtown, said
Robert Finn, spokesman for the seismology lab at the California
Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
   Fifteen minutes later, an aftershock measured 2.7 on the Richter
scale.
   The temblors were felt in nearby Goleta and Isla Vista, and
southward in Carpinteria, Ojai, Ventura and Oxnard, about 30 miles
away, Finn said.
   ``These quakes weren't strong enough to do much damage, but a
lot of people felt them,'' Finn said.
   About 30 people telephoned Santa Barbara County sheriff's
headquarters after the Earth movement to confirm what they felt,
said Deputy Larry Ralston.
   ``They were just concerned and curious, or like one who wanted
to know if he had been dreaming,'' Ralston said.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage,
6 severe damage.
</TEXT>
