<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-23 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wind, Rain, Snow, Death in Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and high winds howled through the Northwest today after
gusts up to 68 mph felled trees, killing a teen-age girl and
injuring another.
   Osita Emetaron of Portland, Ore., was struck by a tree at Ecola
State Park on the northern Oregon coast Tuesday afternoon, said
Cannon Beach Police Officer Kristen Knight. The girl was dead on
arrival at Seaside General Hospital.
   The other girl, a 14-year-old with Ms. Emetaron whose name was
not made public, was treated at the hospital and released.
   Gusts up to 68 mph were recorded in Seaside.
   A gale warning remained in effect today along the Washington
coast and for Oregon's coastal waters. A high wind warning was
posted for the northern and central Oregon coast, and a high wind
watch was issued for eastern Washington.
   Rain showers were numerous along the coast of Washington and
Oregon late Tuesday.
   A heavy snow warning was in effect for Oregon's northern Cascade
Mountains, where up to 8 inches of snow was expected. A snow
advisory was up for the Cascades in southern Oregon and Washington.
   Temperatures were below freezing from Upper Michigan to New
England, with readings in the teens and single digits in eastern
New York state and northern New England.
   By contrast, temperatures remained above 50 degrees early today
from the Gulf Coast states to the middle Mississippi Valley, with
60s reported from Texas to western Illinois.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from eastern Oklahoma and Arkansas to eastern Kansas and Missouri,
scattered rain showers from the middle Mississippi Valley to the
upper Great Lakes and from the Northwest to the northern third of
the Rockies, and numerous rain showers from the northern Pacific
Coast to northern Washington and northwest Montana.
   Temperatures were expected to reach the 60s and 70s across much
of the nation; the 30s in northwest Minnesota and much of Maine;
the 40s in much of North Dakota, the northern Great Lakes and
southern and central New England; the 50s from Oregon to northern
Utah and from the northern High Plains to northern Lower Michigan;
the 80s from the Southwestern deserts to western and and central
Texas and western Oklahoma.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees at St. Johnsbury, Vt., to 70 degrees at Fort Lauderdale,
Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 49 fair; Boston 27 fair; Buffalo 30 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 52 cloudy; Cincinnati 56 fair; Cleveland 42 fair;
Detroit 33 fair; Miami 70 fair; New York 27 fair; Philadelphia 33
partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 35 fair; Portland, Maine 18 fair;
Washington 35 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 31 foggy; Chicago 60 windy; Dallas-Fort Worth
63 windy; Denver 38 fair; Des Moines 41 partly cloudy; Indianapolis
51 fair; Kansas City 54 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 39
cloudy; Nashville 58 fair; New Orleans 59 fair; St. Louis 62 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 51 fair; Anchorage 29 cloudy; Las Vegas 55
fair; Los Angeles 56 foggy; Phoenix 64 fair; Salt Lake City 41
partly cloudy; San Diego 57 fair; San Francisco 54 cloudy; Seattle
45 showers.
   _Canada: Montreal 18 fair; Toronto 28 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
