<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Wedtech     03-23 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wedtech,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedtech Official: I Stole $1.5 Million from Wedtech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Wedtech Corp. official who says he
bribed numerous public officials, including Rep. Mario Biaggi, also
admits that he stole $1.5 million from the defense contractor.
   Mario Moreno, ex-vice chairman of the defunct Bronx company,
detailed numerous bribes and payoffs by Wedtech.
   During his sixth day of testimony Tuesday at the racketeering
trial of Biaggi and six others, Moreno said the payoffs went to
bankers, lawyers and union leaders.
   But under cross examination, he also admitted transferring
$250,000 in kickbacks to a Swiss bank account, even after he had
agreed to cooperate with prosecutors.
   Biaggi; his eldest son; his former law partner and four others
are charged with turning Wedtech into a racketeering enterprise
that paid millions of dollars in bribes to land and maintain
government contracts.
   Moreno, the first prosecution witness, has linked the defendants
to numerous payoff and fraud schemes but he also admitted
personally stealing $1.5 million in Wedtech funds.
   Moreno also said he made false statements to the Internal
Revenue Service, state tax authorities, the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the Small Business Administration, the Defense
Department ``and a few other agencies.''
   Moreno also claimed Wedtech paid $80,000 to Rep. Robert Garcia,
D-N.Y., for ``political favors.'' Garcia, who has not been charged
with any wrongdoing, denied Moreno's allegation through a spokesman.
   The payments for ``political favors and political
introductions'' were made to Garcia ``because he and his wife
requested it,'' said Moreno.
   Moreno also said Wedtech paid $130,000 to two Bronx bankers in
early 1984 for helping the company obtain a $500,000 cash loan _ at
$150,000 interest over three months _ from a Bronx businessman;
$15,000 to a Manhattan banker who helped them launder the $500,000
cash; $10,000 to $15,000 over six years to a Consolidated Edison
manager ``to have Con Edison on our side whenever we needed it''
and a $100,000 payoff to two Teamsters officials in 1985 to settle
a dispute with another union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
