<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VietnamesePatient     03-23 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnamese Patient,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietamese Woman Who Could Not Find Marrow Donor is Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANHASSET, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese refugee has died after she
lost a fight against leukemia that prompted the Vietnamese
government to release her relatives in hope of finding a compatible
bone marrow donor.
   Myhanh Luong, 21, died of an infection stemming from her
leukemia, North Shore University Hospital spokesman Daniel Rosette
said Tuesday.
   Luong came to the United States in 1979 after a seven-day
journey from Vietnam to the Philippines in a small boat with 52
other refugees. In 1986, while attending Baruch College, she was
diagnosed with the blood cancer.
   In January, under pressure from the U.S. State Department, the
Vietnamese government granted exit visas to Luong's parents and two
sisters in Ho Chi Minh City ``on humanitarian grounds.''
   Doctors had hoped that one of them would have bone marrow that
could be transplanted to save Luong. Tests showed, however, that
their bone marrow was not compatible with hers.
   Luong's leukemia had been in remission since November, a step
which is crucial if any other life saving options were to be
attempted, Rosette said.
   In an effort to boost her spirits, doctors permitted her to go
home to Long Island for five days earlier this month.
   A week after she returned to the hospital she contracted an
infection and never recovered, Rosette said.
   ``She really enjoyed her stay at home,'' said her sister, MyMy
Luong. ``We are all very upset.'' MyMy said family members were at
her bedside when she died.
   Funeral services for Luong were held Monday in New York City's
Chinatown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
