<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Japan-Savings     03-23 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Japan-Savings,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Booming Stock Prices Boost Japan's Household Savings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average Japanese household in a recent survey
had $82,000 in savings at the end of last year, up 14.9 percent
from a year earlier, a government report published today said.
   It was the biggest annual increase in savings since 1979, when
average savings rose 15.5 percent from 1978, said Namiko Mizutani,
a statistician at the Management and Coordination Agency, which
conducted the survey.
   Mizutani said the increase resulted largely from an increase in
stock prices last year.
   Despite last October's worldwide stock market crash, the average
prices of 1,058 major stocks listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange's
first section rose about 15 percent in value from 1986, local news
reports said.
   The agency surveyed 6,150 families on Dec. 31, but left out
those engaged in agricuture and fisheries, and single people.
</TEXT>
