<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingJet 1stLd-Writethru a0535 03-23 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Jet, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0535,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Jet On Training Mission Vanishes In Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with some debris found, quotes. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coast Guard searchers today found debris they
suspected was from an Air Force F-16 jet that crashed into the Gulf
of Mexico during a training mission, but there was no sign of the
pilot, officials said.
   The unidentified pilot was flying solo 40 miles west of Fort
Myers when the jet went down Tuesday night, said Air Force Capt.
Diane Lawhon, a spokeswoman for MacDill Air Force Base.
   Officials don't know what caused the crash or if the pilot was
able to eject from the plane.
   Searchers flew over a 100-square-mile area early today and found
small pieces of debris they believe was part of the plane, said
Petty Officer Tom Gillespie.
   ``The pieces are small. The biggest is 1-foot-by-1-foot. They
are collecting the debris and will give it to the Air Force,
(which) will make the decision about whether or not it is from the
plane,'' Gillespie said from the Coast Guard's Miami office.
   He said it is ``not unusual'' to not find a pilot's remains
after crashes of impacts so strong that the plane is torn apart.
   The jet was accompanied by another F-16 from MacDill. When that
pilot lost radio contact with the downed flier, he circled around
to look for him but found nothing, Ms. Lawhon said.
   A Coast Guard jet and helicopter searched about 40 miles off
Sarasota, said Sgt. Michelle Spicer, another MacDill spokeswoman.
MacDill sent a C-130 four-engine cargo plane to aid in the search.
   The F-16 Fighting Falcon has a F100 Pratt and Whitney engine and
is manufactured by General Dynamics. MacDill has about 100 F-16s in
its fleet, delivered in 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
