<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Taiwan-Ferry     03-23 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Taiwan-Ferry,0129</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British ferry, Herald of Free
Enterprise, that capsized off the Belgian coast last year killing
193 people aboard, arrived at a southern Taiwan scrap yard,
officials said today.
   ``The ferry was in a disastrous state. There's only mud and
garbage left inside,'' said Wang Chin-yeh, an official of Chi Shun
Hua Steel Co., a ship salvage company in the Kaohsiung, 220 miles
south of Taipei.
   The ferry arrived in the scrap yard Tuesday night after being
towed on a 50-day, 7,582 nautical mile journey from a Dutch port.
   The Herald of Free Enterprise capsized off the Belgian port of
Zeebrugge on March 6, 1987, in the worst peacetime disaster
involving a British ship since the Titanic sank in 1912.
</TEXT>
