<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Reyner Banham</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reyner Banham, an influential writer on
architecture and the arts, died Saturday of cancer at age 66.
   Banham began working at the Bristol Aeroplane Co. after World
War II. He studied art history at London University's Courtauld
Institute while writing about contemporary architecture for The
Architectural Review.
   Banham wrote three widley studied books ``Theory and Design in
the First Machine Age'' in 1960, ``The New Brutalism'' in 1966 and
``Architecture of the Well-Tempered Environment'' in 1969.
</TEXT>
