<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Philippines-USBases     03-23 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Philippines-US Bases,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks On U.S. Bases Begin Next Month In Manila</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippines and the United States
today said that on April 5 they will begin a periodic review of the
executive agreement under which the United States operates six
military bases here.
   The review of the 1947 Military Bases Agreement is expected to
center on U.S. compensation for the right to operate Clark Air
Base, Subic Bay Naval Base and four smaller installations. The
United States currently pays the Philippines $180 million in
economic and military aid annually.
   Some Philippine legislators have suggested the figure be
increased to more than $2 billion a year. Foreign Secretary Raul
Manglapus, chief Philippine negotiator in the talks, says $1.2
billion annually would be ``realistic.''
   In addition to compensation, the bases also employ 68,000
Filipinos. The United States estimates the installations add nearly
$1 billion a year to the local economy.
</TEXT>
