<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0638EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarvardDonation     03-23 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Donation,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plan to Make Major Donors Harvard Officers Draws Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deal to bestow prestigious Harvard positions on
a Texas couple in exchange for a $500,000 donation has drawn fire
from a senior administrator of the university's John F. Kennedy
School of Government.
   Executive Dean Richard Cavanagh praised some aspects of the
school's ``entrepreneurial style of raising money'' but complained
about the tentative deal in a confidential report based on a
two-month study of funding efforts.
   ``It is clear that this was an unusual, unhappy and unfortunate
incident _ the product of misunderstanding, inexperience, sloppy
handling and hasty processing,'' said Cavanagh.
   Cavanagh's comments were carried in the latest edition of the
weekly Harvard Gazette, published by the university. Harvard
officials confirmed the accuracy of his statements but declined to
release his report.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said no
decision has been made on whether to conclude the agreement. One
official suggested that the controversy surrounding the deal was
the reason for putting it on hold.
   Cavanagh was appointed in December and asked to examine the
school's fund-raising methods. Other Harvard institutions also
conducted fund-raising surveys on orders from Harvard President
Derek Bok.
   Bok's action followed publication by the Harvard Crimson student
newspaper in November of parts of the draft agreement between the
school and Charles Cameron Dickinson III and his wife, Joanne.
   ``The donors will be appointed by the dean to appropriate
positions in the School of Government that will accord them status
as Officers of the University with the privileges associated
therewith,'' said the agreement, tentatively approved by Kennedy
School Dean Graham T. Allison.
   Only full-time instructors and administrators normally are
appointed Officers of the University, academic, administrative or
advisory positions.
   The Crimson also published a in-house memo by an Allison aide
stating that Mrs. Dickinson wanted to know the most prestigious
title she could buy for $250,000 and asking how much it would cost
to be on an advisory committee.
   Kennedy School officials confirmed the existence the memo, but
spokesman Steven Singer declined requests Tuesday for telephone
interviews with Allison or Cavanagh.
   Allison described the deal as a mistake shortly after it came to
light.
   Dickinson, a 1980 graduate of Harvard Divinity School, comes
from a wealthy Texas oil family. No one answered the telephone at
the Dickinson residence in Wichita Falls.
   Kennedy School officials, acting on recommendations in the
Cavanagh report, recently created a position of director of
development and gave the develpment office full responsibility for
fund raising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
