<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--AssyrianGuns     03-23 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Assyrian Guns,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Arrested for Firearm Salute at Assyrian Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three members of this city's Assyrian community
were arrested by police after they fired guns repeatedly in a
cemetery salute to a dead comrade, authorities said.
   The arrests occurred Tuesday during the burial of Charles Warda,
21, who died in an auto accident last week, said Police Capt.
Clarence Zanders.
   John Cannon, an official of the Montrose Cemetery and
Crematorium on Chicago's Northwest Side, said the three men began
firing into the air as part of a makeshift salute.
   ``There was quite a bit of shooting going on, and we really
didn't think it was proper,'' Cannon said.
   Zanders said the officers who were called to the scene
discovered no injuries and no damage to property, but confiscated
five guns.
   A police spokeswoman, Tina Vicini, said gunfire has been
reported before in connection with burials in the Assyrian
community.
   Modern Assyrians, a Christian group from present-day Iraq, are
said to be the descendants of the people who ruled the ancient
Assyrian Empire before its destruction in 612 B.C.
</TEXT>
