<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0727EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0519 03-23 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0519,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>India Cancels Tennis Visit, Rioting Has Cost More Than $335
Million</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with India canceling tennis visit,
figures on cost of uprising to Israel, Cabinet to meet. CHANGES
byline.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India today canceled the visit of a tennis team
to protest Israel's handling of Arab riots, and new figures showed
that anti-occupation violence in the West Bank and Gaza Strip cost
Israel more than $335 million.
   Israel's 10-member inner Cabinet was to meet later in the day to
hear a report from Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on his talks in
the United States.
   Shamir was greeted Tuesday by thousands of singing and dancing
supporters who welcomed his steadfast refusal to accept an American
peace plan.
   ``I return satisfied, especially after people tried to frighten
me before I left that the visit would be a difficult one and that I
would hear harsh words,'' Shamir told an airport news conference.
``I'm satisfied that didn't happen.''
   Also Tuesday, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told a
parliamentary committee that Israel had jailed 3,000 Arabs since
Dec. 8, including 700 since Sunday, Israeli newspapers said today.
   In an underground leaflet circulated in the Gaza Strip, the
Palestine Liberation Organization announced payments will be made
to people who lose family members, property or jobs because of
clashes with Israeli soldiers.
   Gad Yacobi, minister of economy, disclosed that the violence
that began Dec. 8 in the occupied lands has cost Israel more than
$335 million in lost production, exports and added security costs,
spokeswoman Naama Henig said today. The tally does not include
losses in tourism and agriculture.
   ``If the situation continues, it will have a significant impact
on Israel's economy,'' she quoted Yacobi as telling Israeli
economic writers.
   Yacobi said there was a drop in overall production, especially
in construction, of 10 percent to 20 percent a month during the
last three months. This resulted in a loss of at least $75 million,
he said.
   He put the cost for extra security at $60 million.
   The biggest loss was in Israeli exports to the occupied lands _
reduced by $200 million thus far. Israeli exports to Gaza and the
West Bank totaled $1.15 billion last year.
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi announced today that his
country's Davis Cup team was canceling a visit to Israel to protest
Israeli ``repression and atrocities'' against Arabs in the
territories.
   Zvi Meyer, secretary of the Israel Tennis Association, said he
was ``very surprised and disappointed'' by the decision. He said
Israel had already sold 1,500 seats for the three-day series that
was to begin April 7.
   It was the first protest cancellation of a sporting or
entertainment event as a result of the clashes in the occupied
lands, although the violence has made it difficult for promoters to
arrange such events.
   For example, an all-star tennis fund-raiser for Israel's Sharei
Tzadek Hospital was canceled after officials said big name players
such as Chris Evert would not come because of security concerns.
   The underground leaflet distributed in Gaza said families would
receive a one-time payment of $2,900 for ``martyrs'' killed in
confrontations and $600 for anyone arrested. According to U.N.
figures, 107 Palestinians have been killed by Israeli soldiers or
settlers since Dec. 8 in the territories Israel seized in the 1967
Middle East war. One Israeli soldier has been killed.
   Merchants unable to open stores because of strikes would get
$1,450 in compensation from the PLO, and police who resigned their
jobs would get $1,450 as a first payment.
   Israeli officials have taken steps to prevent the PLO from
compensating Palestinians who suffered financial losses.
   Money changers have been particularly hard hit because one such
measure is a ceiling of $1,350 on the amount of money brought into
Israel by individuals or institutions, an official said on
condition of anonymity.
   Demonstrations subsided this afternoon in Israel's occupied
lands, although Arab reports said a curfew was extended on Deir Al
Balah in the Gaza Strip after an overnight demonstration in which
youths threw stones at soldiers.
   All of Gaza is under a nightly curfew until 3 a.m.
   On Tuesday, a Palestinian motorist was ambushed and killed near
the Gaza Strip town of Khan Yunis, and Israeli troops shot and
killed a Palestinian in the West Bank village of Tubas.
</TEXT>
