<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Botha     03-23 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Botha,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Denounced For Intervening To Stop Soldiers' Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberal politicians and a
legal expert today criticized President P.W. Botha for halting the
murder trial of six soldiers charged with the killing of an
activist in South-West Africa.
   Helen Suzman, Parliament member for the anti-apartheid
Progressive Federal Party, noted that Botha's action came a week
after he refused to intervene to spare ``the Sharpeville Six'' _ a
group of blacks sentenced to hang for complicity in a 1984 mob
killing of a black town councilor.
   Despite an international clemency campaign, Botha said his
policy was to avoid interfering with the judicial process. Last
Thursday, after Botha's pronouncement, a judge granted a one-month
stay of execution to the six in order to consider claims that a
state witness committed perjury.
   In light of Botha's refusal to intervene in the Sharpeville
case, Mrs. Suzman said she was ``astonished'' that the president
``did not allow the ordinary course of justice to be followed'' in
the case of the soldiers in South-West Africa.
   Botha ordered the attorney general of the territory, commonly
known as Namibia, to halt prosecution under the Defense Act, which
exempts security forces members from court action if they act ``in
good faith'' in combating suspected terrorism.
   The six soldiers _ four officers and two enlisted men _ were
accused of arranging for 50 black soldiers to disguise themselves
in civilian clothes, arm themselves with spears and knives, and
disrupt a political rally in 1985.
   The rally was sponsored by the South-West African People's
Organization, which seeks independence from South Africa. SWAPO's
outlawed military wing has been waging a guerrilla war since 1966.
   The man fatally stabbed at the rally, Immanuel Shifidi, was a
SWAPO member.
   Dirk van Zyl Smit, a criminology professor at the University of
Cape Town, said Botha's intervention was the worst type of
executive interference because, unlike a pardon or reprieve, it
occurred before a judgment had been made.
   Dave Dalling, a Progressive Federal member of Parliament, said
Botha's action placed the army above the law and undermined public
confidence in the judiciary.
   In the Namibian capital, Windhoek, the local bar association
expressed ``shock and disbelief'' at Botha's action.
   The Labor Party, which represents most of the territory's
mixed-race people, said Botha's ``arbitrary decision ... may give
rise to further public violence, bloodshed and chaos.''
</TEXT>
