<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dial-A-Quaker     03-23 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dial-A-Quaker,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quakers Use Telemarketing To Reach Prospective New Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Telemarketing, a sales strategy usually
associated with business, is gaining popularity in the Religious
Society of Friends, a group not known for evangelism.
   In Kernersville, a handful of Quakers with telephones, address
lists and friendly voices hope to gather a new weekly meeting.
   On Tuesday night, they gathered at the former site of Spruce
Pines Friends Meeting, a dwindling church that finally closed in
November. Quakers from Winston-Salem, Kernersville, Archdale and
Charlotte dial nightly in a four-week campaign that has yielded
more than 200 requests for information since Sunday.
   ``Hi. This is Archie Creed with the new North View Friends
Church that will be opening off Piney Grove Road in May,'' said the
church's pastor in a call to a prospective member.
   Creed first asks if the person is actively involved in a local
church. If they say yes, he thanks them for their time. If they say
no, Creed asks if the church can mail them a brochure.
   Each call is ranked according to the person's response: fair,
good, very good, excellent. ``First one tonight!'' exclaimed Ethel
Holmes, a volunteer from Kernersville, after she marked one
response ``excellent.''
   ``Most of them are receptive, even if they attend another
church,'' she said. ``I have had no hangups.''
   Holmes is sold on this unconventional method of evangelism.
   ``People do not respond to door-knocking real well,'' she
explained. But they usually don't mind a phone call, she said.
   The goal is 25,000 calls, which Creed hopes will produce a
mailing list of 2,500 names.
   He expects more than 200 people at the church's first official
service May 15.
   Steve Wood, pastor of Battle Forest Friends Church in northwest
Greensboro, is also sold on telemarketing.
   His congregation recently completed an 8,000-call campaign. On
Sunday, the 85-member congregation will celebrate its telephonic
fruits at a service for new members.
   Wood, a part-time real estate agent, got the idea from
telemarketing advertisements in real estate magazines. If it works
for business, he thought, why not use it in the church?
   Door-to-door visitation was out because it takes too much time
for too few results, Wood said.
   So far, telemarketing by Quakers has been very successful, says
Billy Britt, superintendent of the N.C. Friends Yearly Meeting. In
Southern California, such campaigns produced seven new churches, he
said.
   About one percent of those called end up joining the church,
which means Battle Forest can expect to add about 60 people to its
rolls.
   If other Quakers object to the technique, they haven't told him
about it.
   ``There has been no opposition to it,'' Britt said. ``It is
aimed at the unchurched. There's no high pressure.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
