<HEAD>Earthquake Jolts People Awake In Santa Barbara</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal residents were jolted awake
by a moderate earthquake and aftershock today, prompting worried
calls to police and radio stations, but there were no reports of
injury or damage.
   The first shock, measuring 3.9 on the Richter Scale, hit at
12:42 a.m. and was centered 11 miles southeast of downtown Santa
Barbara, said Robert Finn, spokesman for the seismology lab at the
California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
   ``At 12:57 there was an aftershock in the same location with a
2.7 magnitude,'' Finn said. ``These quakes weren't strong enough to
do much damage, but a lot of people felt them.''
   About 30 shaken sleepers telephoned Santa Barbara County
sheriff's headquarters to confirm what they felt, said Deputy Larry
Ralston.
   ``They were just concerned and curious, or like one who wanted
to know if he had been dreaming,'' Ralston said.
   The early morning quake was centered about 75 miles northwest of
downtown Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
