<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maria DeSillers Finds More Donations, Ordered To Turn Them Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered Maria DeSillers to turn over
additional donations that she recently told officials she had
received for her late son's liver transplants.
   All undeposited contributions must be listed and handed over to
a court-appointed curator today, Dade Circuit Judge Francis J.
Christie said Tuesday.
   Curator Karen Gievers requested the order after Ms. DeSillers
said Friday that she had found a ``substantial amount'' of unopened
mail last November in warehouse where she stored furniture and
other possessions.
   The carton of mail included checks and cash donated for
DeSillers' 7-year-old son, Ronnie, who died April 29 at Children's
Hospital of Pittsburgh while awaiting his fourth liver transplant.
   When Ronnie's need for a liver transplant was publicized last
year, donations were received from well-wishers throughout the
country, including $1,000 from President Reagan.
   An audit by the Florida Secretary of State found that Ms.
DeSillers received almost $1 million in donations, of which about
$175,000 could not be accounted for.
   Ms. DeSillers' lawyer said Tuesday that for four months his
client didn't deposit the newly found donations, which he said
totaled only a few hundred dollars.
   ``She has kept everything segregated and stapled together,''
attorney Harry Robbins said. ``She figured if she made any more
deposits it wasn't going to look good.''
   The state has charged Ms. DeSillers with using donations for her
personal expenses and failing to register Ronnie's fund as a
charity. Ms. DeSillers, who faces a maximum $1,000 fine, will
contest the charges at a May 10 hearing.
   State investigators say Ms. DeSillers withdrew at least $47,000
in donations to buy jewelry, clothing and furniture, pay rent on
her Miami bayfront apartment and return $5,000 loaned to her by a
former boyfriend.
   Last fall, Children's Hospital sued Ms. DeSillers after she
refused to pay $262,000 of the $424,300 bill that remained from her
son's transplants. Ms. DeSillers claimed the boy received poor
care, which hospital officials deny.
   Meanwhile, the Dade County State Attorney's Office is continuing
a criminal investigation into whether Ms. DeSillers committed fraud
or theft by using some of the donations for her expenses.
   Earlier this month, Christie froze the boy's estate and
appointed Ms. Gievers to oversee the $239,287 that remained in the
child's bank account.
   When Ms. Gievers learned of the undeposited funds last week, she
requested that the money be turned over to her immediately. By
Tuesday, when she had not received the money, she filed the
petition in the Dade court.
   The money will be deposited in a restricted, interest-bearing
account until the court rules how the remaining funds will be
distributed, Ms. Gievers said.
   Robbins has said his client did not misuse any of the donations
and that she is entitled to the estate because she is the boy's
natural heir.
</TEXT>
