<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Bishop,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Calls On Catholics To Quit IRA</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Irish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic bishop whose
diocese includes the IRA stronghold of Catholic west Belfast said
today the outlawed guerrilla organization is ``sheer evil.''
   ``The IRA poses a very grave spiritual danger to the Catholic
community and we must realize that and have no illusions about
it,'' said Bishop Cahal Daly in an interview with Radio Ulster, the
British Broadcasting Corp.'s local Northern Ireland station.
   ``This is a question of sheer evil and we have got to face that
evil and have no truck with it,'' he declared.
   Daly is bishop of Down and Connor. The diocese includes west
Belfast where two British soldiers were killed Saturday when they
drove up to the funeral cortege for Irish Republican Army guerrilla
Kevin Brady.
   In scenes that shocked television audiences around the world,
members of the Catholic crowd in the funeral cortege for Brady
dragged the soldiers from the car, stripped them naked and beat
them unconscious with iron bars before IRA gunmen shot them dead.
   Daly in a statement Tuesday declared: ``IRA violence is often
disguised with a mask of romantic rhetoric and militaristic mock
ritual. For a ghastly half-hour on Saturday, the mask slipped. The
real face of IRA violence was shown and it was horrible to see.''
   He said the crowd Saturday had a right to fear that they were
going to be attacked. The previous Wednesday a Protestant extremist
killed three people and wounded 68 in an attack on an IRA funeral.
   ``But let us not be deceived. This was not a momentary lapse
from high IRA principles and standards. People would not have taken
iron bars in their hands to batter soldiers into unconsciousness if
they had not taken hatred into their hearts,'' he said in Tuesday's
statement.
   Daly pleaded with those who joined the IRA ``for idealistic
reasons and out of sense of justice'' to quit the organization.
   ``For God's sake, for Ireland's sake, let them leave the
organization now before still more grievous harm is done,'' he said.
   Sean Kenny, a Sinn Fein member of Belfast City Council,
dismissed the statement, saying the bishop was an apologist for the
British security forces. Sinn Fein is the IRA's legal political arm.
   Brady was one of three people killed in a gun and grenade attack
at the March 16 funeral at Milltown cemetery of three unarmed IRA
guerrillas killed by British troops in Gibraltar.
   Protestant Michael Stone was charged Tuesday with three counts
of murder in connection with the cemetery deaths and with murdering
three other Catholics in sniper attacks.
   The predominantly Catholic IRA is fighting to unite Northern
Ireland with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
