<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-MIAs     03-23 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-MIAs,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Criticized Over Holding U.S. War Remains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Command today rebuked
communist North Korea for refusing to return the remains of U.S.
soldiers killed during the Korean War, officials said.
   The U.N. Command called for return of the remains at a meeting
with North Korean military officials at the Panmunjom truce site.
U.N. officials accused North Korea of aggravating tension on the
Korean peninsula.
   ``This irrational and inhumane action by your side on this issue
is totally unacceptable and will be denounced by all fair-minded
people and the community of civilized nations worldwide,'' said
U.S. Army Col. Charles Coffman, according to a U.N. statement.
   North Korea refused to return the remains of two U.S. soldiers
who died during the Korean War after the United States imposed
sanctions against the country in January for its alleged bombing of
a South Korean commercial jetliner.
   The United States, South Korea and other nations have accused
North Korea of bombing the airliner, killing all 115 people aboard,
last Nov. 29. North Korea has denied involvement.
   A woman who flew on an early part of the flight confessed in
January to being a North Korean agent and said she planted a bomb
on the Korean Air jet to disrupt the 1988 Olympic Games in Seoul.
   The two Americans whose remains are being sought by the U.S.
have been identified as 1st Lt. Jack J. Saunders of Utah and Cpl.
Arthur I. Seaton of Pennsylvania. They reportedly died in North
Korean prison camps in 1951.
   Coffman, acting as secretary of the U.N. Command, complained
that North Korea was trying to stir up tension on the Korean
peninsula.
   He also objected to repeated North Korean charges that military
exercises being held by U.S. and South Korean forces under the name
``Team Spirit'' were a prelude to a nuclear attack on the north.
   ``Your repetition of charges, and your repeat of your annual
litany of false allegations against Team Spirit _ filled with
abusive language, unfounded and irrelevant allegations _ obviously
satisifed your propaganda purposes,'' he said.
   About 200,000 U.S. and South Korean troops are taking part in
the annual exercises between now and April. The United States keeps
40,000 troops in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   The U.N. Command meets periodically with North Korean and
Chinese representatives for meetings of the Military Armistice
Commission to supervise disputes and violations of the cease-fire
that ended the Korean War in 1953.
   The war began in 1950 after North Korean forces invaded the
south and troops from the United States and other nations came to
the assistance of the south.
</TEXT>
