<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MonetReward     03-23 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Monet Reward,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thanks, But No Reward for Monet Finder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LeGRAND, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The postmaster who found a stolen Claude
Monet painting worth $175,000 will get a pat on the back, but he
won't collect the $17,500 reward because he was simply doing his
job.
   Steve Reutter, spokesman for the St. Paul Fire & Marine
Insurance Co., which paid a $175,000 claim after the theft, said
postal rules prevent Charles Polley and other employees from
collecting rewards ``for things done in the line of duty.
   ``We asked them and that's what they said,'' Reutter said.
   ``I really didn't expect it,'' said Polley. ``You are here on a
payroll and that's the way it is.''
   Reutter said the company will make a ``good will'' offering to a
charity in Marshalltown in Polley's name. The amount and charity
haven't been decided, he said.
   The painting, ``Fishing Boats Under the Cliffs of Etretat,'' was
stolen from the Fisher Community Center March 19, 1987 and was
recovered this month when Polley found it in a mail drop box in
LeGrand, which is near Marshalltown.
   Polley said he has a metal detector and goes hunting for buried
treasures now and then, but the Monet discovery tops his list.
``I've found the gold ring,'' he said. ``That was the most valuable
thing I've ever found.''
   Art experts say the painting is damaged but restorable. The
Fisher Foundation, which operates the center, will keep the
insurance money to build a new gallery. The insurers have said
they'll probably auction the painting.
</TEXT>
