<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Harold'sNewStart 1stLd-Writethru a0527 03-23 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harold's New Start, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Man, Once Homeless, Is Back From New Mexico, Looking For
Work</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, ``For nine months xxx, to fix Thomas' age to
34, sted 35</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Thomas spent harsh winter days in an open
shack, then took a job in New Mexico when a couple offered to
improve his life. Now he's back home looking for more work, and he
might write a book.
   The former homeless man returned to Chicago late Tuesday after
working for two months as a handyman. He said he appreciated the
chance to ``see a lot of America'' but the job given by Roy and
Ethel Gilman didn't provide steady wages.
   ``The Gilmans are fine people, but they didn't want to pay me,''
said Thomas, weary after riding a bus from Portales, N.M., a small
farming community.
   He said he lived in a trailer and worked six days a week, fixing
cars, erecting fences and other farm chores.
   ``But a man can't live on room and board alone. I want to start
a family, maybe get married,'' Thomas said.
   For nine months, Thomas, 34, lived in a shack just west of
downtown Chicago. The Gilmans read an Associated Press account of
his plight and offered him a job in mid-January.
   The Gilmans paid Thomas room and board and deposited $300 in
wages for him in a Portales bank about a month ago. On Monday,
Thomas withdrew the money and boarded a bus for Chicago.
   He said the money was put into an account after media reports
indicated he wasn't receiving a regular salary.
   ``I thought I'd get some wages,'' Thomas said. ``They treated me
very nice. They're nice, church-going people, but no wages.
   ``I didn't have a lot of time for things myself. When a fellow
turns and sees everything negative, what's a guy to do?'' he said.
   Thomas, wearing the clothes he received from well-wishers when
he left Chicago on Jan. 15, said he would be living with a
girlfriend at a public housing project on the North Side.
   ``I don't have a job, not right off,'' he said. ``But I've got a
few ideas of my own. I'm going to be looking. I've got a few
dollars in my pocket to last me awhile.
   ``I'm thinking about writing a book. A lot of people look down
on the homeless. I just want everyone to know people on the street
aren't junk.''
   Mrs. Gilman, 68, said Thomas was treated as well as ``our own
family.''
   She said past news reports about wages may have contributed to
Thomas' departure.
   Mrs. Gilman said people who read those stories had ``been
calling us from everywhere saying we've been trying to make a slave
out of Harold. All we did was try to help him.''
   Thomas said he hasn't forgotten his homeless friends, many of
whom seek shelter in the wooden shack he built last year along the
Chicago River.
   ``I've got to see my friends,'' he said before hopping in a cab.
``We've got a lot to talk about.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0931EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Mitterrand 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 03-23 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Mitterrand, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Has Had Wide Swings in Popularity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0567 to make keyword line conform; rewrites
throughout to recast and incorporate additional background. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand said he will seek
re-election because he can rise above France's fractious politics
and keep the country together.
   The 71-year-old Socialist announced on nationwide television
Tuesday that he will seek re-election next month. Prior to his
announcement, opinion polls put him in the lead.
   Mitterrand told a TV interviewer he decided to run because he
thinks disunity threatens ``to tear the social fabric'' of France.
   ``I saw a risk that the country might fall again into the
quarrels and divisions that have hampered it so often. I want
France to be united ... not be taken in hand by the spirit of
intolerance, by parties who want everything, by clans, by
cliques,'' he said.
   After Mitterrand declared, Michel Rocard, until now the
Socialist Party's only candidate, withdrew and gave his full
support to the incumbent. The main conservative candidates are
Premier Jacques Chirac and former Premier Raymond Barre.
   The first round of the elections is to be held April 24 with a
run-off between the top two candidates scheduled for May 8.
   Mitterrand led the leftist surge in May 1981 that ousted
President Valery Giscard d'Estaing and the center-right alliance
that had controlled the National Assembly for 23 years.
   The victory avenged Mitterrand's defeats in the presidential
elections of 1965 by Charles de Gaulle and 1974 by Giscard
d'Estaing.
   But France's love affair with the Socialists was short-lived.
   After five years, French voters in the March 1986 parliamentary
elections returned control to the right _ creating what became
known in France as ``cohabitation'' between a Socialist president
and a conservative premier.
   Socialist policies had dragged Mitterrand's popularity rating in
public opinion polls as low as 27 percent, but under the unwanted
marriage with the conservatives it soared again to a consistent 55
percent or more.
   That gave Mitterrand the dubious honor of being, in one
seven-year term, both the least and most popular chief executive in
the 30 years of the Fifth Republic.
   In the beginning of his administration, Mitterrand pursued
costly social programs after the Socialists gained power. Then he
reversed course, instituting austerity measures.
   Economic troubles brought his party to power, and caused its
downfall five years later. After the Socialist defeat, Mitterrand
eased into the role of elder statesman and held himself above the
day-to-day battles of governing, commenting on issues only
occasionally.
   The French called him ``Tonton,'' or uncle.
   Mitterrand was born Oct. 26, 1916, in Jarnac and attended
universities in Paris, earning degrees in law and letters. He was
drafted into the army in 1938, and shot and captured during the
German invasion in 1940.
   Mitterrand escaped from a prison camp in Germany, returned to
France and created a Resistance network. His feud with de Gaulle
began when Mitterrand refused to unite his Resistance group with de
Gaulle's.
   It was in the Resistance days that he met Danielle Gouze, and
they married in 1944, soon after France was liberated. He held
several government posts, including interior and justice minister.
   In the early 1970s he built the moribund Socialist Party into a
major political force, but the Union of the Left he formed with the
Communists fell apart in 1977.
   Not until the final days of the 1981 campaign did the two main
leftist parties join forces again to defeat Giscard and oust the
conservatives.
   Mitterrand shocked much of the West by bringing Communists into
his government, but the union lasted only three years. In 1984, the
Communists pulled out in a dispute over economic policy.
</TEXT>
