<DOCNO> AP880323-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0946EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Women-Broadcast     03-23 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Women-Broadcast,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`A Year in the Life' Among Broadcast Award Winners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``A Year in the Life'' and the ABC Afterschool
Special ``Supermom's Daughter'' were among 19 programs honored by
the American Women in Radio and Television for realistically
depicting the roles of women today.
   ``We're raising the sensibilities of producers'' by honoring
programs that wrestle with ``people, issues and relationships,''
said Marlene Belles, controller of KTVU-TV in San Francisco and
president of the women's broadcasting organization.
   ``People still want to be entertained. But the shoot-em-ups are
not nearly as popular,'' she said at the awards ceremony Tuesday.
   Modernizing the role of women on television is difficult because
the number of women in top broadcast management remains
``minuscule,'' Ms. Belles said.
   ``There is still discrimination. It's just more subtle now,''
she said. ``The old boys still run the networks. It's probably
going to get worse before it gets better.''
   ``Today Show'' co-anchor Jane Pauley and Sally Jessy Raphael,
the first nationally syndicated female talk show host, were among
the presenters during the awards luncheon at the Waldorf-Astoria
Hotel.
   Winners were selected from a field of 344 television, cable and
radio programs.
   Universal Studios' ``A Year in the Life'' captured the
television entertainment category for depicting a successful
professional woman who refuses to accept traditional views about
marriage.
   The children's programming winner, ``Supermom's Daughter,''
portrayed a gifted science student torn between fulfilling her own
dreams or satisfying the wishes of her career-oriented mother.
   KUOM Radio at the University of Minnesota was honored for a
documentary in which battered women discussed their plight. WGBH
Radio in Boston won the entertainment category for its story of
American composer Ruth Crawford Seeger.
   Other radio winners were:
   _WTOP, Washington, D.C., ``Are Women Making it in America?''
   _WTSO, Madison, Wis., ``Invisible Voices: Women in the Dane
County Jail.''
   _Michigan Sampler, Kalamazoo, Mich., ``Michigan Pioneer Women.''
   _Solz Advertising, St. Louis, health-care commercial.
   _WINS, New York City, ``Topic: Rape.''
   Other television winners were:
   _WMAQ, Chicago, ``Sexism in City Hall.''
   _KNBC, Burbank, Calif., ``The Spirit of Southern California.''
   _Lifetime Cablevision, ``Generations _ Reflections on Women.''
   _McDonald Davis and Associates, Milwaukee, health-care
commercial.
   _WTBS, Atlanta, ``Between the Lines: National Women's Studies
Association.''
   _WWOR, Secaucus, N.J., ``Victims Fight Back.''
   _ABC News 20-20, ``Triumph Over Darkness.''
   _WMBD, Peoria, Ill., ``Farm Wife Financier.''
   _WJLA, Washington, D.C., ``Women of Love _ Women of Power.''
   _KTCA, St. Paul, Minn., ``Whisper Minnesota.''
</TEXT>
