<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gore 3rdLd-Writethru a0591 03-23 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gore, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0591,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede SAULT STE. MARIE</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to CORRECT total to $500 million sted of $50
million.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISHPEMING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Albert Gore Jr. today called on
the government to ``straighten out its economic policy'' to make
heavy industry more competitive worldwide.
   The Tennessee senator, campaigning in Michigan for a share of
the 138 delegates at stake in Saturday's caucuses, made his plea
during a tour of a giant iron ore processing plant in the state's
Upper Peninsula.
   Gore spoke informally with some of the 700 workers at the Tilden
mining company facility, and then noted the plant's reduced
production, which officials attributed to lowered demands.
   The candidate said the plant ``is competitive so long as the
competition is not unfairly subsidized.''
   ``We need to straighten out our economic policy and stop
borrowing $500 million every 24 hours so that we're competitive in
the world economy _ and we have to take steps to remove unfair
trade barriers overseas,'' he said.
   Gore donned a hard hat to tour the facility where iron ore is
minded and rendered into small pellets. He walked amid large,
whirling cylinders that grind and filter the iron and peered inside
a giant rotating kiln that bakes the final product.
   ``It's an amazing place, isn't it. It's like the inside of a
death star,'' Gore said in apparent reference to the ``Star Wars''
movie trilogy.
   Gore was seeking votes in the state's sparsely populated Upper
Peninsula for a second day today after attacking Vice President
George Bush and the Reagan administration before high school and
college audiences Tuesday.
   He was heading to Wisconsin later today to address the state
legislature in Madison. Aiming toward Wisconsin's April 5 primary,
Gore began airing television commercials there this week lashing
out at corporate greed.
   Gore said Bush represents the choice for voters to ``continue
what we're doing'' without change. Denouncing that choice, he cited
the Iran-Contra affair, U.S. support for Panama strongman Manuel
Noriega in the face of evidence of drug involvement until recently,
and what he said was a general feeling of economic pessimism among
America's youth.
   ``I think if we continue what we're doing now, continuing down
the same path, we're headed for trouble,'' he told high school
students who jammed an auditorium for an after-school rally in
Traverse City.
   He repeated those themes later in a speech to more than 1,000
students at Lake Superior State University in Sault Ste. Marie.
   He denounced Bush as lacking the ``gumption'' to disagree with
President Reagan's veto on the civil rights bill, which Congress
voted to override. Gore dropped plans to campaign in Wisconsin on
Tuesday so that he could return to Washington to vote to override
the veto.
   ``I was quite surprised that George Bush belatedly announced he
was in favor of the veto _ that surprised many people,'' Gore said.
``But of course he has not been willing to disagree with President
Reagan on anything.''
   Gore campaigned in northern Michigan as polls of the state's
Democrats, published by both Detroit newspapers, showed him
trailing far behind rivals Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis.
Democrat Richard Gephardt is also campaigning in Michigan, which is
a do-or-die state for his White House hopes.
   Facing those long odds, Gore has not waged an intensive Michigan
campaign and has aired radio but no television commercials. Much of
Gore's Michigan organization is based on the support of key state
legislators, including a legislative power from the northern
region, Dominic Jacobitti.
   Gore largely avoided mention of his Democratic rivals, however.
The closest he came was saying the country needs a president ``with
foreign policy experience'' _ something he has in the past charged
Dukakis with lacking.
   Gore appeared before an enthusiastic audience of college
students in Sault Ste. Marie and contended, ``I am the first
presidential candidate to campaign in Sault Ste. Marie since Teddy
Roosevelt.''
</TEXT>
