<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Unhealthy Flag,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Department Says Flag Flapping Is Too Noisy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Old Glory is a source of noise
pollution and has to come down at night, health officials say, but
Thomas ``Ski'' Demski calls that demand unpatriotic and has raised
another flag to say ``Don't Tread On Me.''
   Demski, 57, flies a large American flag from a 132-foot flagpole
outside his home day and night. But neighbors have been complaining
they can't sleep because of the flapping noise.
   Recent noise-meter measurements by city health officials found
the flag exceeded legal limits for residential areas. They ordered
Demski to take his flag down every night at 10 p.m.
   But despite his neighbors' objections and the city order, Demski
says he won't strike the colors. Instead, he hoisted the
Revolutionary War-era banner that reads ``Don't Tread On Me.''
   ``When they start picking on the flag, I'll go to jail over it
if necessary,'' said the bumper sticker manufacturer, who has
expressed interest in becoming mayor of Long Beach, 25 miles south
of downtown Los Angeles.
