<HEAD>PTL Lost Nearly $1 Million in February</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL lost nearly $1 million in February,
but the leader of the television ministry says he still hopes to
have more than $4 million to pay debts on May 2.
   David Clark said on the New PTL Club show Tuesday that he has
been trying to ``contain costs'' and to ``refocus this ministry on
the things of God.''
   In his February report to Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds, Clark
noted the auction scheduled April 12 of several parcels of land
owned by PTL, including the parsonage in Tega Cay where Jim and
Tammy Bakker lived before they were forced from the ministry. That
house is valued at $1 million.
   PTL is hoping to raise $4 million above expenses by May, when
the ministry will reorganize into non-profit and profit
corporations.
   Clark's report shows PTL revenues in February of $2.8 million
and expenses of $3.7 million. Net losses since last June 13 are
more than $4 million.
