<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1002EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0427 03-23 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0427,730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4th graf with Shultz comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A date for the next superpower summit and
progress on arms control and human rights appeared in the offing
today as Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze neared the
end of three days of talks here.
   His call on President Reagan at the White House was expected to
complete plans for a summit in late May in Moscow with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev at which the two sides hope to sign a
treaty slashing their arsenals of long-range nuclear weapons by 30
to 50 percent.
   ``The negotiations are going fairly well,'' Shevardnadze said
Tuesday night as he returned to the State Department for another
round of talks with Secretary of State George P. Shultz over a
buffet dinner of hot dogs, potato salad and popcorn. Arrangements
also were made to show the film ``That's Entertainment,'' a
retrospective of Hollywood musicals, during breaks in the
discussions.
   As they renewed their discussions this morning, Shultz told
reporters ``we did a fair amount'' of business even so. But, he
admitted, ``I`m not very big on popcorn.''
   The pair met for 6{ hours during the day and agreed their
session on arms control and human rights was ``businesslike,
straightforward, constructive and broad-ranging.''
   Evidently, it was not entirely harmonious, however. Charles E.
Redman, the State Department spokesman, said there were ``a few
laughs, a few arguments.'' He declined to provide any details.
   Shultz has been pressing the Soviets to relax their emigration
restrictions and liberalize cultural and religious practices. The
Soviets, on the other hand, have made an issue of the homeless
problem in the United States and what they describe as a poor civil
rights record.
   ``This time, it was a much more detailed discussion,'' Vadim
Perfilyev, the deputy Soviet foreign ministry spokesman, said. ``We
think that we have points where we have cooperation between our two
countries. and I think that now we have positive results. ... It is
much more of a two-way street.''
   During the day, Shultz and Shevardnadze also received brief
reports from U.S. and Soviet arms control experts. Discussion of
the conflicts in Afghanistan and Nicaragua _ wars in which the two
superpowers have armed rival forces _ was deferred until Wednesday.
   The arms control experts are trying to mesh U.S. and Soviet
drafts of treaty provisions to scrap 30 to 50 percent of the two
sides' long-range bombers, missiles and submarines and to devise
measures to ensure compliance with the accord.
   The treaty is the projected centerpiece of the summit meeting.
The treaty drafts also include data on the size and locations of
U.S. and Soviet long-range weapons.
   Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne L. Ridgway said Monday
there were ``blanks'' in the information the two sides had
exchanged. She said ``lots and lots'' of disagreements remain.
   Two veteran negotiators, Paul H. Nitze and Aleksei A. Obukhov,
headed the U.S. and Soviet expert groups. They were to report back
to Shultz and Shevardnadze on whether the differences narrowed.
   Reagan has said that if the treaty is not ready he might hold a
second meeting with Gorbachev later in the year to sign it.
   During a break in their talks, Shultz and Shevardnadze presided
Tuesday at the opening of a new communications center designed to
reduce the risk of nuclear war. Matching centers in Washington and
Moscow will be linked by satellite.
   The facility ``will help us to remove misunderstandings, and it
will help us to reduce the risk of any outbreaks of hostilities
between us,'' Shultz said.
   Shevardnadze said he hoped ``one day, when we will have done
away with any offensive arms, such centers will be used for more
humane purposes.''
   In contrast to that cooperative step, the two sides are in
conflict over Central America and Afghanistan.
   In a brief exchange with reporters, Shevardnadze backed away
from an earlier Soviet pledge to withdraw the Red Army from
Afghanistan even if negotiators fail to agree on conditions for
ending the war there.
   Arriving for his talks with Shultz, he declined to repeat the
pledge made by a Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman last week in
Moscow after negotiations deadlocked in Geneva.
   ``I don't know when he said that,'' Shevardnadze said in
Russian. ``We shall see. It is better to have the document signed
in Geneva. This is the better possibility.''
</TEXT>
