<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1029EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-LawProtest     03-23 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Law Protest,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Sit In, Boycott for More Diverse Faculty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sit-in at the University of
California's Boalt Hall law school to protest the lack of women and
minority tenured faculty members ended in the arrest of 28 law
students.
   The students occupied Dean Jesse Choper's office for most of the
day Tuesday and called for an open faculty meeting to discuss the
issue, but the dean told them he had no authority to call a
meeting, Boalt spokeswoman Greta Goldenman said.
   The 28 students were cited and released Tuesday evening after
being taken into custody by campus police for investigation of
trespassing.
   White males occupy 91 percent of Boalt's 43.5 tenured faculty
positions, a percentage exceeded only by the University of Chicago
among the nation's top 10 law schools, said the Coalition for a
Diversified Faculty, which organized the protest.
   Associate Dean Jan Vetter said Boalt has one black and two women
in tenured faculty positions, a woman in a half-time tenured law
Ph.D. program, and several other women and minorities in
non-tenured acting professor posts.
   Choper said the law school has been making its best effort to
find women and minority candidates for tenure but competition for
the ``small pool'' is fierce.
   Students also organized a class boycott, but there were
conflicting reports on how successful it was. Protest group members
said they would continue to press for a meeting with faculty.
</TEXT>
