<2ND_LINE>PM-Shooting Death,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Mistakes Granddaughter's Boyfriend For Burglar, Fatally
Shoots Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 75-year-old woman says she thought there was
a burglar in her home when she shot and killed her granddaughter's
boyfriend.
   ``This was a tragedy, and it will be with me the rest of my
life,'' said Ella Willis. ``If I could blow the breath of life back
in him like God, I'd do it.''
   Assistant St. Louis Circuit Attorney Dan Lesseg said Willis
would not be charged in the shooting Monday night.
   Juan T. Gaston, 25, of St. Louis, was fatally shot on the
second-story porch of Willis' midtown home, said Sgt. Gerald Brown
of the police homicide division.
   Gaston was the boyfriend of Willis' 22-year-old granddaughter,
who lives with Willis, Brown said.
   He said Willis had heard a noise at the back of her home late
Monday and went upstairs to investigate. When Gaston kicked open
the door into the house from the porch, Willis shot him with her
.38-caliber revolver, Brown said.
   ``He lunged at me, and I shot him right between the eyes,''
Willis said. ``I just let him have it.''
   Willis' granddaughter, Monica Hendrix, said that she and Gaston
had argued earlier in the day over a small amount of money. She
said she did not have any bitter feelings toward her grandmother.
   ``She couldn't help it,'' Hendrix said. ``When we heard somebody
breaking in, I thought it might be Juan, and I called and called
and asked who it was.
   ``There was no answer. If he had answered, he wouldn't be dead
right now.''
   Brown said Gaston apparently had come up the back stairs to the
house, then climbed over a wall and dropped into the enclosed porch.
   Brown said Willis told police that Gaston usually came to the
front door when he visited and that she did not know why he had
tried to enter the house through the back without identifying
himself.
</TEXT>
