<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Medicaid     03-23 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Medicaid,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Dismisses Medicaid Dispute Between Administration and
California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today dismissed a Medicaid
dispute between the Reagan administration and California that the
justices had been studying for over a year.
   The court said recent action by Congress has made the case
legally irrelevant.
   Federal authorities had sought to limit state power to ease
eligibilty for Medicaid, a combined federal and state program of
medical assistance to the needy.
   The California Legislature decided in 1983 that aged and
disabled Medicaid recipients were unable to afford necessary
medical care as well as other necessities under the program's
existing income standards.
   So the legislature increased from $544 to $709 the income adult
couples may keep each month for non-medical needs and still qualify
for Medicaid.
   Federal authorities had said the amount was illegally high.
   In an unsigned opinion today, the high court noted that a law
recently enacted by Congress ``required the secretary (of Health
and Human Services) to approve the proposed California amendment,
retroactively to the date of its proposal.''
   The court also noted that lawyers for California and the
administration ``agree that these developments have rendered the
controversy moot.''
   The case is Bowen vs. Kizer, 86-863.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
