<1ST_LINE>u p PM-DemocratsAbroad     03-23 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats Abroad,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Abroad Vote in Expatriate Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats living overseas picked a largely
uncommitted delegation to attend the party's national covention
this summer, although Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the
winner of a non-binding poll, picked up a fraction of a convention
vote.
   In balloting on Tuesday, the Democrats abroad elected 10
delegates, each of whom will cast one-half vote at the national
convention. Nine of those delegates have declared themselves
uncommitted, while one is pledged to Dukakis.
   Another four delegates, each of whom will cast one-half vote,
will be picked later at a meeting in Paris, and under party rules
they initially would be uncommitted.
   ``Of course we have an impact, particularly if we're
uncommitted,'' Sally McNulty, chairwoman of the Democratic Party
Committee Abroad, said Tuesday as organizers around her began
readying stacks of air mail envelopes for counting. ``We could tip
the ballot.''
   Of the 2,385 expatriate Americans voting in the non-binding part
of the ballot, cast mostly by mail, Dukakis got 990 votes, or 41.5
percent and Jackson 347 votes or 14.5 percent, according to
Democrats abroad, the official organizers of the poll.
   In third place was Andrew Sundberg, a businessman living in
Geneva, Switzerland, who campaigns for expatriate benefits. He got
304 votes, or 12.7 percent.
   Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois was fourth with 248 votes, or 10.4
percent, and New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, who is not a candidate,
finished fifth with 171 votes, or 7.2 percent.
   It was the fourth primary for expatriate Democrats, who select
seven national convention delegates. Two other delegates are party
officials.
   The primary gives Democrats worldwide the chance to vote by mail
or in person for convention delegates.
   A slow trickle of voters turned out through the morning Tuesday
at the Queen Elizabeth II Conference Center, around the corner from
the Houses of Parliament. But party officials were not concerned.
   ``Our members would have voted already by post,'' said Ms.
McNulty, who estimated that 2 million to 3 million Americans live
abroad.
   Any Democrat abroad was eligible to mail a ballot to the
primary. Officials believed the majority would come from the 18
countries with Democrats Abroad organizations and large American
populations, including Israel, France and Canada.
   For the first time, ballots were available at embassies and
consulates worldwide.
   Republicans abroad have a similar organization but they do not
hold primaries.
</TEXT>
