<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Farms     03-23 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Farms,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Promotes Cooperatives in Speech to Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev today called
for a transformation of the country's inefficient agricultural
system led by farms owned by farmers, not by the state.
   Gorbachev, in an address to a national congress of collective
farmers at the Kremlin, said the possibilities of cooperatives were
a ``brilliant discovery'' of Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin that
have been underused by subsequent Soviet leaders.
   ``We should revive co-ops not in their old, often too primitive
forms, but in the form of a modern, high-standard cooperative
movement,'' Gorbachev said.
   Collective farms, where members jointly own farm buildings and
machinery and share in earnings, have faded in importance in recent
years in favor of state farms, where farmers, like employees in a
factory, receive a basic wage.
   There were 33,000 collective farms in the Soviet Union in 1970,
but their number dropped to 26,300 by 1986. In that same period,
the number of collective farmers dropped from 16.7 million to 12.6
million.
   Gorbachev has been striving to persuade Soviets to enter into
cooperative ventures to make up for shortages in the state-run
economy. Since reforms instituted last year, nearly 14,000
cooperatives have sprung up to offer restaurant services, pump gas,
make clothes and provide other goods and services in short supply.
   A draft of a new law on cooperatives published earlier this
month in the Soviet press specifically prohibits government
interference in their affairs but also forsees a progressive tax
system to catch what Gorbachev has called ``money-grabbing.''
   Gorbachev, in remarks at the farmers congress summarized by
Tass, said the new law aims to ``ensure the enhancement and
development of cooperative and collective-farm property (and)
create legal machinery to protect cooperative democracy.''
   The summary of Gorbachev's speech distributed by the official
Soviet news agency did not give any indication whether Gorbachev
would move give land to individual farmers.
   Tass said the cooperative law would be a main item of discussion
at the three-day session of collective farmers. It is the first
such conference since 1969.
   According to Tass, Gorbachev said it was the cooperative
movement that ``helped in many ways to overcome hunger and economic
dislocation in the aftermath of the civil war, mend the financial
and monetary systems, and get people more closely involved with the
building of a new life.''
   Gorbachev said his re-emphasis on cooperatives is a result of
greater democracy in Soviet society and ``an important lever for
furthering the democratic process and combatting administration by
fiat and red tape.''
   Soviet agriculture has been plagued by central planners who tell
farms what and how much to plant, lack of incentives for farmers to
work the state-owned land, inefficient production, and poor storage
and transportation facilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0110 </DOCNO>
