<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0593,0767</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Abandon Policy Of Not Policing IRA Funerals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 10th graf, `Security forces ...,' to
UPDATE with details from services. PICKS up 11th graf, `On Tuesday
...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police announced today they
were abandoning a policy of staying away from IRA funerals because
five people, including two British soldiers, were killed during
funerals last week.
   Protestant activists had demanded that police reinstitute the
policy of clamping tight security on IRA funerals.
   Describing the IRA threat as ``deadly,'' a police statement
indicated security chiefs will order heavy police and troop
presence at future IRA funerals.
   ``Experience has shown that maintenance of the law and
prevention of outrages will only be guaranteed through the firm
presence of the police and army,'' a statement from the Royal
Ulster Constabulary headquarters said.
   The statement marked the swift collapse of a policy introduced
under pressure from moderate Roman Catholic leaders in the hope of
avoiding clashes.
   At the first unpoliced IRA funeral March 16, a Protestant
guerrilla launched a firearms and grenade attack from behind a
tombstone in the Catholic Milltown cemetery, killing three people
and wounded 68.
   At the IRA funeral Saturday for one Milltown victim, two British
soldiers drove up to the funeral cortege in an unmarked car were
brutally slain.
   In Britain, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher joined grieving
relatives at Northolt air base north of London where the bodies of
the soldiers, identified as signals corpsmen, were brought home.
   Services for Derek Wood, 24, and David Howes, 23, of the Royal
Corps of Signals, were scheduled for today in Belfast, Ballynahinch
and Lisburn, where they were based.
   Security forces continued to search Catholic areas of west
Belfast for their killers. Police sources said investigators were
looking for as many as 30 suspects.
   At Northolt, Mrs. Thatcher glanced around anxiously while the
sister of one of the men sobbed as the Royal Corps of Signal band
played Chopin's ``Funeral March'' and a bearer carried the
flag-draped coffins to hearses.
   In Belfast, some 25,000 people, mainly Protestants, gathered
this afternoon at the Cenotaph outside the city hall for a memorial
service to the slain soldiers.
   British and Republic of Ireland government ministers said they
will hold a special meeting in London on Friday to discuss tougher
security because of the latest outburst of violence in Northern
Ireland.
   The meeting was called under an Anglo-Irish agreement which
gives the Catholic republic an advisory say in Britain's running of
the Protestant-dominated province.
   On Tuesday, a Protestant guerrilla said he killed three people
at the IRA burial in Milltown because he wanted to avenge IRA
attacks aimed at Mrs. Thatcher and others, prosecutors said.
   The guerrilla, Michael Stone, 33, was charged with murdering
three people in the attack on the March 16 funeral of three IRA
guerrillas killed by British soldiers in Gibraltar. Stone also was
charged with killing three other Roman Catholics in sniper attacks
dating back to 1984.
   None of earlier victims _ a milkman, a bread delivery man and a
carpenter _ had any known links to the IRA.
   Stone was ordered to remain in custody until April 8, when he is
next due in court. A trial date has not yet been set.
   Flanked by heavy security in Belfast Magistrates Court on
Tuesday, Stone remained silent while a police superintendent read a
statement he had made about the Milltown attack.
   ``I alone carried out this military operation as a retaliatory
strike against Provisional Sinn Fein, the IRA, in response to the
slaughter of innocents at La Mon, Darkley, Brighton and
Enniskillen,'' Stone told police.
   ``I would state I am a dedicated free-lance Loyalist
(Protestant) paramilitary. No surrender.''
   The four attacks Stone cited in his statement span nearly 10
years from 1978 to 1987 and claimed the lives of 35 people. Mrs.
Thatcher escaped injury in the October 1984 Brighton attack.
   In Belfast, a senior bishop whose diocese includes the tense
Catholic ghetto of west Belfast, denounced the IRA as ``sheer
evil.'' It was one of the strongest attacks yet by Catholic
prelates, who regularly condemn the mainly Catholic guerrilla
organization.
   Bishop Cahal Daly said the IRA posed a ``grave spritual danger
to the Catholic community.''
   The mainly Catholic Irish Republican Army wants to end British
rule in Northern Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant
province with the overwhelmingly Catholic Republic of Ireland under
socialist rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
