<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1125EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Wiesel-Lecture     03-23 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wiesel-Lecture,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nobel Laureate Cancels Appearance after Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARQUETTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel, a Nazi death
camp survivor who lectures on the Holocaust, canceled an appearance
here after learning his fee would come from a grant by a
conservative publisher once accused of being an agent of South
Africa.
   Wiesel had been scheduled as a speaker today at the John McGoff
Distinguished Lecture Series at Northern Michigan University.
   But McGoff's reported links to the South African government and
the university's plans to pay Wiesel's fee from a $300,000 grant
from McGoff brought protests from the school's faculty.
   ``When it comes to apartheid you cannot make compromises,''
Wiesel said in explaining his decision.
   Philosophy professor James Green, who led the protests, said
Wiesel said he would have declined to appear had he known McGoff's
money was being used to pay for his appearance.
   McGoff, former chairman of the Northern Michigan University
board of control, was accused by the Securities and Exchange
Commission of illegally using South African money to try to buy
U.S. newspapers and lobby on behalf of the South African government.
   McGoff has denied acting as an agent for the South African
government and the charges were dismissed.
   McGoff, whose telephone number in Williamston is unlisted, could
not be reached for comment today.
   Green said the university faculty voted to disassociate itself
from the McGoff lecture series. Friday, the faculty voted 82-62
against using $3,000 from faculty funds to finance Wiesel's talk.
   Green said faculty members asked the university for assurances
that none of the McGoff money to be used for Wiesel's lecture came
from South Africa, but the university never provided such an
assurance.
   Jim Carter, news director at the university, said today the
university received word late Tuesday from the Harry Walker Agency
in New York City that Wiesel's appearance had been canceled.
   ``We are making no further statement to that effect,'' Carter
said, declining to answer questions about how the cancellation came
about.
   Wiesel said some faculty members had urged him to use the
lecture as a forum to denounce apartheid, which by law and custom
establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million
blacks have no vote in national affairs.
   The 5 million South African whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   ``When it comes to mass humiliation, a compromise is already
playing the other side's game. And what is apartheid but collective
humiliation; furhtermore, it is legal humiliation,'' said Wiesel.
``In South Africa, humiliation is the law of the land.''
</TEXT>
