<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTreaty 1stLd-Writethru a0488 03-23 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,830</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 10 grafs new to update with meeting today; picks up 5th
graf pvs, When the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee today
defeated the first attempt by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., to change
the U.S.-Soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear missiles.
   The Democratic-controlled panel voted 12-3 against Helms'
amendment, which would allow non-nuclear U.S. cruise missiles to be
deployed in Europe.
   The pact signed Dec. 8 by President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev bans missiles of ranges from 300 to 3,400
miles. The prohibition includes cruise missiles, both
nuclear-tipped and those armed with non-nuclear weapons.
   The ban covers both types of missiles because ``there's no way
to verify the distinction between'' the two, said Sen. Alan
Cranston, D-Calif.
   But Helms said the ban means ``the conventional imbalance in
Europe will be even greater than it is now'' because NATO will lose
a major weapon in the cruise missile.
   Cranston responded that the Pentagon has no plans to build
non-nuclear cruise missiles.
   The vote came on the first of 43 pending amendments or
reservations, either to the treaty text or the resolution by which
the Senate would register its approval of the pact.
   Of those amendments, 36 were proposed by Helms, the committee's
ranking Republican and the chief opponent of the treaty. Three more
were offered by Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., who has also been
critical of the pact.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., the chairman of the committee, told
his colleagues that he intends ``to oppose all reservations,
conditions, etc.,'' with the possible exception of amendments
designed to solve a long-running fight between the Reagan
administration and Congress over treaty intepretation.
   Helms said today the committee shouldn't be ``a rubber stamp''
for the administration, which has urged approval of the treaty
without changes.
   Both Democratic and Republican leaders predict overwhelming
ratification when the treaty reaches the Senate floor and say only
10 or 12 senators are likely to vote against it. Ratification
requires a two-thirds vote of the 100-member Senate.
   ``I don't intend to obstruct'' the committee's work on the
treaty, Helms told his colleagues Tuesday, but he added, ``I'm
concerned that we're about to rush to judgment.''
   Given the large number of amendments, Pell said the panel now
``seems very unlikely'' to meet its original goal of finishing work
by Friday.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., told Helms, ``If you don't have the
votes and you simply try to overload it with amendments, that isn't
fair.''
   Most of Helms' amendments are designed to improve what he says
are compliance verification problems and clear up ambiguities.
   The majority of Helms' proposals would amend the ratification
resolution, which would not require new negotiations with the
Soviet Union.
   Any change made by the Senate in the actual text of the treaty
would have to be accepted by the Soviet Union, and administration
officials have urged the Senate to avoid so-called ``killer
amendments'' that would cause the Soviets to reject new talks.
   The treaty requires the elimination of nuclear-armed missiles
with a range of 300 miles to 3,400 miles and includes on-site
inspection provisions among its verification system, which is the
most intrusive in arms control history.
   The Foreign Relations Committee heard endorsements of the pact
Tuesday from two other committees, Intelligence and Armed Services,
which had also looked at the treaty during the past two months.
   But the congressional debate over the treaty has been clouded by
the reopening of a long fight between the Democratic-controlled
Congress and the White House.
   The complicated legal fight involves the question of whether an
administration has the legal right to unilaterally change how the
United States interprets a treaty. Reagan asserts the
administration has such a right, but Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman
of the Armed Services Committee, and other legislators have
disagreed.
   The fight involves the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, but
it has spilled over into the debate on the Intermediate-range
Nuclear Forces treaty, Nunn told the Foreign Relations Committee.
   Nunn said letters written by White House Counsel Arthur B.
Culvahouse Jr. effectively undercut previous assurances from
Secretary of State George P. Shultz that administration testimony
on the new pact is ``authoritative.''
   Nunn said Culvahouse asserted that some administration responses
may be less authoritative than others.
   Culvahouse suggested that the testimony of a secretary of state
may be more authoritative than that of other administration
witnesses or responses in writing to questions by members of
Congress, Nunn said.
   Culvahouse has since issued a second letter asserting that his
original remarks were not inconsistent with the Shultz statement.
But Nunn said he finds that unacceptable.
   Nunn said the new letter ``puts the Shultz statement in the
trashcan, saying that certain testimony is not to be taken
seriously.''
   The dispute should be resolved by the full Senate instead of
seeking another letter from the administration, even from the
president, said Nunn.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said the dispute ``is the major
stumbling block and could create grave perils if we don't resolve
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
