<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ConsumerPrices 3rdLd-Writethru a0577 03-23 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Consumer Prices, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0577,720</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf with Fitzwater comment after 2nd graf pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices, restrained by lower food and
energy costs, rose a modest 0.2 percent in February, the government
said today in a report that shows inflation remains tame.
   Food prices fell 0.3 percent after rising 0.3 percent in
January. Energy costs, which had fallen 0.7 percent in the
preceding month, fell 0.6 percent last month.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater hailed the report, and
one showing that the nation's gross national product had risen 4.8
percent in the last quarter of 1987, as ``more good news on the
economic front. ... The economy is doing well. The Reagan miracle
holds.''
   So far this year, consumer prices have been increasing at a rate
of 3.2 percent. That compares to the moderate 4.4 percent rate for
all of 1987 and the scant 1.1 percent 1986 increase.
   Some economists suggested that last month's moderate food and
energy cost hikes may be masking hefty increases for other goods
and services.
   Subtracting these two volatile categories, however, the index
for all other goods and services also advanced 0.2 percent in
February after a 0.5 percent increase in January, when prices
overall rose 0.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A restrained Consumer Price Index had been expected since the
Labor Department reported that the companion Producer Price Index,
also restrained by moderating energy and food prices, had dipped
0.2 percent in February.
   The department gave these other specifics on February retail
price activity:
   _Grocery store prices fell 0.6 percent after a 0.2 percent rise
in the previous month; restaurant meals were up 0.3 percent, the
same as in January.
   Pacing the drop in food prices was a 4.0 percent fall in the
costs of fruits and vegetables, more than offsetting 0.4 percent
rise for meats, poultry and fish.
   _Gasoline prices fell 1.7 percent, down for the third month in a
row. Gasoline prices had fallen 1.7 percent in December and 1.6
percent in January.
   _Heating oil prices were up 0.6 percent while the cost of
natural gas and electricity rose 0.5 percent.
   _New automobile prices rose 0.3 percent.
   _Clothing prices fell 0.3 percent.
   _Alchoholic beverage prices rose 0.9 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Last month's 0.2 percent gain was equivalent to an annual
inflation rate of 2.1 percent.
   The February increase left the overall index at 116.0, meaning
that a hypothetical selection of goods costing $100 during a
1982-84 base period would have cost $116.00 last month.
   Unlike other figures in the report, the overall index is not
adjusted for seasonal fluctuations.
   The Labor Department recently changed its base period. Had the
former computation been used, the February consumer price index
would have been 347.4 compared to a 1967 base of 100.
   That means that the same selection of goods would have cost
$13.00 more last month than in February 1987, when the CPI was
334.4.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Unexpectedly brisk economic activity is raising some economists'
concerns that inflation may pick up in the months ahead,
particularly as import prices rise further under pressure from a
dollar that is now 50 percent weaker against key foreign currencies
than it was three years ago.
   A weaker dollar makes imports more expensive. Higher prices,
particularly for Japanese and European products, have been noticed
on store shelves in recent months as a result of these
exchange-rate movements.
   This is good for the U.S. trade deficit, because as imports get
more expensive U.S. goods become cheaper and more competitive
overseas. But analysts have long warned that any sustained increase
in import prices could fuel overall higher inflation.
   Adding to worries about inflation was the February unemployment
report, showing that the jobless rate fell to 5.7 percent, the best
performance since l979.
   As unemployment declines below a certain level, pressure builds
for higher wages to fill vacant jobs. Economists disagree on the
exact level.
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan told Congress last
week that he felt that inflation could be rekindled if unemployment
fell another 0.5 percentage points.
   ``I don't think inflation will be a problem probably for the
whole year, but the bond markets are worried,'' said Michael K.
Evans, president of a private economic consulting service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
