<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Colombia-DrugCartel 1stLd-Writethru a0526 03-23 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Drug Cartel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0526,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Chief Of Newspaper Slain, Daughter Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with killing of newspaper security chief.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of security for a Medellin
newspaper that has fought drug trafficking was shot and killed
today and his young daughter was wounded, police said.
   El Colombiano security chief, Jorge Alberto Stefan Gomez, was
leaving his house with his wife and child when several gunmen in
parked cars opened fire with pistols and submachine guns.
   Investigators said Stefan's wife was not injured and that they
did not know who was behind the attack.
   On Tuesday, troops trying to arrest an alleged drug kingpin
tripped a sophisticated alarm system at a country estate and the
man got away.
   The army said Pablo Escobar Gaviria escaped after a shootout in
which one man, thought to be one of Escobar's bodyguards, was
injured.
   Escobar, wanted in the United States on drug charges, is an
alleged leader of the notorious Medellin drug cartel and reportedly
a billionaire.
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration says the cartel is
responsible for 80 percent of the cocaine that reaches the United
States.
   At least 25 of Escobar's heaviy armed bodyguards were arrested
after the clash and 13 vehicles, various firearms, ammunition,
communications equipment and documents seized, the army said in a
communique.
   Escobar's wife, Maria Victoria, and her sister were arrested
elsewhere in Medellin carrying ``several documents of interest,''
the army said.
   Escobar was indicted in 1986 on federal drug charges in the
United States. Last month, another U.S. drug indictment named him
along with Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and 14
others.
   Colombia's Justice Ministry in January ordered the arrest of
Escobar and others named as cartel leaders for extradition to the
United States.
   Since then no cartel leader has been arrested.
   The newspaper El Colombiano has urged the Colombian government
to pursue its war on drug traffickers. Medellin, the cocaine
capital of Colombia, is where many drug traffickers live. It is
also the site of cocaine processing plants.
   On March 10 two bombs were thrown from a speeding car at the
newspaper's offices. A guard threw the bombs into the street and a
passer-by was killed.
   Last November gunmen shot up the home of El Colombiano's
publisher, Juan Gomez Martinez. The gunmen apparently were trying
to kidnap Gomez to get the government to suspend extraditions of
Colombians to the United States.
   Drug traffickers have killed a justice minister, an attorney
general, 21 judges, two newspaper editors and scores of policemen
and soldiers in the last four years.
</TEXT>
