<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ski-Avalanche     03-23 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ski-Avalanche,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Avalanche Claims Life Of California Skier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REVELSTOKE, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An avalanche that plunged
down on a helicopter skiing expedition left one skier dead, but an
expedition guide was rescued after being buried under snow for
nearly 90 minutes, authorities said.
   Pandora Chapman, 26, of Davis, Calif., died in avalanches on
Sale Mountain near this southeastern British Columbia community
Tuesday, said coroner Sam Olynyk.
   It was the second fatality this year involving Selkirk Tangiers
Heli-Skiing, based in Golden, British Columbia.
   Guide Erik Suchovs of Revelstoke skied ahead of his party and
was buried by an avalanche.
   ``The three skiers skied down to locate him and another
avalanche came down behind them,'' Olynyk said. Chapman was buried,
and the other two skiers were partly buried.
   Suchovs was uncovered by searchers using emergency radio
locators. According to Queen Victoria Hospital administrator Jim
Vaillancourt, Suchovs was in good shape and was treated and
released.
   The two surviving skiers, a California man and a woman from
Revelstoke, were also treated and released.
   Jim Bay, an avalanche technician with the Highways Ministry,
said the avalanche occurred because ``basically, the snow of the
past three or four days didn't bond to the surface.''
   Since 1972, 29 people have died while heli-skiing in British
Columbia. Heli-skiers are taken to areas of deep powder snow
accessible mainly by helicopter, allowing them to ski untouched
areas.
</TEXT>
