<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Fox     03-23 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Fox,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former New York Mirror Fashion Columnist Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alma Archer Fox, a well-known authority
on fashion, style and taste during her career as a syndicated
columnist with the New York Mirror, has died. She was 89.
   The Galesburg native, who died Tuesday, was a 1919 graduate of
Knox College in Galesburg and landed her first fashion job in Los
Angeles where she designed custom-made Cadillacs.
   Ms. Fox moved to New York in 1924 where she ran a charm school
on Fifth Avenue and became a columnist. Highlights of her career
included interviewing Adolf Hitler, drinking with Ernest Hemingway
in Paris and sailing south of France with James Joyce.
   In 1937, at the height of her popularity, Ms. Fox was featured
in a full-page ad in The Saturday Evening Post promoting Chrysler
automobiles and proclaiming her ``one of the world's great
authorities on style and smartness.''
   She was editor of the women's section of the New York Mirror and
her column on fashion and style was syndicated by the United Press
Association to more than 1,100 newspapers.
   Ms. Fox was married to Broadway composer Harry Archer and later
to T. Edward Fox. She returned to Galesburg in 1959 following her
second husband's death and wrote a weekly column for the Galesburg
post until her retirement in 1983.
   Ms. Fox, who died of pneumonia in a nursing home, is survived by
two nephews.

</TEXT>
