<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-ChemicalWarfare     03-23 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Chemical Warfare,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration today condemned the
reported use of chemical weapons by Iraq that Iran says killed or
wounded 5,000 people in Kurdish border cities last week.
   ``We condemn the use of chemical warfare and the gas use by
anybody, anywhere, anytime,'' said White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater.
   Referring to television broadcasts, Fitzwater said, ``I saw _
everyone in the administration saw _ the same reports you saw last
night. They were horrible, outrageous, disgusting and should serve
as a reminder to all countries of why chemical warfare should be
banned.''
   Asked if the United States would convey its reaction to Baghdad,
he said, ``our views are known ... to all governments.''
   Meanwhile, the International Committee of the Red Cross also
condemned the use of chemical weapons in the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq
war, calling it a ``new and tragic escalation'' of the conflict,
and said it had taken urgent steps to end such attacks.
</TEXT>
