<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1224EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Armenia 1stLd-Writethru a0565 03-23 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0565,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviets Ignore Armenian Annexation Demands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Soviet government not
addressing Aremenian demands. Picks up 2nd graf, `Alexander
Ogorodnikov ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet government today ignored Armenian
demands for annexation of a predominantly Armenian section of a
neighboring republic and called for efforts to improve social and
economic conditions in the area.
   A session of the Presidium of the national Supreme Soviet,
called after carefully orchestrated appeals by 13 Soviet republics,
made no reference to the Armenian demands.
   The resolution today appeared to be a definitive response from
the Kremlin leadership to the demands regarding the
Nagorno-Karabakh region of the republic of Azerbaijan.
   Armenian activists want the region united with Armenia.
   The Presidium ordered the Soviet Council of Ministers to ``work
out all measures directed at deciding the immediate economic and
social-cultural development of the Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous
Region.''
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other top leaders
participated in the meeting. It called on officials of Armenian and
Azerbaijan to bring to ``strict accountability those who with their
actions destabilized the situation.''
   That statement appeared to indicate authorities would take
action not only against those who have been arrested for violence
in ethnic rioting that killed at least 32 people, but also Armenian
activists.
   Earlier, a Moscow dissident said Soviet authorities had sent
back to Armenia an activist who had been giving foreign journalists
information about the ethnic unrest between Aremanians and
Azerbaijanis.
   Alexander Ogorodnikov, a former political prisoner, said
Armenian nationalist Paryur Arikyan was put on a plane for Yerevan,
the Armenian capital, at 1:30 a.m.
   He said calls to Armenian activists in Yerevan today indicated
that Arikyan had arrived from Moscow.
   Another dissident source, Tamara Grigoryants, told The
Associated Press on Tuesday that police arrested Arikyan in central
Moscow after he met with a Western television journalist.
   Thousands of Armenians protested last month for approval to
annex Nagorno-Karabakh.
   On Feb. 28 rioting broke out in Sumgait, a city of Azerbaijan,
in which officials say 32 people were killed.
   Armenian activists say at least 78 Armenians were killed by
Azerbaijanis in Sumgait.
   Arikyan, who said he spent 17 years in jail for Armenian
nationalist activities, arrived in Moscow from Yerevan last week
and held news conferences for foreign journalists at Ogorodnikov's
apartment.
   He said Saturday that officials had confiscated his internal
passport, so he had traveled to Moscow via Soviet Georgia and the
Russian city of Tula to escape detection.
   The Tass news agency, meanwhile, announced the governments of 13
Soviet republics had addressed the violence in the republics of
Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   Tass said the Supreme Soviets of Kazakhstan, Lithuania,
Moldavia, Latvia, Kirghizia, Tadzhikistan, Turkmenia and Estonia
passed resolutions calling for ``discretion and composure, and at
the same time for issuing a decisive rebuff to any illegitimate
actions.''
   That followed a Tass report Tuesday that the Russian federation,
and the republics of Ukraine, Byelorussia, Georgia and Uzbekistan
had passed similar resolutions and urged the national Supreme
Soviet to take action.
   Such concerted action by those 13 republics, equal under the
Soviet constitution to Armenia and Azerbaijan, was very unusual and
almost certainly orchestrated by Communist Party authorities.
   The government calls for action also came as the Communist Party
newspaper Pravda and the government newspaper, Izvestia, ran
articles sharply criticizing Armenian activists.
   Pravda's article Monday charging that the annexation campaign
had a ``clear anti-socialist spirit'' sparked a protest in Yerevan.
The Pravda journalist whose name was one of three attached to the
article disassociated himself from it in a telegram to the paper's
editor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
