<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorkerNotice     03-23 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Worker Notice,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Refuses to Limit Debate on Worker-Notice Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate refused today to limit debate on a
bill that would require the government to individually warn
thousands of workers each year that they face a high risk of cancer
and other diseases from exposure to dangerous chemicals and other
substances in their jobs.
   In a key test vote, Democratic supporters of the House-passed
legislation could muster only 33 of the 60 Senate votes necessary
to limit debate on the measure to 30 hours before an up-or-down
vote on its passage.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, the primary Senate author of the
legislation, offered today to accept amendments expanding
exemptions for small businesses and farms in an effort to pick up
more support in anticipation of another vote scheduled Friday on
cutting off debate.
   The bill's proponents had filed motions to limit the debate as
soon the measure was brought to the Senate floor on Tuesday after
Republican and business opponents made it clear they would try to
prevent a vote on the bill itself through the use of a filibuster.
   Ending a filibuster requires 60 votes while final passage of a
bill requires only a simple majority, or 51 votes if all 100
senators are present.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the leader of the opponents, said
Metzenbaum's willingness ``to whittle the bill down until he gets
engouh votes to pass it'' demonstrates the problems with the
legislation.
   ``If it's good enough for one, it's good enough for all,'' Hatch
said. ``The overwhelming majority of the business community opposes
this bill.'' Business groups that support it, Hatch said, ``have
worked out exemptions for themselves to the exclusion of everybody
else.''
   Among the business supporters of the bill are the Chemical
Manufacturers Association, the American Electronics Association and
dozens of the nation's largest companies, including General
Electric, IBM and Atlantic Richfield. Most already have their own
worker notification programs.
   Opponents include the Reagan administration, the National
Association of Manufacturers and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
   The bill would establish an agency in the Department of Health
and Human Services to determine which workers are most at risk. The
National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health would then be
required to send individual notices to between 100,000 and 300,000
of them every year and employers would be required to provide
medical monitoring programs for them.
   The National Association of Manufacturers and other opponents
claim that the monitoring programs and the possibility of
subsequent lawsuits by workers and former workers against their
employers could cost businesses up to $6 billion a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
