<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Murder     03-23 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Murder,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Given Suspended Death Sentence for Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager was given a suspended death sentence
and six classmates received prison terms ranging from two years to
life for the stabbing death of a college student, an official
newspaper reported Tuesday.
   The Beijing Daily said the seven, all 17- and 18-year-old
students from a technical school, were convicted Monday of
involvement in the Dec. 2 slaying of Zhang Han, a student from
Beijing Normal University.
   The report said the seven ran out of their dormitory and
attacked Zhang and others with bricks and knives after hearing
people outside shouting insulting remarks. It was not clear if
Zhang was among the shouters.
   Dong Qiufei, identified as the assailant who stabbed Zhang,
received a death sentence with a two-year reprieve. That means the
sentence will be changed to life imprisonment if he shows a good
attitude in the next two years.
   Long Kaiyuan, who had a criminal record for thefts, was
convicted of hooliganism and sentenced to life in prison. The other
five received terms ranging from two to 10 years.
   Zhang was among three college students murdered in brawls in
December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
