<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ReadingBooklet     03-23 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reading Booklet,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Offers Parental How-To Book on Helping Kids Learn To
Read</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Education Department on Wednesday released
a booklet with tips for parents who want to help their children
read but may not know the best way to go about it.
   ``The surest prevention of illiteracy is making sure kids know
how to read,'' Chester E. Finn Jr., assistant education secretary
for research and improvement, said in unveiling the 29-page booklet.
   ``And children's first and most important teachers are their
parents. We want to help parents who want to help their children to
read,'' he said.
   The booklet, ``Becoming a Nation of Readers: What Parents Can
Do,'' begins by noting that reading is a skill that continues to
improve with practice. Then, starting with parents of preschoolers,
the booklet offers suggestions for things parents can do to
encourage their children to read.
   The Education Department's first tip to parents of young
children is to read aloud to them. ``When adults read aloud,
children quickly learn that a book is a wonderful thing,'' the
booklet notes.
   For parents of children in kindergarten and first grade the
booklet suggests parents continue to read aloud with their
children, take their children on trips to the library or bookstores
and listen to their children read. The booklet also recommends that
parents ``place reasonable limits on TV viewing.''
   And for parents of children in higher grades, the booklet
suggests parents set aside a time and place at home for studying.
It also recommends parents keep close tabs on their children's
progress and encourage reading for fun.
   ``For some families, plainly this booklet is not necessary,''
Finn said. ``But it's a useful book for parents who have the
impulse and don't know how to go about it.''
   The reading booklet, which is being printed by the Lexington,
Mass.-based D.C. Heath and Co. textbook publishers, can be obtained
by sending 50 cents to: ``What Parents Can Do,'' Consumer
Information Center, Pueblo, Colo. 81009. Numerous school districts
and the American Federation of Teachers also are printing copies.
</TEXT>
