<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WaterEmergency     03-23 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Water Emergency,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Declare Emergency In Water Shortage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Water officials facing what could be the
state's second-driest year ever have declared an emergency shortage
and warned 1.1 million customers that water rationing may be
ordered for homes and businesses.
   The East Bay Municipal Utility District stopped short of
imposing emergency restrictions but voted yesterday to approve a
$300,000 campaign to teach the public water conservation methods.
   ``We don't want to make this a Draconian thing, but we do want
to save a lot of water,'' district General Manager Jerome Gilbert
said at the board of director's meeting Tuesday.
   The board will meet again April 13 to consider rationing but is
already divided over whether to allow more water in the warmer
areas such as the San Ramon Valley.
   Directors from Berkeley and Richmond argued it would be unfair
if affluent suburbs such as San Ramon receive an extra share of
water for their sprawling lawns and gardens.
   Water officials said studies show rain and snow runoff from the
Mokelumne River Basin, the district's major water source, is
estimated at 180,000 feet, 24 percent of normal.
   ``This year has the potential to be the second-driest year
ever,'' said Ted Way, chief engineer.
   Officials stopped short of declaring a drought for the district
east of San Francisco, but said river runoff from snow melt will
average 60 percent of normal between April and July statewide.
</TEXT>
