<DOCNO> AP880323-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1304EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Christic-Lawsuit Bjt   03-23 0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christic-Lawsuit, Bjt,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendants Call Drug-Trafficking Allegations `Legal Terrorism'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nearly 2-year-old lawsuit that accuses
several Iran-Contra figures of collaborating with Colombian drug
lords is under attack by the defendants who call the complaint
``legal terrorism.''
   The lawsuit, filed in May 1986 several months before the
Iran-Contra affair was exposed publicly, names some of the people
in the private network that Lt. Col. Oliver L. North formed to help
the Nicaraguan Contras.
   The lawsuit has attracted widespread attention, and The Christic
Institute, a liberal policy group representing the plaintiffs, has
used it as a vehicle to raise money.
   Daniel Sheehan, the Christic's chief counsel, has traveled
around the country speaking about the suit, which was filed by
Martha Honey and Tony Avirgan, two American reporters based in
Costa Rica.
   The allegations in the civil lawsuit _ set for trial June 26 in
federal court in Miami _ are significantly different and much
broader than the issues raised by Lawrence Walsh, the independent
counsel in the Iran-Contra case.
   Last week, a federal grand jury indicted four men on charges of
conspiring to defraud the U.S. government in the program to sell
weapons to Iran and divert the proceeds to the Contras.
   They are John M. Poindexter, the former national security
adviser; North, Poindexter's one-time aide; and Richard V. Secord
and Albert Hakim, two arms dealers who helped North run the
Iran-Contra program.
   Secord and Hakim are among the 29 defendants in the Miami
lawsuit, which does not cite any U.S. government officials. Central
to the lawsuit is the claim that the defendants conspired to
traffic in drugs and plot assassinations in Central America and
elsewhere.
   Lawyers for both sides expect the trial to proceed despite
Walsh's criminal indictments.
   ``This case is going to trial,'' said Thomas Spencer, an
attorney for retired Gen. John Singlaub, one of the defendants in
the lawsuit.
   Honey and Avirgan are represented by attorneys for The Christic
Institute, a liberal policy group based in the nation's capital.
   ``I think they (the plaintiffs) are desperately looking for a
way to get out of the lawsuit,'' Spencer said. ``They have come to
the conclusion there is no basis for their case.''
   Peter Dykstra, a spokesman for the Washington-based institute,
rejected Spencer's claim. ``We want a trial _ why else would we be
doing this?'' he said.
   Spencer and other defense lawyers have waged a concerted effort
to discredit the lawsuit. Among other things, they have obtained
affidavits from some of the Christic's sources, contradicting
information in the lawsuit.
   Judge James Lawrence King ordered the institute to reveal its
sources.
   Secord, meantime, has filed a $5 million slander suit against
Eugene Wheaton, one of the institute's principal ources. Wheaton's
lawyer, Robert Thompson, said his client has not responded to the
lawsuit.
   At the heart of the Honey-Avirgan lawsuit is the allegation that
``a secret team'' headed by former CIA official Theodore Shackley
worked over two decades to manage a covert, shadow government
funded with drug profits. There has never been independent
confirmation of the charge.
   Shackley has waged a personal publicity campaign to defend
himself and vowed to seek reprisals through the legal system.
   In an article in the Journal of Defense & Diplomacy, Shackley
described the plaintiffs as ``practitioners of character
assassination through legal terrorism...''
   The Christic Institute stands by its charges, and Sheehan says
he is developing more information that implicates the defendants.
But many of the institute's theories will not be tested in court
because King has limited testimony in the case to events between
1983 and 1986.
   Specifically, Avirgan and Honey seek damages of $22 million to
compensate Avirgan for injuries he suffered inside Nicaragua at a
bombing at a May 1986 press conference held by former Contra
leader, Eden Pastora. Three reporters died in the bombing.
   The lawsuit claims the defendants, who include known Colombian
drug smugglers Pablo Escobar and Jorge Ochoa, conspired to:
   _ Kill Pastora because he would not cooperate with other Contra
rebels.
   _ Smuggle cocaine into the United States to finance Contra
operations.
   _ Assassinate a U.S. ambassador in Costa Rica in order to claim
a bounty.
   The special congressional committees that investigated the
Iran-Contra case last summer did not deal specifically with
allegations raised in the lawsuit.
   But a Senate panel chaired by Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., is
looking into reports of drug-dealing by the Contras. The rebels
have denied they trafficked in narcotics.
   The Iran-Contra committees, however, heard public testimony from
Glenn Robinette, a former CIA security specialist who said Secord
paid him thousands of dollars to investigate the lawsuit in 1986.
   Over the past several months, the institute has conducted
depositions of witnesses, many of whom have refused to talk, citing
their Fifth Amendment right to remain silent.
   Spencer said the lawsuit has cost Singlaub $150,000 in legal
fees so far, and that could double. The institute has budgeted $3
million to cover operational expenses 1988, with 90 percent of the
money expected to be spent on the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
