<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1310EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CancerAward     03-23 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Award,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marrow Transplant Researcher Wins $50,000 Cancer Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bone marrow transplant researcher was named
Wednesday as recipient of the $50,000 Bristol-Myers Award for
Distinguished Achievement in Cancer Research.
   George Santos, professor of oncology and medicine at The Johns
Hopkins University School of Medicine in Baltimore, will receive
the prize at a luncheon May 4 in New York.
   Bone marrow transplants are used to treat leukemia.
   Santos was among the first researchers to realize the importance
of suppressing the immune system with drugs in bone marrow
transplants, to avoid a potentially fatal complication known as
graft-versus-host disease, said E. Donnall Thomas, director of the
Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center and a member of the award
committee.
   In the disease, immune system cells from the donated marrow
attack the recipient's tissue as foreign.
   Santos said he and colleagues are now studying use of marrow
transplants as part of treatment of cancers of the breast, ovary
and colon. The research involves using higher-than-usual doses of
chemotherapy to kill cancer cells, then doing transplants to
restore marrow destroyed as a side effect.
   Another line of research is using the drug thalidomide in
fighting graft-versus-host disease, he said. Animal studies are
encouraging, he said in a statement.
   Thalidomide is best known for causing birth defects when taken
by pregnant women as a sleeping pill in the 1950s. But apart from
that, scientists say, it has far fewer side effects than
cyclosporine, another suppressor of the immune system that can
damage the kidneys.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
