<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Iraq     03-23 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Iraq,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Planes Bomb Joint Security Zone Near Turkish Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Iraqi jetfighters inadvertently
violated Turkish airspace when they bombed Kurdish guerrillas in a
joint security zone along the border, it was reported Wednesday.
   The semi-official Anatolia News Agency said Tuesday's air raid
caused panic in villages in southeast Turkey, a few miles from the
border with Iraq. It said the Iraqi warplanes bombed Kurdish
guerrillas fighting for an autonomous homeland.
   It was not known if there were any causualties.
   An estimated 19 million Kurds seeking independence live in the
area where the borders of Iran, Turkey and Iraq meet.
   Turkey and Iraq have an agreement granting rights to each other
to operate in a 6-mile-wide joint security zone along the common
frontier.
   Turkish military units also have been fighting Kurdish
guerrillas over the past four years. Turkish warplanes staged two
air raids against Kurdish rebel hideouts in the joint security zone
in the past two years.
