<HEAD>Shamie Will Not Challenge Kennedy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with announcement</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Republican Party Chairman Ray Shamie said
today he will not challenge Sen. Edward M. Kennedy this year.
Instead, longtime Shamie aide Joseph Malone will run against the
veteran Democrat.
   Shamie, a retired Walpole millionaire, told a news conference he
had decided, despite pleas from President Reagan and other national
party officials, to remain state party chairman.
   Among other things, Shamie said he was concerned about giving up
a chairmanship won only last year to run what most observers agree
is an uphill battle to unseat Kennedy, who will be seeking his
fifth full term.
   Shamie, 67, endorsed Malone, saying that none of the other
Republicans who expressed interest in challenging Kennedy would be
serious candidates.
   Malone, 33, of Waltham, has been a close aide to Shamie since
1982, when Shamie emerged by mounting a credible challenge to
Kennedy. Currently, Malone is executive director of the Republican
Party under Shamie.
   A graduate of Harvard College in 1978, Malone has helped operate
a family trucking business and also is a partner in family real
estate holdings.
   ``I have devoted 10 years of my life working to help bring back
a two-party system to Massachusetts,'' Malone said in an interview.
``It's important that we have a strong, aggressive campaign in
Massachusetts.''
   The top GOP party brass was concerned that a weak challenge to
Kennedy would leave him free to roam the country helping other
Democratic campaigns, including the presidential race.
   But state Rep. John MacGovern said Shamie, ``did not like being
used by other people like a battering ram. He did not want to run.
You're just banging yourself up to keep Ted Kennedy busy.''
   Malone is a virtual unknown in Massachusetts except in political
circles. He is well off from his family business interests but said
he is not a millionaire.
   Shamie spent $1.8 million against Kennedy in 1982 when he lost
61 percent to 38 percent. He spent a record $2.3 million in 1984
against John Kerry for Senate in a race Kerry won 55 percent to 45
percent.
</TEXT>
