<1ST_LINE>u i PM-US-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru a0649 03-23 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-PLO, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0649,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Assemby condemns U.S. Move Against PLO Mission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to update with PLO statement, editing for
transition. Picks up 10th graf pvs ``The feud...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL ALEXANDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly voted overwhemingly
today to condemn the U.S. move to close the Palestine Liberation
Organization's U.N. Mission.
   The assembly voted 148-2 to deplore the U.S. action and urge it
to abide by the international U.N. Headquarters Treaty, which
allows foreign missions to operate. The United States and Israel
voted against the resolution.
   General Assembly resolutions are not legally binding, but carry
moral weight.
   The vote came one day after the U.S. Justice Department filed a
lawsuit seeking to close the PLO Mission and freeze its funds, in
accordance with an anti-terrorist law.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun, the deputy permanent
representative, said the Justice Department was obliged by law to
enforce the anti-terrorist legislation, which would close the
mission.
   But he said the United States would take no further steps to
close the mission until a court has ruled on the U.S. lawsuit filed
in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
   The PLO envoy, Zehdi Labib Terzi, told the assembly that the
United States claims to be proud to play host to the United
Nations. Then he shouted:
   ``What pride to you have in throwing your guests out?
   ``Is this the message the U.S. delegation wants to bring to the
world? That guests have no respect, the United Nations has no
respect, international law has no respect? ...
   ``This is not gunboat policy any more. We are living in a stage
where the human approach, where obligations are respected,'' said
Terzi. He said the PLO will fight the U.S. lawsuit.
   Of the United States, Terzi said: ``Is this the country which
claims to be the bastion of freedom and democracy ... afraid to
permit the voice of the Palestinians?''
   Israeli Ambassador Johanan Bein, the deputy permanent
representative, told the assembly that the PLO has been ``the
principal terrorist organization of our time'' and it rejects the
central U.N. principle of peaceful settlement of disputes.
   On Tuesday, the PLO accused the United States of engaging in
``financial terrorism'' by seeking a court order to close the
mission and force the PLO to transfer its bank funds out of the
United States.
   The closure of the mission is required under the 1987
Anti-Terrorism Act, which found the PLO and its affiliates were a
terrorist organization responsible for numerous violent incidents,
including the murder of an American citizen during the hijacking of
the cruise ship Achille Lauro in 1985.
   The feud over the future of the PLO's mission on East 65th
Street has created a crisis in U.S.-U.N. relations.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz also has called the law ``a
very bad piece of legislation'' which unnecessarily glorifies the
PLO.
   Terzi has said he will have to be dragged away from the PLO
mission and that if forced to move, it will be to the United
Nations on international territory, out of reach of U.S. marshals.
   In 1973, PLO Chief Yasser Arafat spent a night at the United
Nations because he could not stay on U.S. territory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1319EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Politics     03-23 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Politics,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Comes Out Swinging in Re-Election Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobody was surprised when President Francois
Mitterrand finally announced he would seek re-election, but many
were stunned by the pugnacity of his words and his version of
Charles de Gaulle's ``me or chaos'' alternative.
   The 71-year-old Socialist president declared his candidacy in a
television interview Tuesday night, waiting until five weeks before
the first round of voting to end months of speculation.
   Mitterrand had said he preferred to step down but would run for
a second seven-year term if ``exceptional circumstances'' warranted
it. He said Tuesday that after listening to the speeches of other
candidates, he was convinced France is in danger.
   ``I see a risk that the country might fall into the quarrels and
division that so often have undermined it,'' he said. ``I want
France to be united. And it will not be if it is taken in hand by
intolerant minds, by parties who want everything, by clans, by
gangs. ...There must be civil peace in France.''
   Though he named no names, the president's remarks were aimed at
his two main opponents, conservative Premier Jacques Chirac and
former centrist Premier Raymond Barre.
   Typical of the reaction in the conservative press Wednesday,
Gerard Badel wrote in Le Parisien: ``The chief of state has, in
sum, confronted the French people with the choice that he had so
often reproached Gen. de Gaulle for: me or chaos.''
   Alain Juppe, spokesman for Chirac's government, said Mitterrand
``goes to war against perils that do not exist.''
   ``If there is really danger, one wonders why Mr. Mitterrand
waited so long to say so. In reality, all that is pure
fabrication,'' Juppe said.
   French presidential elections are run in two rounds. The first,
April 24, pits Mitterrand against Chirac, Barre and a handful of
minor candidates. If, as expected, nobody wins a majority, a runoff
will be held May 8 between the top two vote-getters.
   For the past year, the polls have indicated that Mitterrand will
win the second round handily, no matter who his opponent is. But he
could slip now that he has had to abandon his strictly presidential
role.
   Chirac remarked on what he called Mitterrand's ``language of
rare violence and sectarianism that risked setting the French
against one another.'' The stakes, he said, are clear: ``On one
side, there is the Socialist Party that wants to retake power and
institute Socialist policies ... on the other is the (conservative
parliamentary) majority that has governed for two years in calm and
union.''
   Barre said he doubted Mitterrand could unite the country, adding
that since the president's election in 1981 he has been ``the
president of one fraction of the French population against
another.''
   The reality is that since the mid-1980s, French politics have
moved toward the center. The gulf between the left and right has
narrowed to the point where it is difficult to distinguish the two.
   Without an overriding issue, the campaign has evolved into one
of personalities.
   There is Chirac, 55, the hard-driving, almost frenetic,
political bulldozer, and currently the leading rightist; Barre, 63,
the thoughtful economics professor, who is more toward the center;
and Mitterrand, who in the two years since the right ousted the
Socialists from control of the National Assembly, has become the
sage father figure.
   The vocabulary is the same. Each has presented himself as the
only man capable of uniting the French.
   Few differences exist in foreign policy and defense. Even
unemployment, now at 10.4 percent, has not emerged as a
battleground. Both right and left have tried and failed to come to
grips with it.
   In his announcement, Mitterrand presented no program, saying
only that he would get to it later.
   Since ``cohabitation'' between the Socialist president and the
conservative premier was forced on French politics by the 1986
legislative elections, Mitterrand has profited the most. He has
taken pains to distance himself from the Socialist Party, which he
founded and led for years, and is trying to appear as a man above
parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1322EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Fast     03-23 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Fast,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protest Fast For Return Of Refugees To Pakistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ailing leader of at least 150,000
Pakistani refugees began a fast Wednesday to demand that Islamabad
take back the refugees stranded here since 1971.
   ``If the Pakistan government does not respond favorably to our
request for early return to our country, hundreds and thousands of
our brothers and sisters will be on fast unto death,'' said Nasim
Khan, 64, who began his fast outside the National Press Club.
   Khan suffered a heart attack two weeks ago. He told The
Associated Press, ``It's better to die struggling to go back to our
homeland than live in vice, hunger and disease ridden camps in an
alien country.''
   Khan and the others were stranded in 1971 when Bangladesh,
formerly East Pakistan, became an independent country after a
liberation struggle and a war between India and Pakistan.
   By 1973, 174,000 refugees returned to Pakistan, but the
repatriation ended abruptly when funds ran out, stranding 250,000
people. About 100,000 are believed to have returned since, but the
rest remain in refugee camps in Bangladesh.
   Bangladesh Foreign Secretary Nazrul Islam told reporters
Wednesday that his government has renewed a longstanding request to
Pakistan to make arrangement for the return of the refugees.
   Islam said Pakistan has agreed in principle to take back the
refugees. But a Pakistani diplomat, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said sufficient funds for the transfer still were
lacking. Moslem charitable organizations have been asked for help
in raising the money.
   As Khan began his fast, hundreds of other refugees held a silent
march on a nearby street.
   Nasim Khan Bazlul Huda, 19, said, ``I will burn myself to death
soon if Pakistan does not announce a timetable for our
repatriation.''
   Islam said that Dhaka and Islamabad had approached a number of
countries and world organizations to raise enough money for a
repatriation of refugees.
   Four years ago, the stranded Pakistanis planned a march to their
homeland, but border guards crushed it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1318EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0658 03-23 0921</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0658,0947</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Mecham Staff Chief Testifies `No Effort To Cover Up' Loan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs details after 8th graf; pickup 9th graf:
Colter said...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham's former chief of staff
testified today there was no effort to cover up an $80,000 loan
from the governor's protocol fund to Mecham's auto dealership.
   ``I just forgot or failed'' to record the check in the fund's
checkbook register, former chief of staff Jim Colter told the
Senate.
   Colter also told prosecutor William French that Mecham had
called his home on Tuesday and left a message on the answering
machine ``that I had done a good job, or something to that effect''
in his earlier testimony.
   Meanwhile, the Senate voted 25-4 today to drop the longer
schedule it had adopted in an effort to speed up the impeachment
trial. Prosecution and defense lawyers complained the eight hours
of testimony Tuesday left them too little time for preparation, and
lawmakers agreed to return to a six-hour schedule.
   Voting against the shorter schedule were Republican Sens. Carl
Kunasek, Bob Usdane, Tony West and Peter Kay.
   The Senate is now hearing testimony on the second impeachment
charge, which accused Mecham of misusing $80,000 from the
governor's protocol fund by loaning it to Mecham Pontiac.
   ``There was certainly no effort to cover up'' the loan, Colter
testified today.
   Colter testified Tuesday that he warned the governor it would be
``politically unwise'' to borrow the money, but Mecham instructed
him to write the check anyway.
   ``You certainly were not anxious that the general public be
aware of this loan, were you?'' French asked today.
   ``No, I did not broadcast it,'' Colter replied.
   The former chief of staff acknowledged that he did not shop
around for better interest rates before processing the loan to
Mecham Pontiac, but added, ``As far as I'm concerned (the loan) was
a good investment of the money.''
   It had ``nothing to do with the governor's personal use,''
Colter said.
   However, Democratic Sen. Jones Osborn questioned whether it
would be a subsidy to Mecham Pontiac to loan it money if the
interest rate were lower than the dealership would have had to pay
to a bank.
   Colter said Mecham also asked him not to record a document
securing the loan, although Colter did not know why. He testified,
however, that he did not think any law had been broken ``or I would
have objected.''
   The protocol fund, created with fund-raising revenues from
Mecham's inauguration, is intended to be used for state ceremonial
gifts.
   The prosecution contends the fund is public money and therefore
the loan was illegal, while the defense says the money can be used
as Mecham sees fit, except to repay his campaign expenses.
   However, the first two witnesses to testify on the charge said
they were shocked when they heard that Mecham had loaned the funds
to his auto dealership.
   ``I was very surprised and disappointed and saddened,'' said
Warner Lee, a former state attorney general who advised the Mecham
inaugural committee. ``I thought that it was a very awkward thing
politically to have done.''
   ``I personally was shocked and initially felt betrayed,'' said
Deputy Maricopa County Attorney Howard Schwartz, who helped draft
an agreement for use of funds raised by Mecham's inaugural
committee.
   In an interview Tuesday on KTAR radio, Mecham said he considered
the protocol fund to be ``private association money ... not state
money.''
   He acknowledged he was told ``it was politically not a wise
thing to do, but I wasn't thinking of that.'' The governor said he
could have borrowed the money from other sources, but decided on
the protocol fund so it would earn the 9 percent interest being
paid by Mecham Pontiac.
   Mecham, the first U.S. governor to be impeached in six decades,
also said if he is exonerated, he will do a better job as governor.
   ``They'll probably say this is another one of those gaffes, but
a lot of the rats have come out of their holes that's been after
me, and now we know a lot more who they are,'' Mecham said. ``Quite
frankly, I'll be a lot wiser governor from here on out.''
   If he is allowed to resume his job, Mecham said, he will fire
Department of Public Safety Director Ralph Milstead, one of the
chief accusers in his Senate trial.
   A Senate conviction, Mecham said, ``will certainly not be on the
basis of evidence and on that we'll go and appeal it of course ...
probably direct to the U.S. Supreme Court.''
   Earlier Tuesday, the Senate finished hearing testimony on the
first impeachment charge _ that Mecham tried to thwart an
investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
against a former top Mecham aide.
   After heated debate, a motion to vote on the first count
immediately was dropped after it became clear most senators wanted
to hear testimony on all three charges first.
   The third charge accuses the governor of concealing a $350,000
campaign loan. A two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate is
required to convict Mecham and remove him from office.
   Meanwhile, a lawyer defending Mecham at his April 21 criminal
trial on six felony counts related to the $350,000 loan sought
dismissal of the charges. The lawyer, Michael Scott, said the
governor has been singled out for prosecution because he is
unpopular.
   The judge did not rule on the motion. Mecham also faces a May 17
recall election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1323EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BRF--Kennedy-Shamie 2ndLd-Writethru a0648 03-23 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Kennedy-Shamie, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0648,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamie Will Not Challenge Kennedy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0682 to correct keyword order, note it is 2nd
Ld-Writethru and expands throughout</NOTE>
