<HEAD>Light & Heavy Industry Ministers Replaced by Army Officer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein has dismissed the
ministers of light industry and heavy industry from his Cabinet and
replaced them with the army officer who supervises the manufacture
of Iraq's military hardware.
   A presidential decree issued Tuesday night and published
Wednesday by government newspapers said Heavy Industry Minister
Abdul-Tawab Mulahuwaish and Light Industry Minister Hatem
Abdul-Rashid were relieved of their duties.
   It did not say what prompted their dismissal, but added that
Col. Hussein Kamil has been appointed Minister of Industry and
Minerals.
   Government sources said the cabinet reshuffle is designed to
merge the two ministries and give the military industry a boost.
   Kamil, a career military man, has been heading the War Industry
Committee that supervises the manufacture of military equipment.
   Iraq says it is making some of its own ammunition and weapons,
including long-range missiles.
   More than 100 missiles have been fired at the Iranian capital,
Tehran, since Feb. 29 in a missile duel by the nations.
   While the Iraqis say these were homemade, Western military
analysts believe they are Soviet-built, surface-to-surface Scud-Bs
that the Iraqis have equipped with boosters to increase their range.
