<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dole 1stLd-Writethru a0701 03-23 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Accuses Democratic Hopefuls of `Failure of Vision' in Foreign
Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 9th graf pvs, bgng, `Broadening his,'
to UPDATE with comment from Dukakis campaign.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential contender Bob Dole on
Wednesday accused Michael Dukakis and the rest of the Democratic
White House hopefuls of a ``failure of nerve as well as a failure
of vision'' in responding to the Soviet-backed regime in Nicaragua.
   ``The call to defend the freedom of Nicaragua, which should be
easy for them to answer, instead produces endless foot-shuffling
and sophistry,'' Dole said in a speech that made little mention of
his own presidential candidacy and avoided even a single reference
to GOP front-runner George Bush.
   Dole said the issue of the Sandinista government in Nicaragua is
``as symbolic for our time as Hitler's brazen aggression was for an
earlier generation.''
   He warned that failure to confront it might eventually lead to
communist governments in Costa Rica, Panama or even Mexico as the
Sandinistas strengthen their grip at home and begin supporting
guerilla movements elsewhere.
   ``What will the Democrats say then?,'' he asked in a speech that
marked the beginning of an effort to lay out his views on a variety
of issues. The Kansas senator is far, far behind Bush in the race
for delegates to the Republican National Convention, and is widely
viewed as a candidate for withdrawal after the Wisconsin primary on
April 5.
   In his speech to the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, Dole addressed an issue that has divided Republican
candidates _ who favor military support for the Contras fighting
the Nicaraguan government _ from the Democrats who oppose it.
   He turned his fire on Massachusets Gov. Dukakis, the other
Democratic presidential hopefuls and the ``Democratic left.''
   Dole said Dukakis ``says that the Monroe Doctrine, which has
defined America's security in its own neighborhood for some 200
years, is `obsolete.' He says that this country ... has no choice
but to tolerate the existence of Soviet client states wherever
subversion might install them.''
   Broadening his attack, Dole added, ``Today, all the Democratic
party presidential candidates sound themes similar to the `Dukakis
Doctrine' for Latin America .... Instead of joining President
Reagan in challenging the thieves, they have found ways to
rationalize the loss of liberty in Nicaragua.''
   Dole's charges brought a sarcastic reply from Dukakis'
communications director, Leslie Dach.
   ``I guess Bob Dole is taking after Michael Dukakis because he's
accomplishing what Bob Dole can't _ beating George Bush in the
polls,'' Dach said.
   Dole said Democrats are guilty of an attitude that says
``America must not be too forceful'' that stems from the belief
that America, rather than the Soviet Union, poses a threat to peace.
   ``Perverse but pervasive, this attitude has enveloped the
Democratic side of the primary campaign like nerve gas,'' he said.
   Dole cited anti-Communist stands taken by Democratic presidents
Harry Truman and John F. Kennedy, but said the party has abandoned
its heritage.
   ``The question (among Democrats) has become whether we should
bear any burden at all? Will the liberal Democrats pay even a small
price, one reckoned in American money rather than American lives?''
he said.
   Dole said, ``What we see on the Democratic side of this
presidential campaign is a failure of nerve as well as a failure of
vision.''
   He added, ``Today we stand and watch as Nicaragua slowly twists
in the wind and the fate of the Americas begins to tilt.''
</TEXT>
