<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Streetsweeper,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Streetsweeper's Suicide a `Futile Gesture'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unemployed streetsweeper who burned himself to
death in a car near Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's residence
took his life in a ``futile gesture,'' a coroner said Wednesday.
   Westminster Coroner Paul Knapman made the remark after an
inquest ruled that Derek Bainbridge's death Feb. 16 was a suicide.
   Bainbridge, 40, who lived in Worksop in central England, had
been depressed about his inability to find work a year after
leaving his job as a streetsweeper.
   ``I am quite satisfied he has taken his life in a rather
dramatic but futile gesture,'' Knapman said.
   On Wednesday, Bainbridge's brother visited Mrs. Thatcher's
residence and presented a photograph of Derek inscribed with the
words from his suicide note, ``Too young to retire ... Too old to
live.''
   ``We are not a political family,'' said Joseph Bainbridge. ``But
we want Mrs. Thatcher to see the man who died at the end of her
road.''
   Unemployment in Britain was 9.1 percent in February, down from
9.2 percent in January and 11 percent in February last year.
</TEXT>
