<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Heard     03-23 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Heard,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Centenarian Philanthropist Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>McKINNEY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bessie Heard, who endowed her hometown
with a wildlife sanctuary and natural science museum, has died, a
museum spokesman said Wednesday. She was 101.
   More than 40,000 visitors each year come to the Heard Natural
Science Museum and Wildlife Sanctuary, which Miss Heard endowed in
1964. It includes more than five miles of nature trails, said Steve
Runnels, the museum's director of development.
   The non-profit museum and sanctuary are funded by the Bessie
Heard Foundation, membership dues, tuition fees, gift shop sales
and contributions.
   At the heart of the museum was ``Miss Bessie,'' as she was known
for most of her life.
   Miss Heard died Tuesday night at home, Runnels said.
   She was born May 26, 1886, the eldest of five daughters. Her
father, John Spencer Heard, spent four years in the Confederate
Army and then opened a general store in McKinney, north of Dallas,
with his brother.
   Miss Heard attended Mary Baldwin College in Staunton, Va., but
spent most of her life in McKinney.
   Survivors include two cousins. A funeral was scheduled Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
