<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Workers     03-23 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Workers,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Considers Federal-State Role in Protecting Fired
Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal collective-bargaining laws should take
precedence over state laws protecting union employees who are fired
for filing workers' compensation claims, a lawyer told the Supreme
Court on Wednesday.
   Giving states the authority to govern union contracts ``would be
a threat to collective bargaining,'' said Charles C. Jackson, a
Chicago attorney representing the Norge Division of Magic Chef Inc.
   Federal laws regulating collective bargaining agreements provide
for arbitration to resolve unfair labor practices.
   But the lawyer for an Illinois woman fired by Norge said federal
law never was intended to thwart state statutes prohibiting
retaliatory firings.
   ``If this were (not) true, all states' rights could be channeled
away by arbitration,'' lawyer Paul Alan Levy contended.
   The Supreme Court agreed to weigh both arguments before ruling _
probably in July _ in the case of Jonna Lingle, who was fired in
late 1984 from her job at Herrin, Ill.
   The woman had notified Norge that she was injured on the job and
asked the company, under the state workers' compensation law, to
pay her medical bills. Norge fired Mrs. Lingle a week later,
contending she filed a false claim.
   However, her union contract contained a provision protecting
workers from dismissal without just cause, and the union filed a
grievance the day she was fired.
   An arbitrator ruled the firing violated the just-cause provision
and ordered her reinstatement. But before the ruling was issued,
Mrs. Lingle filed a lawsuit contending the dismissal was contrary
to Illinois law.
   The relief available through the courts was greater than what
she could receive through arbitration, which did not include
punitive damages and compensation for lost overtime.
   A U.S. District Court judge threw out her lawsuit, ruling that
the state law was pre-empted by the arbitration remedy available
under federal labor law, and the 7th U.S. Circuit Court upheld the
dismissal in June 1987.
   Levy asked the Supreme Court to overturn the lower-court rulings.
   ``The right of action is available to both union and non-union
employees alike,'' Levy argued. ``If there is any state cause of
action that is independent of a labor agreement, Lingle's case
ought to be one of them.''
   But Jackson said Congress gave states authority to supercede
federal law only on health and safety issues and said the power
does not extend to rules against retaliatory firings.
   ``If independent state laws were enacted that flew in the teeth
of a labor contract, they were pre-empted,'' he said. ``Mrs.
Lingle's claim is exactly what arbitration is all about. This is
why we have collective bargaining agreements.''
   A brief filed on Mrs. Lingle's behalf by the State and Local
Legal Center in Washington said 21 states and the District of
Columbia have laws protecting workers filing workers' compensation
claims.
   It identified the states as California, Connecticut, Hawaii,
Illinois, Louisiana, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Missouri,
Montana, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma,
Oregon, South Carolina, Texas, Virginia, Washington and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
