<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel canceled an
appearance here after learning his fee would come from a grant by a
conservative publisher once accused of being a South African agent.
   The Nazi concentration camp survivor had been scheduled as a
speaker today at the John McGoff Distinguished Lecture Series at
Northern Michigan University.
   But McGoff's alleged links to the South African government and
the university's plan to pay Wiesel's fee from a $300,000 grant
from McGoff brought protests from the school's faculty.
   ``When it comes to apartheid you cannot make compromises,''
Wiesel said in explaining his decision.
