<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New thruout with Bradley endorsement, comments from senator
and Dukakis. ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley today
endorsed the presidential bid of Michael Dukakis, calling the
Massachusetts governor the Democrat's best hope against Republican
front-runner George Bush in November.
   ``Today I endorse Michael Dukakis for president of the United
States,'' Bradley said with the Democratic hopeful by his side. ``I
do so because among the candidates of both parties, he would make
the best president. And among the Democratic candidates, he is the
one who can beat George Bush.''
   Bradley, often mentioned as a possible dark-horse nominee if the
Democratic convention is deadlocked, said Dukakis can defeat the
vice president ``because he is tenacious, innovative, resilient and
disciplined.''
   ``And he has the personal depth and life experience that
embodies the promise of America,'' he said.
   Dukakis, who is expected to draw strong support in the state's
June 7 primary election with the endorsement, welcomed Bradley's
decision.
   ``This is a very important endorsement because it comes from one
of the most respected and one of the most accomplished public
figures in America today.''
   Bradley made the sought-after endorsement in an old railroad
terminal at Liberty State Park, in the shadow of the Statue of
Liberty. The terminal, now a museum, was used at the turn of the
century by immigrants who came through Ellis Island.
   Dukakis' parents came through the New York entry point in 1913.
   Bradley, a second-term senator, has declined repeated calls to
enter the presidential race himself. A former Rhodes scholar and
pro-basketball star who is viewed as one of the Democratic Party's
rising stars, Bradley has said he is not ready to seek the
presidency.
