<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Bradley endorsement of
Dukakis; picks up 7th graf pvs, bgng: Gephardt hammered...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis today picked up the
endorsement of New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, once mentioned as a
possible rival for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   The endorsement came as Dukakis' campaign was under attack from
Democratic and Republican presidential candidates on issues ranging
from trade to Central America.
   Bradley, who for months has fended off suggestions that he would
enter the presidential race if no front-runner emerged, today
called Dukakis the ``candidate who can beat George Bush.''
   ``He can beat George Bush because he is tenacious, innovative,
resilient and disciplined and he has the personal depth and life
experience tht embodies the promise of America,'' Bradley said.
   Dukakis, who appeared with Bradley at a New Jersey park, said
the endorsement came from ``one of the most respected and one of
tghe most accompliched pubblic figures in America today.''
   Meanwhile, Democratic presidential contender Richard Gephardt
today accused Dukakis of talking tough on trade to entice Michigan
voters.
   Bush, too, came under fire for supporting President Reagan's
veto of a major civil rights bill.
   Gephardt, who has staked out Michigan's caucuses on Saturday to
revive his battered presidential campaign, issued a statement today
accusing Dukakis of trying ``to have it both ways.''
   ``He may talk tough on trade in Michigan, but everywhere else he
has opposed tough legislation,'' Gephardt's statement said.
   And Sen. Bob Dole, a candidate for the Republican nomination,
also attacked Dukakis today for failing to stand up to
Soviet-backed subversion in Central America.
   ``He says that the Monroe Doctrine, which has defined America's
security in its own neighborhood for some 200 years, is
`obsolete,''' Dole said of Dukakis. ``He said this country ... has
no choice but to tolerate the existence of Soviet client states
wherever subversion might install them.''
   Gephardt hammered away at Dukakis as a new poll suggested he
trailed the Massachusetts governor by a 2-1 margin in Michigan,
which holds Democratic caucuses on Saturday.
   According to the survey, Dukakis had 35 percent; Jesse Jackson
29 percent; Gephardt 17 percent; Sen. Albert Gore Jr. 6 percent and
Sen. Paul Simon 5 percent, with 9 percent undecided, Detroit
television station WJBK said Tuesday night. The telephone poll of
400 Democratic or independent voters, with a margin of error of 5
percentage points, was taken over the weekend.
   Gephardt, who has made trade a campaign centerpiece, questioned
the sincerity of Dukakis' support for Senate trade legislation,
calling it a ``political ploy'' to win workers' votes in Michigan.
   ``Who is for a tough trade policy? Who is going to be for a
tough trade policy after Michigan?'' Gephardt asked. ``Dick
Gephardt is. ... Mike Dukakis hasn't been, isn't and won't be.''
   But the Dukakis campaign countered with a tape-recorded
interview in which Dukakis praised the Senate trade measure as long
ago as last year.
   ``I think the Senate bill, which is very, very different from
the Gephardt amendment, is sound policy. I would have voted for
it,'' the governor told the Des Moines Register on July 11.
   The Dukakis camp also hinted that if Gephardt keeps up the
accusations, it will strike back. A Dukakis aide, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said: ``Our gun is loaded and ready if any
salvos are fired at us.''
   Dukakis collected endorsements from Connecticut Gov. William
O'Neill and Sen. Christopher Dodd on Tuesday, a week before the
state's primary. O'Neill said he expected Dukakis, who has won in
every New England state so far, would do ``extremely well.''
   Meanwhile, a survey published in today's Washington Post
suggested Dukakis was the only Democrat who could outpoll Bush.
Fifty percent said they would vote for Dukakis in an election held
today and 45 percent said Bush. The newspaper said the survey,
conducted with ABC News, had a margin of error of 4 percentage
points.
   Bush was the chief target of Democrat Gore, who faulted him for
lacking the ``gumption'' to break with Reagan over the president's
veto of a civil rights bill, which Congress overrode Tuesday.
   Gore interrupted his campaigning to fly back to Washington and
vote for the override, as did fellow Democrat Simon.
   ``When push comes to shove the vice president never disagrees
with President Reagan,'' Gore said in Traverse City, Mich. ``He
really has not carved out an identity of his own in this election.''
   Simon hailed the civil rights measure and attacked the White
House for trying to quash it.
   ``It's another indication of the insensitivity of the
administration to women, to people with disabilities, to
minorities,'' Simon said.
   Jackson used the occasion to blast both Reagan and Bush.
   ``When you have a president who vetoes a civil rights act and a
vice president who suports him, there's a leadership gap in
Washington,'' he told an audience at Benton Harbor High School in
Michigan.
   ``Too many lives (were) lost in the struggle for civil rights to
stand on the sideline while those policies are abandoned,'' said
Jackson, a onetime associate of slain civil rights leader Martin
Luther King Jr.
   Bush announced on the eve of the veto vote that he supported the
president, although he said he agreed with the main thrust of the
bill. New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, who had endorsed Bush just hours
before the vice president sided with Reagan, said Tuesday it was
time for Bush to start speaking his mind.
   ``The vice president in this instance should have said publicly
the way he felt. He said instead that he was going to be loyal to
the president,'' Kean said.
   Bush wasn't the only one put on the spot by the veto override.
Bob Dole, who did not vote on Tuesday, said if he were casting the
deciding vote he would have sided with the president. But he
indicated Tuesday night on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' that
otherwise, he would have voted for the override.
   Dole stressed he's not conceding the nomination _ yet _ but said
he wouldn't mind if his wife, Elizabeth, ended up on a ticket with
Bush.
   ``It would be all right with me,'' he said. ``I'd probably get a
car and driver out of it.''
   Mrs. Dole stepped down as transportation secretary to campaign
for her husband.
</TEXT>
