<1ST_LINE>u w AM-GNP     03-23 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GNP,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economy Grew At 4.8 Percent Rate In 1987 Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported Wednesday that the
U.S. economy performed even better than previously thought from
October through December, growing at a robust 4.8 percent rate
which further eased fears of a recession triggered by the October
stock market collapse.
   The Commerce Department said the increase in the gross national
product, the total output of goods and services, was the fastest
advance in almost two years and represented an upward revision from
last month, when the GNP gain was put at a slightly lower 4.5
percent.
   Especially encouraging to economists was the upward revision in
particular sectors. The new GNP report said that both consumer
spending and business investment were not as weak as previously
feared and U.S. export sales were even stronger than originally
reported.
   When the fourth quarter GNP report was first released, many
economists expressed concern because the bulk of the growth came
from production of unsold goods which was occurring at the same
time that consumer spending was falling sharply.
   Many analysts worried that this overhang of excess business
inventories would cause a big drop in factory production and job
layoffs at a time when consumers were already worried about the
impact of the huge 508-point drop in the stock market which
occurred on Oct. 19.
   Some analysts even forecast that a recession would start in
early 1988, caused by weak consumer spending and falling industrial
production.
   But the economic evidence so far this year shows those worries
were overstated. Many analysts, while still looking for
significantly slower growth than last year, are now predicting the
economy will get through this presidential election year without a
downturn.
   ``One thing is clear _ the economy has shrugged off Oct. 19
pretty well,'' said Donald Straszheim, chief economist for Merrill
Lynch. ``We will not have a recession in 1988.''
   The brighter economic outlook is certain to cheer Republicans
campaigning to hold onto the White House. President Reagan,
speaking to a group of business executives Wednesday, boasted that
the country is now in the midst of its longest peacetime economic
recovery with the percentage of the labor force at work at an
all-time high.
   With the new revisions, the economy during 1987 grew 4 percent,
almost double the 2.2 percent increase turned in during 1986 and
the best showing since 1984. This figure measures growth from the
fourth quarter. Averaging all the quarters, the GNP grew 2.9
percent in 1987, identical to 1986.
   The administration is forecasting GNP growth of 2.4 percent this
year, with almost half of that gain expected to come from a further
rise in export sales.
   Private economists, whose original forecasts were well below
that estimate, have been busy revising their own projections upward.
   William Dunkelberg, dean of the business school at Temple
University, said he believed many private economists are still
underestimating economic strength, citing the February unemployment
report, which showed the jobless rate dropping to an 8{ year low of
5.7 percent.
   ``I think the economy is going to look a lot stronger in the
first half of the year than people have been predicting,'' he said.
``We see tremendous strength in the export side of the economy.''
   The 4.8 percent GNP growth in the fourth quarter followed growth
of 4.3 percent in the July-September quarter and was the fastest
quarterly growth rate since an increase of 5.4 percent in the first
three months of 1986.
   The rapid growth occurred without a pick-up in inflation. A
price index tied to the GNP rose at an annual rate of 3.6 percent
in the fourth quarter, little changed from a 3.4 percent third
quarter increase.
   In a second report, the Commerce Department said U.S.
corporations' after-tax profits rose 1.6 percent in the fourth
quarter, closing out a year in which business profits shot up 8.4
percent, reflecting the boom in export sales that boosted the
fortunes of American manufacturing companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
