<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomosexualFunds     03-23 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homosexual Funds,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arts Council Defends Funding of Homosexual Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Council on the Arts, under fire
for funding homosexual-oriented art projects, espouses freedom of
expression and not points of view, chairwoman Kitty Carlisle Hart
said Wednesday.
   ``The process is like democracy,'' the actress told a joint
legislative committee hearing. ``It may not be perfect, but it's
the best thing we've got.''
   Hart was summoned before the Assembly and Senate arts committees
following a New York Post report last week that the council had
provided $7,200 to help pay for a photographic exhibit on
transvestism sponsored by the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force
Fund for Human Dignity.
   Other council grants went to create an archive on gay and
lesbian writers and to fund a feminist magazine with an emphasis on
writing by lesbians.
   Hart, who complained of being put on the ``hot seat,'' said the
council supports a variety of groups in the name of artistic
expression.
   ``We fund art,'' she said. ``We are neutral as far as anyone
else is concerned. We don't fund anyone's point of view.''
   About 100 spectators watched the hearing, with the majority
applauding lawmakers who defended Hart's viewpoint.
   Assemblyman Philip Healy said the arts council should show
``delicacy and discretion'' in how it spends taxpayers' money. He
said he sees ``an element of propaganda creeping in'' with some of
the programs funded.
   ``To have only one side portrayed on any level, be it the war in
Nicaragua or lesbians, shows a lack of judgment,'' Healy said. ``I
don't know if this was an overt act or a mistake. I hope it's a
mistake.''
   Fellow Republican Assemblyman Frank Talomie said the arts
council should have a greater system of checks and balances to
ensure proper funding decisions.
   ``I think there's a concern regarding the public's best
interests and the taxpayers' dollar ... that we have to go back and
justify to our constituents,'' he said.
   Hart said each funding request is reviewed by the arts council
staff and a ``peer group committee'' before it is approved or
turned down by the 20-member council. Council members are appointed
by the governor and serve without salary.
   Mary Hays, the council's executive director, said the council
funded 3,633 different programs last year from 6,000 requests.
   ``I defy you to find any prejudice or imbalance in what we do,''
she said.
</TEXT>
