<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1949EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EPA-NaziData     03-23 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EPA-Nazi Data,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Won't Use Data on Nazi Gas Experiments for Study of Phosgene</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency will not
use data from a Nazi poison-gas experiment on prisoners of war and
will study whether such data should ever be used, an agency
official said Wednesday.
   The decision was prompted by a letter to EPA Administrator Lee
M. Thomas from 20 agency employees, many of them scientists, asking
that the issue be studied and the report in which the data appeared
be put on hold.
   ``We don't need this kind of data,'' was Thomas' response,
according to Craig DeRemer, an assistant to the administrator.
   The gas is phosgene, used as a weapon in World War I and used
today in the production of other chemicals. There is a wealth of
data from animal experiments and other human exposure.
   DeRemer said Thomas was ordering a study of the issue, probably
by the agency's Risk Assessment Forum, an interoffice group that
tries to forge common policies in EPA's programs.
   ``This has not been nailed down yet,'' DeRemer said Wednesday.
   EPA has listed phosgene, which forms hydrochloric acid in the
lungs, among the most toxic 406 chemicals that communities should
consider in disaster planning.
   Small quantities can be deadly since effects may take three or
four hours to appear. The Occupational Safety and Health
Administration permits exposure of only 0.1 part per million over
an eight-hour shift and says 2 ppm represents ``imminent danger to
life or health.''
   The agency is considering whether to add phosgene to the
airborne chemicals it regulates, and as part of that work asked a
consultant to ``validate some computer models,'' DeRemer said. It
was the consultants' report that prompted the letter to Thomas.
   The report of the consultant, ICF-Clement Inc., referred to the
findings of a French military court which tried those responsible
for exposing French prisoners to phosgene, according to one of the
signers of the letter who saw the report, microbiologist Morris
Levin.
   Levin said he believed the consultant found the court report in
its own research, but DeRemer said he understood EPA officials had
called it to the attention of ICF-Clement when they discussed the
work to be performed.
   The ICF-Clement vice president in charge did not immediately
return two telephone calls Wednesday.
   ``Some have suggested that such data, if scientifically sound,
and verifiable, should be used if some `good' to humans can
result,'' the letter to Thomas said. ``Others feel that to use such
data debases us all as a society, gives such experiments legitimacy
and implicitly encourages others, perhaps in less exacting
societies, to perform unethical human `experiments.'''
   His own view, Levin said, had changed in discussions in the
group of 20 from acceptance of use to the belief that such findings
should never be used. The use of radiation data by EPA and others
from the U.S. nuclear bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, Japan, in
1945 is ``not in the same category, but close,'' Levin said.
   The German phosgene results, he said, are ``useless. They had no
proper controls (an untested group used for comparisons) and no
idea what the dose was until halfway through. If anyone had brought
us those results from mice, we would have said, `Do it over.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
