<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paraguay-Prisoner     03-23 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraguay-Prisoner,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Prisoner Freed From Virtual House Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former army captain who was
Paraguay's most famed political prisoner fled virtual house arrest
Wednesday with the help of two opposition leaders and sought asylum
in the Colombian Embassy residence.
   Colombian Ambassador Vicente Ramirez Emiliani told The
Associated Press a diplomatic note had been sent to the Paraguayan
foreign ministry advising that Napoleon Ortigoza had taken refuge
in the residence and asked for political asylum.
   ``The Colombian government will proceed to study the
situation,'' he said, adding that he did not know how long that
might take.
   Hermes Rafael Saguier, a leader of the opposition Authentic
Radical Liberal Party, said he and attorney Felino Amarilla went to
see Ortigoza, 56, at the home where he has been held under armed
guard since completing a 25-year prison sentence for his
involvement in a 1962 slaying and an alleged plot against President
Alfredo Stroessner.
   ``At first the guards wouldn't let us in or let Ortigoza out,''
Saguier said by telephone from the embassy residence.
   ``Then we asked Ortigoza if he was prepared to recover his
freedom and he said `yes,' and we forced our way past the guards
and put him in a car and drove him to the residence of the
Colombian ambassador,'' Saguier said.
   ``The last thing we heard were three or four shots,'' Saguier
added. ``I can't tell you for sure because we were too scared to
listen.''
   Saguier said no one was injured.
   The opposition leader, whose party is a frequent critic of the
34-year-old Stroessner government, said the Colombian residence was
chosen because it is only a block and a half from where Ortigoza
was confined.
   Half a dozen armed police blocked the entrance to the embassy
residence.
   Ortigoza was released from an Asuncion prison on Dec. 19 and
confined in a hotel in San Estanislao, 135 miles northeast of
Asuncion. On Feb. 9, he was taken to Asuncion and confined under
guard in a house belonging to his invalid mother.
   Saguier said he and Amarilla decided to remove Ortigoza from the
home after Attorney General Clotildo Jimenez Benitez told reporters
Tuesday that the Ortigoza case was closed and the former captain
was ``in complete freedom.''
   Questioned about the presence of armed guards at the house, the
attorney general said they had been there to protect Ortigoza and
not restrict him.
   Ortigoza was sentenced to 25 years in prison in 1962 after he
confessed to having participated in the slaying of Army cadet
Alberto Benitez. Also convicted in the case was Sgt. Guillermo
Ovando, who was freed in 1984 after spending 21 years behind bars.
   The former captain, who never was allowed to appear in court in
his own defense, maintains his confession was obtained under
torture.
   Paraguayan human rights leaders have said Ortigoza's
imprisonment was meant by the government to serve as a lesson to
those who might conspire against Stroessner's authoritarian rule.
</TEXT>
