<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-23 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police van's megaphone issued a strange
warning to the crowd of over 100 people hovering around the
Manhattan exit from the Queens Midtown Tunnel early Wednesday.
   ``Do yourself a favor and don't touch the cages.''
   Up from under the river came Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey
Circus' annual three-mile parade of animals as the big top moved
into Madison Square Garden for a six-week run.
   The caged lions and tigers came first, 14 of them in two strands
of cages linked together and pulled by trucks.
   ``Living things in Manhattan that are not people, and are not
cockroaches!'' yelled Amy Slaton, a 30-year-old art critic. ``This
is the happiest night of my life.''
   The crowd roared as the 19 elephants walked out of the tunnel.
The cry went up, ``Wooo-oooo! Elephants! Elephants! Aaaall Right!''
   Richard Dunne, a 37-year-old lawyer from Baltimore, bought his
seat atop one of the elephants in a charity auction.
   ``It was like a gigantic horse,'' Dunne said. ``It's so fresh
for New York. Everyone is smiling and happy, even the cops were
happy.''
   After the elephants came 15 horses, five zebras and six camels.
   Inevitably, the rear was brought up by a Department of
Sanitation street sweeper.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former New Yorker living here was astonished
when a Denver policeman showed up at his front door, apologized and
ripped up a four-point traffic citation he had issued just a day
earlier.
   ``In New York, this just doesn't happen. I couldn't believe
it,'' said Joe Milotta, 34.
   But the action by Patrolman Glen Miller, an eight-year veteran,
didn't surprise Deputy Chief Cliff Stanley.
   ``He has, on more than one occasion, admitted his mistakes,''
Stanley said. ``Police officers are human and we do admit our
mistakes. In fact, we encourage it.''
   Miller said he mistook Milotta's car for a similar vehicle that
used an emergeny lane to avoid morning rush-hour traffic on March 9.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RUSHVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rush County farmer Andy Ariens has a
built-in barometer so accurate it has earned him a countywide
reputation as an ace weather prognosticator.
   ``I told Trudy before we got married, `Now, there's something
you need to understand about me,''' said Ariens, 56. `` `Whenever
there's a storm on the way, I'll go off to bed and I'll just sleep
right through it. I may sleep all afternoon and all night long if
you let me.'''
   Ariens also reads the winds and watches the behavior of animals
and insects to predict Mother Nature's plans. He said if he sees an
ant cover its hole or if cows refuse to graze, he knows it is going
to rain.
   Neighbors say Ariens has a 90 percent accuracy rate. He
correctly predicted the ice storm that coated central Indiana March
3.
   So what's his forecast?
   ``In two weeks, we'll have above-normal temperatures, say around
the first of April,'' Ariens said recently. ``It'll be a wetter
spring than last year, so planting season should be a little
later.''
   The last two weeks of spring will be quite cool with below
normal temperatures, he added.
</TEXT>
