<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deputies-FireGear     03-23 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deputies-Fire Gear,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deputies Gain Entry to House by Dressing as Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The men wore firefighting gear, and a fire
truck was parked on the street, but the ``firefighters'' served a
search warrant and made an arrest on drug charges.
   The men were deputies disguised to trick occupants of the house
into opening the door. It worked, but it made fire officials angry.
   Orange County Fire Chief John Hunt said he didn't know one of
his subordinates had lent the truck, and he said he would not
permit a recurrence.
   ``People could become suspicious that firefighters are really
police, and real firefighters could come under fire,'' he said.
   And Hunt's boss, Deputy County Administrator Phil Brown, said
Tuesday that nobody told the deputy sheriffs they could use the
coats, hats and boots firefighters wear.
   Police officials disagreed.
   ``We're not at all upset about the way we did this. We got two
stolen guns and some drugs off the street,'' said sheriff's
spokesman Randy Means.
   ``I don't think there is any threat to firefighter safety,''
said Sheriff's Sgt. Mike Foreman. ``This was the safest way to
execute the search warrant. It involved us not having to make any
forced entry.''
   The head of the 427-member firefighters' union, Jerry Polk, said
he wouldn't object in some situations, such as those involving
hostages.
   ``Let's say there was a kid in there and the police needed a
decoy to get in. That is within the realm of reasonable judgment,''
Polk said. ``But going into the criminal community is a daily
occurrence the police world deals with. To intermingle the fire
department, which has no protection, well, that's not a very smart
move.''
   Deputies arrested Sammie Battle, 66, on a charge of possession
of cocaine. They said they found less than a fifth of an ounce of
rock cocaine. Also seized were two stolen guns. Battle was released
on bond.
</TEXT>
