<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0692 03-23 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0692,840</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng, `Dukakis flew,' with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with Bradley endorsement, comments from senator and Dukakis.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, fighting to establish himself as the Democratic
presidential front-runner, picked up a key endorsement Wednesday
but also came under fire from rival Richard Gephardt for his trade
views and from Republican Bob Dole for a ``failure of vision'' on
foreign policy.
   New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, once mentioned as a possible
candidate for the Democratic nomination, announced his support for
Dukakis at an old railroad terminal in Jersey City, N.J.
   ``Among the candidates of both parties, he would make the best
president. And among the Democratic candidates he is the one who
can beat George Bush,'' Bradley said with the candidate by his side.
   The senator said Dukakis can defeat the vice president in
November ``because he is tenacious, innovative, resilient and
disciplined.''
   Dukakis, who is expected to draw strong support in the state's
June 7 primary election with the endorsement, called Bradley's
decision ``a very important endorsement because it comes from one
of the most respected and one of the most accomplished public
figures in America today.''
   Dole, setting aside his attacks on Republican rival George Bush,
focused on the Democrats in general and Dukakis in particular in a
foreign policy speech at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies in Washington.
   After the speech, Dole flew to Hartford, Conn., to address the
state legislature, but before he landed, top Connecticut GOP
officials announced their backing of Bush for the presidential
nomination.
   Bush and Dukakis were heavily favored to win most of the
delegates at stake next Tuesday when Connecticut holds its
presidential primary.
   In his Washington speech, Dole said Dukakis ``says that the
Monroe Doctrine, which has defined America's security in its own
neighborhood for some 200 years, is `obsolete.' He said this
country ... has no choice but to tolerate the existence of Soviet
client states wherever subversion might install them.''
   The Kansas senator went on to say that ``what we see on
Democratic side of this presidential campaign is a failure of nerve
as well as a failure of vision.''
   Michigan, which holds Democratic caucuses on Saturday, was the
next major battleground for Dukakis and his rivals, and Gephardt
was hammering away at the Massachusetts governor for allegedly
waffling on trade.
   The Gephardt campaign produced a sheaf of Dukakis quotes
opposing trade legislation and used them to support the Missouri
congressman's contention that Dukakis' support for Senate trade
legislation was a ``political ploy'' to win workers' votes in
Michigan.
   ``The president of the United States today has all the authority
he needs to do something about those unfair trade practices,''
Gephardt quoted Dukakis as saying during a debate last August in
Iowa. ``We don't need more laws or more amendments.''
   Campaigning in Michigan, Gephardt asked, ``Who is for a tough
trade policy? Who is going to be for a tough trade policy after
Michigan? Dick Gephardt is. ... Mike Dukakis hasn't been, isn't and
won't be.''
   The Dukakis campaign produced a tape-recorded interview in which
Dukakis praised the Senate trade measure as long ago as last year.
   ``I think the Senate bill, which is very, very different from
the Gephardt amendment, is sound policy. I would have voted for
it,'' the governor told the Des Moines Register on July 11.
   A new Michigan poll commissioned by Detroit television station
WJBK said Dukakis was leading in the state with 35 percent support.
Jesse Jackson had 29 percent; Gephardt 17 percent; Sen. Albert Gore
Jr. 6 percent and Sen. Paul Simon 5 percent, with 9 percent
undecided.
   Connecticut GOP State Chairman Robert S. Poliner announced his
support for Bush, saying, ``Among Republicans I believe George Bush
has the best chance of winning the presidency in 1988.''
   ``I'm sure that a Connecticut ticket led by George Bush and
(U.S. Sen.) Lowell Weicker will be strongly supported by many
independents and Democrats as well as most Republicans, and will
give Connecticut Republicans a chance to increase our numbers in
Congress and in the state legislature,'' Poliner added, predicting
that Bush would take 25 of the 35 Connecticut delegates at stake in
next week's primary.
   A poll published Wednesday by The Hartford Courant showed Bush
favored by 64 percent of likely GOP voters, while his nearest
rival, Dole, is the choice of 20 percent. The margin of error for
the random sampling of 432 likely Republican voters was 5.5 percent.
   Gore also talked about trade as he toured a giant iron ore
processing plant in Ishpeming, Mich. and said, ``We have to take
steps to remove unfair trade barriers overseas.''
   In London, Democrats living overseas picked a largely
uncommitted delegation to the party's national convention. Dukakis,
who won a non-binding preference poll, picked up a fraction of a
delegate.
   Democrats Abroad send 22 delegates to the convention, where they
will cast nine votes. Nine of those delegates were uncommitted, one
was backing Dukakis.
</TEXT>
