<DOCNO> AP880323-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 2008EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FederalDeadbeats     03-23 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federal Deadbeats,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Businesses Say Federal Agencies Too Slow Paying Their Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate leaders on Wednesday described the
nightmares of doing business with federal agencies that refuse to
pay their bills on time, and pleaded with Congress to crack down on
Washington's bureaucratic deadbeats.
   ``Small businesses cannot afford to carry any customer for an
indefinite period of time, even if it is the U.S. government,''
Joseph A. Schaedel of the National Federation of Independent
Business told a House hearing.
   Kenton Pattie of the International Communications Industries
Association said the Defense Department was more than 19 months
late paying its $1,424.15 bill to a small Virginia supplier, and
didn't pay the delinquent penalty required by law.
   Worse, he said, an Alabama company waited nearly two years
before the Air Force paid the $8,833 due for some playground
equipment, after Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., was enlisted to exert
pressure.
   When the Air Force check finally arrived, the company was
cheated out of $648.21 in interest penalties.
   One contractor, frustrated after waiting three months for the
Navy to pay for a shipment of steel pipe, drove a truck to the main
gate at the Philadelphia naval shipyard and told guards: ``We want
it back!'' The Navy returned the goods, Pattie said.
   An August 1986 report by the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, estimated that 24 percent of all
federal agency bills were unpaid for more than 30 days.
   Members of a House Government Operations subcommittee listened
sympathetically as other legislators and witnesses for small
businesses, industrial contractors and trade associations urged
Congress to close loopholes in the 1982 Prompt Payment Act, which
requires the federal government to pay its bills within 30 days.
   The witnesses endorsed amendments, which the Senate approved
unanimously last October, that would provide a stricter statutory
definition of when a federal agency receives an invoice, which
triggers the 30-day time clock for payment.
   The Senate bill also would set a five-day limit for an agency to
accept or reject a supplier's goods or services; eliminate a 15-day
grace period for payment of late penalties; require automatic
payment of penalties with a double penalty if not paid within 10
days; and prohibit agencies from taking an early-payment discount
after payment is due.
   Raymond S. Wittig of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce said the
government's late payment of bills causes the most damage to small
businesses, which lack large capital funds and depend heavily on
cash flow to finance their operations.
   ``They often do not have the resources to battle the federal
bureaucracy over late or incorrect payments,'' Wittig said. ``As a
result, small businesses concentrate on selling to customers who
pay on time.''
   He added: ``If the government does not pay on time, all
taxpayers and citizens are injured because fewer businesses choose
to sell to the government. This decreased competition raises the
costs of goods and services purchased by the government.''
</TEXT>
