<DOCNO> AP880323-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 2009EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarrowTransplants     03-23 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marrow Transplants,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Raises Hope of Disease Resistance in Marrow Transplant
Recipients
^For release at 6 p.m. EST, time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have triggered
disease-fighting defenses in bone marrow transplant recipients with
an experimental procedure, a scientist said Wednesday.
   The recipients had their immune system defenses raised against
poisons that are produced by tetanus and diphtheria bacteria,
showing they benefited from vaccines given marrow donors a week
before the marrow was harvested, said Albert Donnenberg of Johns
Hopkins University in Baltimore.
   Those diseases are not particular problems in marrow recipients,
but the experiment suggests that a similar process might one day
protect against potentially lethal fungal and viral infections that
do appear in recipients, he said.
   Recipients had to be immunized within 35 days of their marrow
transplants, or else the transferred immunity was lost, he said.
   Donnenberg described results to science writers at a seminar
sponsored by the American Cancer Society.
   Marrow transplants are performed in cases where radiation or
chemotherapy for cancer is powerful enough to destroy a patient's
own marrow. Bone marrow produces the white blood cells of the
immune system, as well as red blood cells and platelets.
   The experiment included 38 recipients who got marrow from
immunized donors that was then treated with a technique designed to
prevent graft-versus-host disease. This is a potentially fatal
complication in which immune system cells from transplanted marrow
attack the recipient's body.
   The technique uses a centrifuge to strip the marrow of about 99
percent of the white blood cells called lymphocytes that cause
graft-versus-host disease.
   The experiment, designed to look for side effects rather than
effectiveness, found the technique did little to reduce the
incidence of the disease. But it did appear to reduce the number of
moderate to severe cases in comparison to standard experience with
non-treated marrow, Donnenberg said.
   The transfer of vaccine effects from donor to recipient occurred
because the processing of the marrow enriched it, in the
lymphocytes remaining, with a ``memory'' for the vaccine,
Donnenberg said.
   Such transfer has been shown before, said David Golde, chief of
hematology and oncology at the University of California, Los
Angeles, School of Medicine.
   A key research problem now is how to retain some
disease-fighting capability in marrow recipients but not enough to
trigger graft-versus-host disease, he said in a telephone interview.
   Another study reported at the meeting found that cancer patients
whose marrow had been destroyed by therapy regained marrow function
after injections of their own blood cells.
   Such injections may allow aggressive cancer treatment in
patients who cannot get marrow transplants or store some of their
own marrow for use after cancer treatment, said Margaret Kessinger
of the University of Nebraska College of Medicine in Omaha.
   Marrow transplant experts said the technique's near-term
usefulness would be limited, but that it may have potential for
wider use.
   Kessinger said the experimental technique begins with extracting
white blood cells from a patient's blood.
   The goal is to harvest a kind of cell called the pluripotent
stem cell, which essentially replaces lost bone marrow.
   Kessinger described a study of 26 patients who went through that
procedure and received the injections of blood cells, rather than
marrow, after cancer therapy.
   In comparison to 83 patients whose marrow had been harvested by
conventional means and later returned, the experimental group first
showed white cells in the blood three days sooner, for an average
of eight days after the procedure, she said.
   Both groups took the same amount of time to recover other marrow
function, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
