<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Vandals-CoonDogs     03-23 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vandals-Coon Dogs,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Damage Reported At Coon Dog Graveyard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREEDOM HILLS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's only coon dog graveyard
may need the help of some patrol hounds to keep vandals at bay.
   Caretakers of the Key Underwood Coon Dog Memorial Graveyard in
northwest Alabama say vandals have damaged the unique tombstones
and littered the tourist attraction with beer and soda cans, the
Florence TimesDaily reported Sunday.
   ``It used to happen just once in a while,'' William O. Bolton of
Russellville, secretary-treasurer of the Tennessee Valley Coon
Hunters Association, told the newspaper. ``But it's been happening
more frequently lately.''
   Underwood started the graveyard when he buried his coon dog
Troop on the 10-acre site in 1937. Many of the graves are marked
with elaborate epitaphs, stones with statues of dogs or wooden
crosses.
   ``I just think some people are jealous for some reason,'' said
Bolton. ``I think they go out there and drink beer and smoke pot,
and I guess they want to do something bad before they leave.''
   Erecting a tall fence around the graveyard, as some people have
suggested, is not a solution because it would discourage visitors,
he said.
</TEXT>
