<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest Bjt   03-23 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, Bjt,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Rejects Armenian Campaign For Annexation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin on Wednesday rejected demands by
Armenians who want to control an area of neighboring Azerbaijan,
and it threatened to crack down on Armenian activists who cause
further ethnic unrest.
   The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the country's highest
executive body, did not directly address Armenian demands to annex
the Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan. But it made it clear
that the government would not bend to pressure to change internal
borders.
   At least 32 people were killed in riots after Armenians demanded
that the predominantly Armenian section of Azerbaijan be united
with Armenia. Aremenians are mostly Christian while the Azeris are
mostly Moslem.
   In what appeared to be the Soviet Union's definitive statement
on the territorial dispute, the Presidium ordered government
ministries to make efforts to improve ``the economic, social and
cultural development of the Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous Region.''
   Armenian activists have said such efforts would not meet their
demands.
   The meeting, attended by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
President Andrei A. Gromyko and other senior officials, was held
after carefully orchestrated appeals by 13 Soviet other republics.
   A statement carried by the Tass news agency said it was
``intolerable'' to use pressure to ``resolve complicated
national-territorial issues.''
   Such actions can lead to ``unpredictable consequences,'' Tass
said.
   Armenians held a series of large protests in February to demand
that Nagorno-Karabakh, which is three-quarters Armenian, be annexed
from Azerbaijan. Ethnic rioting broke out in the Azerbaijani city
of Sumgait on Feb. 28, and officials said 32 people were killed.
   Armenian activists put the death toll at 78 Armenians, killed by
Azerbaijanis. Most Armenians are Christian, while Azerbaijanis are
predominantly Shiite Moslem.
   The Soviet officials condemned violence that caused loss of life
and also called on Armenian and Azerbaijani officials to ``bring to
strict account those who by their actions destabilize the
situation.''
   That statement appeared to indicate an impending crackdown on
Armenian activists and on those arrested for taking part in
violence.
   In early February, the policy-making Communist Party Central
Committee turned down an appeal by Armenians to annex
Nagorno-Karabakh. But Gorbachev promised in a Feb. 26 speech that
the region's problems would be considered when the Central
Committee meets to discuss problems between the Soviet Union's
nationalities.
   As recently as March 17, Communist Party officials in
Nagorno-Karabakh appealed for permission to join the Armenian
republic.
   Before the government's decision Wednesday, Armenian activists
had been planning a meeting for March 26 to determine their course
of action.
   Wednesday's pronouncement was seen as an attempt to discourage
further protests.
   The Presidium said Armenian and Azerbaijani officials must speak
out against any ``nationalistic or extremist manifestation,''
protect the rights of citizens of all nationalities. It ordered
Armenia, Azerbaijan, the national prosecutor's office and the
Interior Ministry to ensure order.
   The Soviet leadership also demanded that Armenian and
Azerbaijani officials drastically improve their political and
education work to ensure that riots do not happen again.
   The Presidium's pronouncement came at a time when the official
press had started to sharply criticize Armenian activists.
   The activists said 7,000 people turned out in Yerevan on Monday
to protest an article by the Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda
that said the annexation campaign had a ``clear anti-socialist
spirit.''
   Y. Arakyelan, an Armenian correspondent whose name was one of
three attached to the article, later disassociated himself from it.
   At a news conference sponsored by the Soviet Foreign Ministry,
Yulian Bromley, director of the Soviet Union's Institute of Ethnic
Studies, indicated that top government and party officials soon
would establish an apparatus for handling differences between
Soviet republics after many years of pretending they did not exist.
   But he and the institute's deputy director, Solomon Bruk, said
transferring territory from one republic to another would not help
Gorbachev's effort to restructure Soviet society. Bruk said
economic development rather than ethnic differences would be a more
likely reason for any changes in internal borders.
   Earlier Wednesday Moscow authorities sent home an Armenian
activist who had been providing foreign journalists with
information about the unrest.
   Alexander Ogorodnikov, a Moscow religious activist, said Paryur
Arikyan was put on a plane for Yerevan, the Armenian capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
