<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NATO-Sharing     03-23 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Sharing,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says Allies Doing Better in Sharing Defense Burden</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and the NATO allies are doing more to
ensure the free world's security than they get credit for, but the
administration will continue to press them to assume a larger share
of the burden, Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said Wednesday.
   In a 14-page report requested by Congress, Carlucci said, ``I
intend to follow up personally on this issue and to reiterate at
every opportunity the need for progress in improving both allied
defense capabilities and the equity with which the roles, risks and
burdens of the alliance are shared.''
   Carlucci, while promising a more extensive report later this
spring, said it appeared that Japan and eight European countries
might have increased their defense spending by 3 percent or more in
1987 _ matching the NATO goal.
   He identified the eight as Greece, Italy, Luxembourg, Norway,
Spain, Turkey, France and Portugal.
   Only Greece, however, appears to be allocating as much of its
gross national product to defense as the United States ``and there
are substantial variations in the performance among the individual
allies,'' Carlucci wrote.
   ``While some are doing at least their fair share, others are
making a contribution that can best be characterized as mixed, and
a few are doing far less than their fair share,'' he continued.
   ``Progress to date has likewise been mixed, with the good
performers generally making the greatest improvements in their
defense postures while the others fall further behind.''
</TEXT>
