<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GluingClimbers     03-23 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gluing Climbers,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hueco Tanks Reopens to Climbers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUECO TANKS STATE HISTORICAL PARK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have
reopened Hueco Tanks to rock climbers, ending a three-week
moratorium that gave rangers time to remove bolts climbers hammered
into the rock to aid tricky maneuvers.
   Park officials had feared the bolts might have destroyed ancient
Indian rock paintings, but said they found no damage.
   Hours after the moratorium was lifted Friday, park rangers were
fielding calls from as far as Europe.
   ``Hueco Tanks is one of two good winter-climbing spots in the
United States,'' David Cottom, spokesman for the Texas Parks and
Wildlife Department, said Wednesday. ``The world climbing community
is tight-knit; you wouldn't believe how fast word gets around.''
   Officials closed the 860-acre park about 35 miles east of El
Paso to climbers after rangers discovered the steel bolts they said
had been placed mostly by European visitors. Some climbers had even
used epoxy to create handholds and footholds on the sheer rock
faces.
   Climbers often embed bolts into rock to secure safety ropes.
Most climbers use bolts only to halt falls and consider it cheating
to use them as handholds or footholds.
   ``A lot of (bolts) are for safety, but these aren't for
safety,'' said Ranger Bob Parker, pointing at three bolts in the
face of a 30-foot-high boulder. ``Bolts like these are for
acrobatics. That's what we disagree with.''
   Rangers removed 23 bolts and epoxy handholds, and filled the
holes with brown epoxy to blend in with the rock, Parker said.
   Drilling bolts is banned at Hueco Tanks, though rangers have
decided to leave bolts necessary for safety on the many established
routes.
   And park officials plan to call a conference of climbers next
month or next winter to discuss the ethics of bolting _ a hot topic
in climbing circles.
   Parker said he hoped the moratorium and the conference will get
climbers to police themselves and report illegal bolting.
   Park officials want to make sure everyone follows the rules
because the sport is growing fast at Hueco Tanks, Cottom said.
Several hundred climbers from the Americas, Europe and Asia
traveled to Hueco Tanks this winter. A few years ago, most of the
park's climbers were from Texas and New Mexico.
   Hueco Tanks and Joshua Tree National Monument, east of Los
Angeles, are the most popular North American winter climbing sites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
