<HEAD>Assistant State Attorneys Leads Police on High Speed Chase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assistant state prosecutor has been
suspended with pay following claims that she led police on a 90-mph
car chase and was naked from the waist down when stopped.
   Assistant State Attorney Jan Bamping, 32, was charged with
fleeing to elude an officer and improper passing, both
misdemeanors, the Bradenton Herald reported Wednesday.
   Police reports cited by the Herald said Bradenton Beach
Patrolman Ron Robertson stopped Bamping and fellow Assistant State
Attorney Jerry Blevins, 27, a passenger in the car and owner of the
vehicle, at about 1:45 a.m. Sunday after a 1{-mile chase.
   Robertson said Bamping had been drinking, but he didn't order
her from the car to take a roadside sobriety test because she was
naked from the waist down. He said he could see she had ``a tattoo
on the inside of her leg.''
   Robertson said that when he asked Ms. Bamping why she was
partially nude, she became upset and answered that it's ``not
against the law to drive nude.''
   Ms. Bamping could not be reached by phone Wednesday for comment.
   Blevins was fully clothed, Robertson said. He was not charged
and the Herald reported there was no indication he was disciplined.
   Police reports also said Ms. Bamping and Blevins tried to use
their positions as prosecutors to intimidate Robertson, but Blevins
denied that.
   ``I don't think we did anything improper as far as using this
office,'' Blevins told the Herald.
   Chief Assistant State Atorney Mack Futch said he will request
that Gov. Bob Martinez appoint a special prosecutor to handle Ms.
Bamping's case.
   Ms. Bamping was scheduled to appear in traffic court May 11.
