<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0706 03-23 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Bombers Blast Guerrilla Bases in Lebanon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th pvs `One rocket ...' to UPDATE with
statement from Fatah-Revolutionary Council. PICKS up 5th graf pvs
bgng, A base ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli fighter-bombers blasted
Palestinian and Moslem guerrilla bases on the outskirts of Sidon on
Wednesday, destroying at least six in Israel's second
anti-guerrilla air strike in a week.
   Police said four Skyhawks and eight Phantom F-4s roared in at
4:05 p.m. and staged eight dive-bombing and rocketing runs in a
one-hour raid.
   At least five bases manned by guerrillas of terrorist mastermind
Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary Council went up in flames in the
villages of Bekesta, Majdelyoun and Salhiyeh near Sidon's Ein
el-Hilweh refugee camp, police said.
   One rocket struck a guerrilla arms depot in Bekesta, setting off
a two-hour chain of ammunition explosions that demolished the
building, police said.
   In a military communique Fatah-Revolutionary Council claimed the
jets raided only ``one of the organization's positions.'' It vowed
to ``severely strike back against the Zionist enemy's arrogance and
barbarism ... at the adequate time and venue.''
   ``The attacks left a number of our heroic fighters martyred or
wounded. We will announce specific figures in a later communique,''
the statement said. ``This crime will be added to the black record
of the Zionist enemy.''
   A base of the Moscow-oriented Democratic Front for the
Liberation of Palestine also was destroyed as the jets fired 25
rockets and dozens of delayed-action bombs in the area, police
reported.
   They said the warplanes also hit Sidon's power plant, plunging
the city into darkness. Sidon residents watched the raid from
balconies.
   Guerrillas cordoned off the stricken targets after the raid,
preventing police and reporters from getting a casualty figure.
However, police said two boys aged five and 10 were rushed to
Sidon's Hammoud hospital from Bekesta.
   Israel Radio's Hebrew broadcast said explosions in Sidon
prevented Red Cross vehicles from reaching the bombed areas. It
said residents of Sidon and its Palestinian refugee camps closed
their stores and rushed in panic to bomb shelters.
   A communique from the Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine said an unspecified number of Lebanese civilians were
injured in the raid.
   ``The escalation of the enemy's aggression reflects the
deepening crisis engulfing Israel as a result of the continuous
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,''
said the communique, released in Beirut.
   It described the raid as ``the first fruit'' of Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's recent visit to Washington.
   The Israeli command said its planes destroyed buildings used by
guerrillas for storing military hardware and vehicles.
   Police said Israeli gunboats cruised off Sidon, 25 miles south
of Beirut, during and after the raid. It was Israel's fourth into
Lebanon this year.
   The Israelis said all planes returned safely to their bases and
that the pilots reported accurate hits.
   Sidon police said the Israeli pilots released air balloons that
deflected waves of heat-seeking SAM-7 missiles shoulder-fired by
guerrillas.
   A communique issued by the Popular Liberation Army militia of
Sidon's Sunni Moslem Nasserite leader, Mustafa Saad, said its
positions east of the city were also hit by the Israeli jets.
   It charged the air attack was aimed at breaking the
``Lebanese-Palestinian nationalist alliance.''
   Saad's militia, which has controlled Sidon since the 1975
outbreak of Lebanon's civil war, has been allied with Yasser
Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization and maintained close
ties with Abu Nidal's group, which opposes Arafat.
   Thirty-one people were killed and 43 wounded in the previous
Israeli air raids on Lebanon this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
