<DOCNO> AP880323-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 2035EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Charities     03-23 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Charities,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Urged To Allow State Regulations On Fund-Raising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court was urged Wednesday to allow
states to place strict new regulations on professional
organizations that solicit contributions for charities.
   Attorney General Lacy H. Thornburg of North Carolina said the
rules his state seeks to impose would not violate free-speech
rights.
   Professional fund-raisers ``are keeping too much'' of the money,
he said. ``We want it to go back to the charities.''
   But charitable groups said if the North Carolina plan were
adopted nationwide it would severely threaten their ability to
raise money.
   The North Carolina regulations, invalidated by a lower court,
force fund-raisers to tell prospective contributors what percentage
of the money the solicitors raised over the past 12 months had been
used for expenses and the fund-raisers' fees.
   The law also could limit the fees paid by charities to the
professional fund-raisers. A licensing provision of the statute
presumes that in most cases if more than 35 percent of donations
goes for the solicitor's fee, that is unreasonable.
   Errol Copilevitz, an attorney representing professional
fund-raisers and charities, said the law ``creates a real and
present danger of censorship.''
   ``I'm telling you professional representatives will not make
their services available if this regulation is allowed to stand,''
he said.
   Copilevitz particularly challenged the requirement that
solicitors tell a prospective contributor at the outset how much
money goes for expenses. That could cripple fund-raising over the
phone, he said.
   By the time the solicitor provides that information he ``will
have received a dial tone,'' Copilevitz said, adding, ``High costs
are not a measure of fraud or the worth of a charity.''
   The North Carolina law, enacted in 1985, was designed to prevent
fraud and assure that most of the money goes to charities and not
fund-raising costs.
   U.S. District Judge Earl Britt declared the law unconstitutional
in 1986.
   Britt said that without the help of professional solicitors,
many charities might be unable to communicate their views and goals.
   The judge also said that requiring a solicitor to disclose his
track record for the past 12 months ``is not relevant to the
particular solicitation campaign he is involved with at the time.''
   During an hour of Supreme Court arguments Wednesday, the
justices briskly questioned lawyers for both sides. The court is
expected to announce a decision by July.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist compared North Carolina's law
to a state regulation that sets a maximum price on theater tickets.
   Copilevitz said that would be permissible if the purpose was to
make artistic performance more widely available.
   But when Justice Antonin Scalia asked whether a state could
place a ceiling on the cost of a renting a hall for a political
rally, Copilevitz said that would be unconstitutional.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall questioned the authority of states to
tell charities how to allocate their resources.
   ``Could you stop them from throwing away their money?'' he said.
   Thornburg said the charities need such protection. He said a
survey by North Carolina officials showed that from 1980 through
1984 the five largest professional fund-raisers in the state spent
approximately 80 percent of the money they raised on expenses and
their fees.
   The Supreme Court in 1980 and 1984 barred states from limiting
the amount of money charities spend on fund-raising. Thornburg
argued that those rulings do not preclude the type of regulation
North Carolina seeks to impose.
   Many states require fund-raisers to disclose to regulatory
agencies how much is spent on expenses.
   But Copilevitz said North Carolina's plan goes far beyond that.
   He is representing the National Federation of the Blind, the
Optimist Club and professional fund-raisers. Other charities have
joined in urging the court to declare the North Carolina law
unconstitutional.
   The case is Riley vs. National Federal of the Blind, 87-328.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0191 </DOCNO>
