<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Portugal-US     03-23 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portugal-US,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Portugal Asks U.S. For F-16s In Return For Azores Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portugal has asked the United States to
equip its air force with F-16 fighter-bombers to compensate for a
shortfall in U.S. funds for the use of a strategic air base, a
government official said Wednesday.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Lisbon
was seeking substantial U.S. help in modernizing its armed forces.
   The military assistance would offset cuts made by the U.S.
Congress in aid paid for use of the mid-Atlantic Lajes Air Base.
   Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva last month formally requested
a review of the defense agreement under which the United States
uses the submarine-warfare and refuelling base on the Azores
archipelago because of falling U.S. aid to Portugal.
   The request for the F-16s, described as the world's finest
fighter-bombers, was presented to a U.S. military delegation that
visited Lisbon March 1-5, the official said.
   He refused to specify how many F-16s Portugal is seeking but
indicated the number requested in the first phase of negotiations
could approach 50. Washington officials are studying the proposals,
he added.
   The official said Portugal also sought Hawk missiles, combat
helicopters, sophisticated radar equipment, armored personnel
carriers and M-60 combat vehicles from the United States.
   Portugal's request for F-16s comes after neighboring Spain asked
the United States withdraw 74 F-16s from an air base outside
Madrid. There was no indication of where Portugal would station the
planes if they were supplied.
   Cavaco Silva called for a review of the defense agreement after
Congressional cuts caused U.S. aid to Portugal to fall from $208
million in 1985 to $117 million this year.
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci visited Lisbon to try to soothe
Portuguese dissatisfaction. The two countries agreed to set up a
joint task force to examine the posssibilities of supplying
Portugal with surplus U.S. military equipment to make up for the
shortfall in financial assistence.
   Apparently Portugal rejected the offer.
   ``We wanted to take the initiative by informing the United
States of the equipment we need instead of being presented with a
list of available surplus material that we can choose from,'' said
the government official.
   He said the proposals for U.S military equipment supplies were
based on Portugal's needs to modernize its armed forces so that it
could adequately fulfill its defensive role within the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</TEXT>
