<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     03-23 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corruption Scandal Develops Into Major Political Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition parties on Wednesday said
the government must not cover up the growing scandal involving
alleged corruption by the brother of former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   The opposition alleged that corruption by Chun's relatives and
the Saemaul development movement was widespread.
   Saemaul, or New Community, which claims a membership of more
than 5 million community leaders, was formed in 1971 to improve
rural and urban living standards.
   ``We warn the government against minimizing, covering up or
whitewashing the scandal,'' said Park Young-sook, acting president
of the Party for Peace and Democracy. The rival opposition
Reunification Democratic Party also called for an independent
parliamentary probe.
   Kim Tae-ryong, RDP spokesman, also demanded an investigation
into the Ilhae Foundation, a semi-official think tank established
by Chun.
   The government is investigating charges that Saemaul, while
headed by Chun's younger brother, embezzled millions of dollars,
sold patronage and forced donations.
   The former president, who is on a private visit to the United
States, installed his brother, Kyung-hwan, as Saemaul head. Chun
Kyung-hwan resigned in 1987 after being linked to gangsters locked
in a bloody power struggle.
   Many political observers contend the Saemaul probe stemmed from
a power game between President Roh Tae-woo and Chun, with Roh's
supporters working to reduce the former president's power.
   Roh, a former general picked by Chun to succeed him, is widely
thought to be building popular support by proving corruption under
Chun. Roh has promised reforms since he won the country's first
democratic election last December.
   ``The new government faces an unavoidable challenge ... the
burdensome legacy of the old government,'' Don-A Ilbo, an
influential Seoul newspaper, said in a commentary.
   Newspapers said the Saemaul probe could be Roh's efforts to
distance himself from Chun, who tried to retain power. But
governing party officials fear the growing scandal would erode
their chances in National Assembly elections in April.
   The Prosecutor General's office said Wednesday it had questioned
about 50 government and Saemaul officials about allegations of
fraud, embezzlement and influence peddling.
   The prosecutors said Saemaul was found to have diverted some of
an estimated $130 million in funds to profit-oriented projects,
land speculation and other irregular activities.
</TEXT>
