<HEAD>Cuomo Draft Would Harm Democrats, Top Party Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic Party's chances in November
would suffer if a non-candidate such as New York Gov. Mario Cuomo
won the presidential nomination after a deadlocked national
convention, a top party official said Wednesday.
   It would be a difficult situation and there would be
increasingly bad feelings, Lynn Cutler, vice chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, said at a news conference. ``To the
general electorate it might not make any difference at all, but to
the people who have to go out and win the election ... I think it
would be very tough.''
   Cuomo has said much the same thing, but has refused to rule out
accepting a draft if the convention is deadlocked. He has also
declined, as yet, to endorse any of the Democratic candidates.
   ``He's fully aware of the power of his endorsement and what it
means,'' Ms. Cutler said. ``It makes a national statement. Without
question I think it would have a big impact in a place like
California where there's a great deal of affection for the
governor.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Presidential Candidate Offers Jackson Supporters Alternative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lenora Fulani says her presidential campaign
gives blacks and other minorities someplace to go when, she
predicts, Jesse Jackson is denied the Democratic nomination.
   Ms. Fulani, 37, of New York, candidate of the New Alliance
Party, says she is the first black woman presidential candidate to
