<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Glance     03-23 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Glance,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Truce Proposals At a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the key points in truce
proposals by Nicaragua's Sandinista government and the Contra
rebels:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SANDINISTAS
   A cease-fire of up to 90 days during which the Contras would lay
down their weapons and join a ``national reconciliation dialogue.''
   For every rebel who stops fighting, the government would free a
political prisoner considered eligible for release. Nicaragua has
an estimated 3,300 such prisoners.
   Rebels who put down their arms would be free from prosecution
without applying for amnesty and could take part in political life.
They would be permitted to operate uncensored newspapers, magazines
and radio stations, but television would remain a government
monopoly.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CONTRAS
   A 45-day truce, with zones where rebel fighters could await
negotiation of a permanent truce, keeping their weapons. There is
no mention of when the rebels would give up their arms.
   Total amnesty including release of all political prisoners,
return of political exiles, full press freedom, suspension of the
military draft and inclusion of Contras in the Sandinista dialogue
with the domestic opposition.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   VERIFICATION
   The Sandinistas propose an international commission to verify an
end to hostilities. The Contras suggest a commission run by
Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, Roman Catholic archbishop of
Managua, and Joao Baena Soares, secretary-general of the
Organization of American States.
</TEXT>
