<DOCNO> AP880323-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1702EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CaliforniaDrought Bjt   03-23 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-California Drought, Bjt,0854</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Officials Declare Emergency in Water Shortage</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SLT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have declared a water shortage
emergency in the communities east of San Francisco and are warning
they may ration water to 1.1 million customers for the first time
in a decade.
   If a voluntary conservation plan approved by the East Bay
Municipal Utility District on Tuesday fails, the agency may impose
water restrictions of up to 25 percent for homes and businesses in
the burgeoning Alameda and Contra Costa counties from May through
September.
   Rationing measures under consideration include refusing water
hookups to new housing developments, and restricting new or
expanded landscaping, car washing and street washing. Swimming
pools could not be filled after a certain date and lawns could be
watered just two days a week.
   The proposed conservation measures would be the most severe
steps taken by the district since the 1977 drought, when water
customers were charged up to 10 times the normal rate for excessive
water use, district spokesman Gayle Montgomery said Wednesday.
   ``We don't want to make this a Draconian thing, but we do want
to save a lot of water,'' said district General Manager Jerome
Gilbert, at a packed, four-hour public hearing Tuesday.
   From Oct. 1 to March 1, precipitation was 85 percent of normal
statewide, water officials said. That means there's much less snow
in the mountains ready to melt and flow into rivers and reservoirs
this spring.
   State Water Resources Department engineers said last week that
river runoffs from snow melt will average below 60 percent of
normal between April and July statewide, even if spring rainfall is
normal. If rainfall stays sparse, the situation will be even worse.
   At least one farm irrigation district has already declared a
drought emergency and cut back water allotments to its farmers.
   The Turlock Irrigation District, which serves Central Valley
farmers in southern Stanislaus to northern Merced counties, said
farmers will be allotted only about one-fourth their typical water
amount this year.
   ``Without question, we are in a drought situation,'' said
district General Manager Ernest Geddes. ``Even with normal
precipitation for the remainder of the spring, the Tuolumne River
runoff will total no more than 50 percent of the historical
average.''
   In the East Bay Municipal Utility District, Gilbert said
reservoirs that are half-full now could be one-quarter full by
September unless there are major storms during the next two months.
   ``Runoff this year is the second-lowest year on record in our
area and follows a year that was the fourth-worst,'' said Ted Way,
the district's chief engineer. He predicted this year's dry
conditions will become as severe as those in 1977.
   If the dry spells continued into a third year, the effect would
be ``devastating,'' said Montgomery.
   San Francisco, Marin and Santa Clara counties face possible
water shortages next year, but are in better shape than Alameda and
Contra Costa because they have more water sources and have received
more storms.
   At a meeting in Sacramento last week, state water experts
considered whether to declare a drought for the state as a whole,
deciding to take a wait-and-see approach for the time being.
   ``Every day without a storm, the picture gets worse,'' said Jack
Pardee, a snowpack survey engineer with the state Water Resources
Department.
   But Maurice Roos, chief of the department's water supply branch,
said declaration of a drought is premature because even though
river runoff from the mountains is substantially below average,
storage in reservoirs is only slightly below normal in most parts
of the state.
   Water officials aren't the only ones worried about the dry
weather. Fire officials say it could be the sign of an early and
dangerous fire season. During the grim fire season last year,
lightning-spawned blazes blackened nearly a million acres of mostly
forest lands in California.
   ``This is very similar to the weather pattern we saw last year
at this time,'' said Maryn Pitt, assistant director of the state
Department of Forestry. ``It will only further distress the
watershed, and to date already this year we've had 520 fires over
448 acres. Our 90-day forecast (for rain) is below normal through
May.''
   East Bay water district directors will consider specific
rationing proposals April 13, and judging from Tuesday's hearing
the issue threatens to set suburban residents against city dwellers.
   ``I think we should share the pain,'' said Sandy Skaggs, water
board president and a resident of an affluent development in San
Ramon, where suburbanites take their lawns seriously.
   But Danville Mayor Beverly Lane, whose lawn died in the 1977
drought, agreed with landscapers that the area could suffer layoffs
and financial losses if new landscaping was restricted or valuable
grasslands allowed to die.
   ``We are the hot weather part of the district,'' Lane said
Tuesday during four hours of spirited debate by more than 100 city
leaders and landscaping and gardening industry representatives.
``Our needs are different than the cooler parts of the district.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1727EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Northwest-Smoking Bjt   03-23 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northwest-Smoking, Bjt,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Smoking Ban Could Be Risky Move, Some Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a move some analysts called risky, Northwest
Airlines announced Wednesday it will become the first major U.S.
airline to ban smoking on all domestic flights except those to and
from Hawaii.
   The ban by the Minneapolis-based carrier, the nation's
fifth-largest airline, also covers some foreign routes. It goes
beyond federal regulations that go into effect next month for
domestic flights lasting two hours or less.
   The stringent non-smoking policy appears to be aimed at
attracting new passengers but could backfire and cost the carrier
some traffic, some analysts believe.
   ``It does run the risk of some loss of business,'' said James V.
Cammisa, the publisher of Travel Industry Indicators, a New
York-based newsletter. ``I guess they (Northwest officials) really
stuck their neck out.''
   Wall Street seemed unimpressed by Northwest's smoke-free
innovation. The airline's stock closed on the New York Stock
Exchange at $45.75 per share, down 12{ cents from Tuesday.
   The Northwest ban is ``somewhat contentious from a marketing
point of view,'' said Robert Joedicke, an airline analyst for
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``If there is a danger, why try to be a
leader?''
   It is fairly unlikely that the other big U.S. airlines would
match Northwest's policy, creating a financial risk for the
carrier, some observers believe.
   But Northwest says the prohibition is a response to its
passengers' and employees' requests. A.B. ``Sky'' Magary,
Northwest's executive vice president for marketing, told a news
conference in New York that while the policy is not without risk,
``we believe more non-smokers will switch to Northwest than smokers
will leave.''
   He cited a Northwest study showing that nine out of 10
passengers prefer to sit in the no-smoking section of a plane. More
surprisingly, about 30 percent of smokers express the desire for
smoke-free flights, according to the survey.
   The new policy, called ``Northwest Clears the Air,'' will take
effect on April 23 _ the same day as the less restrictive federal
law. It will apply to flights within the contiguous 48 states as
well as flights to and from Alaska, Mexico, Canada, Jamaica and the
Cayman Islands.
   Northwest flights to and from Hawaii and overseas will continue
to offer smoking sections because those flights ``carry a greater
proportion of foreign passengers who feel differently about the
issue,'' the airline said in a statement.
   ``We still have competitors that are handing out cigars to
passengers on board,'' Magary said.
   About 30 percent of Northwest's domestic flights last more than
two hours, and could have kept their smoking sections under the new
federal regulations. The longest flights covered by the smoking ban
are four or five hours, according to the airline.
   Under those rules, passengers who insist on lighting up will
face civil fines of as much as $1,000, and passengers who tamper
with smoke alarms in airplane lavatories will be liable for as much
as $2,000 in penalties.
   Air Canada, which banned smoking on some flights between Canada
and the United States last April, said it has gained customers as a
result of its no-smoking policy. ``It's been very successful,''
said Steve Pisni, a spokesman for the carrier.
   Northwest's announcement drew praise from several quarters,
including officials of the American Cancer Society, the American
Lung Association and the U.S. surgeon general's office, who
participated in the news conference with Magary.
   Rep. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., the prime sponsor of the new
federal non-smoking law, also hailed Northwest's move. He said he
is sending letters to all the other major U.S. carriers, urging
them to follow Northwest's lead.
   ``This action by Northwest just proves what we've been saying
all along: Cleaning up the air in airplanes is a good business
decision and a good health decision,'' Durbin said.
   Some travel agents also praised the new policy, saying many of
their customers have been pressing for a tougher stance.
   ``I think it's a good move ... because the public is the one
that wants it,'' said Jack Bloch, owner of JB's World Travel in New
York.
</TEXT>
