<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ArmsTreaty 1stLd-Writethru a0778 03-23 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0778,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Clears Way for Early Vote on Arms Treaty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Soviet Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: UPDATES throughout with Helms backing off on amendments;
edits to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee cleared
the way Wednesday for an early vote to endorse the new arms
reduction treaty with the Soviet Union after a series of lopsided
tallies against amendments proposed by the pact's chief opponent,
Sen. Jesse Helms.
   Helms, R-N.C., had introduced a series of 36 amendments to the
accord. But he agreed to press for substantive action on just four
of them after Republican and Democratic senators accused him of
obstruction and deliberately engineering a series of delays.
   Committee chairman Claiborne Pell, R-R.I., announced the panel
will vote next Tuesday afternoon on reporting the treaty to the
Senate floor with a favorable recommendation.
   Pell had promised to keep the committee in lengthy session to
dispose of the Helms amendments, none of which had attracted more
than three votes among the 19 committee members.
   Helms's reversal of course came after a morning session of the
panel in which Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., complained: ``We're just
in a delay, stall situation which I find disagreeable.''
   ``If you don't have the votes and just try to overload it with
amendments, that isn't fair,'' Lugar said shortly before the
committee defeated the first of the Helms amendments, 12-3.
   ``I don't know what is the magical effect of racing to get this
thing reported'' to the Senate floor, Helms said at that point.
   Meanwhile, Pell and several other key committee members said the
last major factor complicating Senate consideration of the new
agreement banning U.S. and Soviet medium-range missiles is the
dispute between Congress and the Reagan administration over the
interpretation of treaties.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, seeks to add language to the treaty text declaring the
Senate's understanding that administration testimony about the
contents and impact of the accord is authoritative and binding.
   The dispute stems from the administration's earlier
reinterpretation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty to
permit the deployment of a Star Wars missile defense system which
most arms control treaty experts believed had been effectively
banned.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., told the Senate
on Wednesday he has concluded it will be essential to attach a
reservation or understanding to the pact spelling out the Senate's
position.
   Byrd said that while there have been exchanges of letters on how
the treaty should be interpreted, ``this matter is not going to be
resolved, in my judgment, by any exchange of letters, because a
future administration can say ... `We don't agree with that
interpretation at all.'''
   The initial 12-3 committee vote rejected a Helms amendment which
would have changed the treaty to permit the United States to deploy
a ground-launched cruise missile armed with conventional and not
nuclear explosives.
   Only Sens. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., and Frank Murkowski,
R-Alaska, joined Helms in supporting the amendment.
   Adopting the amendment would mean reopening negotiations with
the Soviets, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said. ``And that would
mean we would plainly not get a treaty anytime soon. So this can
fairly be labled as a killer amendment.''
   He said conventionally armed cruise missiles were included in
the pact because it is impossible to differentiate them from
identical weapons armed with nuclear warheads.
   With the conventionally armed missiles excluded, the treaty
would not be verifiable, Cranston said.
   But Helms said the ban means ``the conventional imbalance in
Europe will be even greater than it is now'' because NATO will lose
a major weapon in the cruise missile.
   However, Helms later relented, the Tuesday vote was set, and the
committee overwhelmingly rejected three amendments, all of which
were described by opponents as having the potential to kill the
treaty by forcing the reopening of negotiations with the Soviets.
   An amendment by Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D ., which would have
delayed implementation of the treaty until negotiations reduced
Soviet surperiority in conventional arms in Europe also was
rejected, 15-2.
   Both Democratic and Republican leaders predict overwhelming
ratification when the treaty reaches the Senate floor and say only
10 or 12 members of the 100-member Senate are likely to vote to
reject it. Ratification requires a two-thirds vote.
</TEXT>
