<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BaptistAlliance     03-23 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baptist Alliance,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Head Of Moderate Group Says Feuding Has Scared Many Baptists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new president of a moderate group of
Southern Baptists said Wednesday the organization has no intention
of forming a separate denomination, but he acknowledged it appears
headed in that direction.
   The Rev. John Thomason of Jackson, Miss., was elected president
Tuesday of the 25,000-member Southern Baptist Alliance, a group of
moderates formed in response to fundamentalist control of the 14.7
million-member Southern Baptist Convention.
   The alliance, which was formed more than a year ago, concluded
its annual meeting here Wednesday.
   While both factions generally are conservative, they disagree on
key issues, including ordination of women and biblical inerrancy,
the view held by fundamentalists that the Bible is the literal
truth.
   The fundamentalists have gained control of the SBC hierarchy
through nine years of electing their presidential candidates.
   During the next year, Thomason said in an interview, he will
``keep pressing the concern of the alliance, to continue sounding
the word about our threatened heritage.''
   While some have accused the alliance of being the nucleus for a
denomination, Thomason said: ``We are not a fringe group, we are
not an avant garde faction of the Southern Baptist Convention. The
great majority of SBA members are denominational loyalists.''
   Thomason acknowledged that the alliance may appear to be headed
toward denominational status because of its publishing activities
and its discussions concerning the possible need for a new seminary
or divinity school.
   ``Whenever we take specific steps like that, we are acting
independently of the institutions of the Southern Baptist
Convention and that gives the appearance of independence, but it is
not our desire to forge a permanent split with the SBC,'' Thomason
said.
   He said the alliance has to be an ``advocate for groups and
causes we feel are disenfranchised. ... If this means acting
independently of the existing agencies and channels of SBC life,
then for the time being, we are willing to do that.''
   Fundamentalists, who oppose ordination of women, say the Bible
is without factual error in historical, scientific and religious
areas. Moderates maintain there is room for interpretation,
especially in non-religious areas.
   Before fundamentalists gained control of the SBC, Thomason said,
there was no ``creedal litmus test'' for appointees. If the
practice continues, ``one by one, we will see our institutions
succumb to creedalism,'' Thomason said.
   Fundamentalists have clear control of Southeastern Baptist
Theological Seminary in Wake Forest, N.C. and the Home Mission
Board in Atlanta.
   R. Randall Lolley resigned last year as president of
Southeastern rather than carry out the board's order that only
Biblical inerrantists be hired as professors. The Home Mission
Board has refused to help pay women ministers.
   Thomason is pastor of the 561-member Northminster Baptist
Church, the third church to join the alliance after its formation
in February 1987. The alliance includes 40 churches in 11 states.
</TEXT>
