<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-IRA-Media     03-23 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-IRA-Media,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Networks Give Police Videotapes of Northern Ireland Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Irish, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's two television networks on Wednesday
gave police unbroadcast videotapes of a mob attack leading up to
the killing of two British soldiers at an IRA funeral procession in
Northern Ireland.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. and Independent Television News
had refused earlier to comply with police demands for the film, on
grounds that doing so would endanger their crews in the British
province.
   On Wednesday night, however, the BBC in Belfast said it gave
police a 49-second videotape from the funeral.
   An Irish Republican Army mob at the procession dragged the two
soldiers from a car Saturday and beat them with iron bars. The
soldiers were hauled away and later found shot to death nearby.
   An announcement from ITN said the commercial network also gave
police untransmitted footage from the funeral in Belfast, the
provincial capital.
   ``Having considered our legal position, we have complied,'' ITN
said. ``The principle of withholding our untransmitted material
remains important to us, but ITN's policy is to observe the law.''
   BBC director Michael Checkland said the network relinquished the
footage in ``response to a legal requirement'' after plainclothes
officers visited its Belfast office.
   ``The BBC has never set itself above the law,'' Checkland said.
``In dealing with this matter, we have been concerned with the
difficult and dangerous position of our crews in Northern Ireland.
I very much hope ... the BBC's future newsgathering in the province
will not be damaged.''
   Both networks had shown the mob attack, but not the killings, in
their regular newscasts. The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the
provincial police, demanded untransmitted film to assist its
investigation.
   Network spokesmen said their untransmitted tapes did not show
the soldiers being shot to death and would be of little help, but
police demanded the material under Britain's antiterrorist
legislation.
   Officials of BBC, ITN and the Irish network RTE had said they
would not release footage that had not been broadcast unless a
court ordered it. RTE said Wednesday the police had not yet made a
formal request.
   All the networks said terrorists had threatened the lives of
employees who covered the funeral, and argued that crews covering
future violence would not be safe if they were thought to be
cooperating with police.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher rejected the networks' argument
that they must maintain an impartial stance in their coverage of
violence.
   ``Either one is on the side of justice or on the side of
terrorism,'' she told Parliament on Tuesday.
   ``I believe everyone, the media included, has a bounden duty to
do everything they can to see that those who perpetrated the
terrible crimes we all saw on TV, which disgusted the whole world,
are brought to justice.''
</TEXT>
