<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 2110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HamadiTrial     03-23 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Says Defendant Admitted West German Abduction</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: El Saheli is full name</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness at Abbas Hamadi's
kidnap trial testified Wednesday that Hamadi confided to a friend
that he was involved in abducting one of two West Germans kidnapped
in Lebanon.
   The Lebanese-born defendant is accused in the separate
kidnappings of the two Germans in January 1987 in a bid to force
the Bonn government to release his brother, Mohammed Hamadi, who is
charged with hijacking a TWA airliner.
   El Saheli, who was hired by West German investigators to listen
in on Abbas Hamadi's wiretapped telephone calls after the
abductions, testified that Abbas Hamadi acknowledged at least one
kidnapping.
   Saheli said a Lebanese friend asked Abbas Hamadi in one
telephone conversation whether he helped kidnap businessman Rudolf
Cordes.
   ``He answered `yes,''' said Saheli.
   But defense attorney Eckhardt Hild told the court his client was
``only bragging to make himself look good'' in the eyes of his
Lebanese friends in West Germany.
   In other testimony Wednesday, Abbas Hamadi said two members of
the extremist pro-Iranian Hezbollah group prevented him from
boarding a plane leaving Beirut just before Cordes was kidnapped on
Jan. 17, 1987.
   Hamadi said an employee of Beirut airport, whom he identified as
``L. Ham Rachan,'' could verify he was forced to miss his flight to
Europe.
   The 29-year-old defendant did not indicate what he thought
Hezbollah's motives might have been.
   West German investigators suspect Hezbollah was involved in the
kidnappings and that Hamadi had links to the group.
   Abbas Hamadi returned to West Germany from Lebanon on Jan. 26,
1987, and was arrested at Frankfurt airport.
   Since his trial began on Jan. 5, Abbas Hamadi has appealed for
the release of Cordes, and has denied any role in the kidnappings.
   West German engineer Alfred Schmidt, abducted in Beirut on Jan.
20, 1987, was released in September.
   Mohammed Hamadi, 23, was arrested at Frankfurt on Jan. 13, 1987,
carrying liquid explosives and forged identification documents.
   West Germany has refused a U.S. extradition request for the
younger Hamadi, but has charged him in connection with the June
1985 hijacking of a TWA airliner in which 39 people were held
hostage 17 days and a U.S. Navy diver was killed.
   Mohammed Hamadi is being held in a Frankfurt prison pending
trial. Abbas Hamadi's trial is to resume on April 5 and a decision
is expected by April 19.
</TEXT>
