<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Zaccaro     03-23 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Zaccaro,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Drug Charge Against John Zaccaro Jr. is Dropped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUTLAND, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has dismissed one of two drug
charges against John Zaccaro Jr., the son of 1984 vice presidential
candidate Geraldine Ferraro.
   District Judge Francis McCaffrey ruled Monday there is
insufficient evidence to support a charge of possession of cocaine
with intent to sell.
   McCaffrey also said defense attorneys cannot claim at trial that
Zaccaro was a victim of selective prosecution because it does not
relate to guilt or innocence.
   Zaccaro was arrested in 1986 in a raid of his home and car while
attending Middlebury College. His trial on a charge of sale of a
regulated drug is scheduled to begin April 4.
   McCaffrey in 1986 had ruled inadmissible eight grams of cocaine
and records of drug transactions seized by police from Zaccaro's
car. The judge said at the time that the search warrant was based
on insufficient evidence.
   Addison County State's Attorney John Quinn argued he could prove
the possession charge based on the observations of undercover state
Trooper Laura Manning.
   But McCaffrey disagreed, saying, ``There is no evidence ... to
show that the other packets observed by Manning contained cocaine.''
</TEXT>
