<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 2112EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Missiles     03-23 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Missiles,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egypt Warns Israel Not To Attack Saudi Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt warned Wednesday it will consider any
Israeli attack on Saudi Arabia's new intermediate-range missile
launchers an attack on Egypt itself. Other Arab nations issued
similar warnings.
   Egypt, the only Arab state that has diplomatic relations with
Israel, accused the Jewish state of violating international laws by
demanding that Saudi Arabia remove the missiles, which are capable
of carrying nuclear warheads and of reaching Israel.
   In Amman, chairman Sharifuddin Pir Zadeh of the Organization of
Islamic Conference said the group also would support Saudi Arabia.
His statement echoed similar declarations of support by Syria and
Jordan, which said they would consider any attack on Saudi Arabia
an attack on them.
   They pledged to help the Saudis militarily if necessary.
   ``I am sending a cable to King Fahd supporting his Moslem
kingdom and our Saudi brothers against the Israeli threats,'' Pir
Zadeh said.
   Pir Zadeh was in the Jordanian capital for a meeting of foreign
ministers of the Islamic Conference. He said conference members
would support the Saudis ``morally and, if necessary, militarily.''
   Saudi Arabia recently acquired Chinese CSS-2 missiles, which
have a range of 2,200 miles. They are capable of being fitted with
nuclear warheads, but the Saudis have denied this will be done.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel said Tuesday that his
country and the United States were ``making efforts to deal with .
.. (the) grave development.'' He did not elaborate.
   Israel radio on Sunday quoted a close Shamir aide, Yossi Ben
Aharon as saying Israel had a reputation of not waiting until
potential dangers became actual ones, apparently a reference to
Israel's 1981 air raid against a nuclear reactor under construction
in Iraq. Shamir said Ben Aharon denied making the statement.
   Egypt warned it will deal with any Israeli attack on Saudi
missile launchers ``strongly and with firmness.''
   Official Cairo television broadcast the warning, attributed to a
responsible source, as the first item of the main evening newscast.
It was later carried by the Middle East News Agency.
   ``Egypt reiterates that it considers any attack on Saudi Arabia
an attack on itself which must be dealt with strongly and with
firmness and the offender will have to bear the responsiblity for
this attack,'' the source was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
