<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WorkerNotice 1stLd-Writethru a0818 03-23 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Worker Notice, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0818,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Senators Delay Bill To Require Notice of Hazardous Work Sites</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with later developments, SUBS 8 new grafs for grafs
8-9 pvs, bgng: ``One amendment ...''; Picks up 10th graf pvs: ``A
similar ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republicans succeeded Wednesday in
delaying any votes on a bill to require the government to warn
millions of workers they risk cancer and other diseases from job
exposure to hazardous substances.
   Democratic supporters of the ``High Risk Occupational Disease
Notificiation and Prevention Act'' were unable to break off lengthy
orations by opponents led by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, aimed a
preventing a vote on the bill.
   In a key test vote, the bill's chief author, Sen. Howard
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, was able to muster only 33 of the 60 Senate
votes necessary to limit further debate to 30 hours.
   The legislation is aimed at what the National Institute of
Occupational Safety and Health says are the one in every four
Americans who have been exposed to carcinogens or other hazardous
substances on the job, most of them unware of it.
   Metzenbaum and other supporters of the bill on Wednesday put
together what he said were ``weakening amendments'' aimed at
diminishing opposition from farmers and small businesses before
making another attempt to limit debate on Thursday.
   Hatch, however, prevented votes on the amendments, as well,
holding control of the Sente floor for hours, but saying he might
allow their consideration on Thursday.
   ``I don't consider this a filibuster,'' Hatch said. ``A
filibuster is reading from the phone book. This is a discussion
that is very necessary. This bill could cost taxpayers and
consumers millions or billions of dollars.''
   Later Wednesday, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of
the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee, substituted the
bill entirely with a new version including several weakening
amendments on which Hatch had been blocking action.
   The new version effectively exempts companies with less than 50
workers and farms from having to continue to pay wages and benefits
for up to a year to workers ordered off the job because of the
danger continued hazardous exposure would raise for them.
   It also puts restrictions on what information from the program
that workers and former workers could use in pursuing liability
suits against employers and places a $250 ceiling on the medical
monitoring expenses that companies would have to pay for each
covered worker.
   ``Do we have a `For Sale' sign on the legislation so that you
keep watering it down until you get enough votes to pass it?''
Hatch asked rhetorically, calling Kennedy's action a
``reprehensible tactic.''
   Democrats admitted that Kennedy's parliamentary maneuver,
although allowed by Senate rules, could be used to keep Repubicans
from offering amendments of their own. But they maintained that was
not the intent.
   Democratic Leader Robert C. Byrd acknowledged the ``unfairness
that has been circumstantially brought about ... with no malicious
intent.''
   Because of that, Byrd said that on Thursday he would vote
against his own motion that was part of a second attempt to bring
an end to the Republican delaying tactics.
   Metzenbaum, attempting to salvage the measure in what appears to
be a swell of opposition to it, said he would urge fellow
supporters to also vote against putting a limit on the GOP delay
tactics.
   A similar bill was passed by the House on a 225-186, largely
party-line vote last October despite vehement opposition from the
Reagan administration.
   Unions have been seeking the legislation for the past four
years, contending the administration effectively had ``defanged''
the Occupational Safety and Health Administration from protecting
workers from hazards.
   Over the past two years, Metzenbaum had succeeded in winning
support for the bill from several trade groups and corporations,
including the Chemical Manufacturers Association, the American
Electronics Association, IBM, General Electric, Occidental
Petroleum and W.R. Grace and Co.
   But hundreds of other business groups, led by the National
Association of Manufacturers and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
remained opposed to the measure in any form.
   Jerry Jasinowki, the NAM's chief economist, called the
legislation a ``ticking time bomb'' that could subject employers up
to billions of dollars in lawsuits each year from workers and
former workers that the government identifies as being at risk to
occupational diseases.
   The bill would set up a panel of seven scientists in the
Department of Health and Human Services to identify hazards and the
groups at risk from exposure to them.
   The National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health would
then be required to send individual notices to between 100,000 and
300,000 individuals every year, and employers would be required to
provide medical monitoring programs for each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
