<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0703 03-23 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0703,0819</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Attacks Freighter, Lobs Missiles At Baghdad</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. reaction to chemical
weapons use and raise references to claims. PICKS up 10th graf pvs
bgng, `The Kuwaiti-bound... SUBS bottom three grafs, ``The
Netherlands ..' with 1 to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran accused Iraq on Wednesday of using
poison gas against civilians and warned it might retaliate with its
own chemical weapons, and the United States urged a U.N. Security
Council protest.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross called the use of
chemical weapons a ``new and tragic escalation'' in the 7{-year-old
war between Iran and Iraq.
   Also Wednesday, Iranian gunboats attacked a Cypriot freighter in
the Persian Gulf, leaving it in flames, and Iran fired six missiles
into Iraqi cities.
   Iraq claimed a number of civilians were killed or wounded by an
Iranian missile fired into Iraq's capital, Baghdad.
   Iranian Prime Minister Hussein Musavi claimed Iraqi troops
killed 5,000 Iraqi Kurds with poison gas last week after their home
villages and towns were ``liberated'' by Iranian troops fighting
with the autonomy-seeking Kurds. He called the use of poison gas
``one of the greatest crimes of the Middle East.''
   ``It depends on international measures taken to stop these Iraqi
crimes,'' Musavi was quoted as saying by Iran's official Islamic
Republic News Agency, monitored in Cyprus.
   Western journalists who toured the affected area in northeast
Iraq and the hospitals where victims were taken corroborated the
claims.
   Iran's War Information Minister Kamal Kharazi said Iran may
retaliate with its own chemical weapons if the U.N. Security
Council does not condemn Iraq for its use of such weapons.
   Iraq has denied using chemical weapons.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross said in Geneva that
it had taken urgent steps to end such attacks and had informed Iran
``of its readiness to provide emergency assistance for the
victims.''
   In Washington, the State Department urged the U.N. Security
Council to mount an international protest.
   ``This incident appears to be a particularly grave violation of
the 1925 Geneva protocol against chemical warfare,'' said spokesman
Charles E. Redman. He said there was also evidence Iran may have
fired chemical artillery shells against Iraq.
   ``We call upon Iran and Iraq to desist immediately from any
further use of chemical weapons, which are an offense to
civilization and humanity,'' Redman said.
   Refering to film footage on American television showing victims
of the alleged attacks, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told
reporters: ``We condemn the use of chemical warfare and gas use by
anybody, anywhere at any time.
   ``I saw, everyone in the administration saw, the same reports
you saw last night. They were horrible, outrageous, disgusting and
should serve as a reminder to all countries of why chemical warfare
should be banned.''
   The Kuwaiti-bound Cypriot freighter, identified as the
34,346-ton Odysseas H, was struck about 10 miles west of the Strait
of Hormuz as it entered the gulf with a shipment of barley from
Tarragona, Spain.
   The master issued a distress call at 4:45 p.m., saying two
gunboats had raided his vessel and set it ablaze, according to
gulf-based shipping executives who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Two salvage tugboats that rushed to the scene brought the flames
under control by nightfall, and there were no reported injuries.
The extent of damage to the cargo was not immediately known.
   About the same time and in the same vicinity, an Iranian frigate
challenged the Saudi Abha, a 42,600-ton vessel laden with motor
vehicles for Saudi Arabia. The vessel, which flies the Singapore
flag, is operated by the national Shipping Co. of Riyadh.
   The sources said that the Saudi Abha was told to wait for an
Iranian boarding party to check the cargo.
   Interception of commercial vessels sailing through the Strait of
Hormuz, the sole entryway to the gulf, is common practice by
Iranian gunboats looking for Iraqi-bound cargo to confiscate.
   Iran has struck nine vessels in the last week.
   The Iraqi News Agency reported that the latest missile lobbed by
Iran at Baghdad crashed at 7:30 a.m. into a residential
neighorhood, ``killing and wounding civilians and destroying
property.''
   It said Iraqi gunners fired a similar projectile into Tehran on
Tuesday.
   The Iranian news agency said five other misiles were fired at
``economic and military centers'' in the Iraqi towns of Basra and
Karnaqin.
   Iraq has fired more than 100 missiles against Iran and Iran has
fired more than 60 at Iraq this month.
   The Netherlands announced that it is planning to withdraw one of
its two mine hunters from the Western European force protecting
commercial shipping in the gulf. Diplomatic sources cited
assessments by Western security analysts that the mine threat has
diminished.
</TEXT>
