<1ST_LINE>u p AM-KennedyChallenger     03-23 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Challenger,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy To Face Unknown Republican In Senate Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little-known, 33-year-old GOP leader will run
against Edward M. Kennedy in the fall for the Senate seat Kennedy
has held without serious challenge since 1962, the Republican state
chairman said Wednesday.
   Joseph Malone of Waltham, executive director of the
Massachusetts GOP, will challenge Kennedy, said party Chairman Ray
Shamie, who himself declined a request from President Reagan last
week that he take on Kennedy a second time.
   The Kennedy campaign insisted the five-term Democrat will ``take
nothing for granted,'' and will wage a statewide grassroots
campaign.
   In Washington, B.J. Cooper, a deputy White House press
secretary, said the White House had no comment on Shamie's decision.
   Shamie aide Charles Manning said that Malone represented a new
generation of Republicans and that as a Catholic of Italian
descent, Malone would be a departure from the Yankee-Protestant
line of New England Republicans.
   Malone will have neither the name recognition nor the cash of
Shamie, who sold a high tech business three years ago for more than
$60 million.
   Kennedy, 56, was first elected for an interim term from 1962 to
1964, filling the seat once held by his brother John. He went on to
victories against a succession of old-line Republicans like George
Cabot Lodge and Josiah Spaulding.
   A 1978 graduate of Harvard College, Malone has helped operate a
family trucking business and also is a partner in family real
estate holdings.
   ``I have devoted 10 years of my life working to help bring back
a two-party system to Massachusetts,'' Malone said in an interview.
``It's important that we have a strong, aggressive campaign in
Massachusetts.''
   State Democratic Party Chairman Chester Atkins said Malone is
too closely tied to Shamie to present himself as a ``new
generation'' Republican.
   ``If the people wouldn't accept the real thing in Ray Shamie, it
will be even harder still for them to accept his understudy,'' he
said.
   Shamie, 67, launched his political career in 1982 by investing
$1.8 million, mostly of his own money, in a Kennedy challenge.
While he lost in a landslide _ 61 percent to 38 percent _ it was
also the best finish by a Republican against Kennedy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
