<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gusty Winds in West; Record Warmth in Michigan, Ohio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow and wind gusting to 89 mph chilled the Northwest on
Wednesday, while the mercury in Michigan and Ohio hit record highs
and most of the rest of the nation had sunny skies.
   Eighteen inches of snow fell overnight across Stevens Pass in
the Oregon Cascades, and a heavy snow warning remained in effect in
the northern Cascades of Oregon during the afternoon. Advisories
for snow also were posted in the Washington Cascades and Olympic
mountains, as well as the southern Cascades of Oregon.
   As the storm system moved eastward, a winter storm warning was
posted for Wednesday night and Thursday in the northern and central
mountains of Colorado.
   Gusts were clocked at 89 mph in Reno, Nev., in the morning, but
no serious damage was reported. In Idaho, winds gusted to 58 miles
at Twin Falls and 54 mph at Idaho Falls, and thunderstorms and hail
also were reported.
   Gale warnings extended along the northern Pacific Coast through
the afternoon.
   Warnings or advisories for high winds were posted from the
Sierra Nevadas of California and much of inland Southern
California, to parts of Washington, Nevada, Arizona, Wyoming and
Colorado.
   It was springtime in Michigan and seemed like summer in Ohio.
The temperature at Lansing, Mich., hit 69, tying the record for the
date, while in Alpena, Mich., the thermometer hit 61, breaking the
record by one degree.
   In southeastern Ohio, Chesapeake reported 79 degrees. The
73-degree mark in Toledo broke a record of 72 set in 1945.
   Rain and occasional thunderstorms continued over the Pacific
Northwest into the afternoon, with snow showers in the Idaho
Panhandle and western Wyoming.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended over western Louisiana.
Afternoon skies were sunny in much of the remainder of the nation.
   There were no reports of measurable snowfall during the six
hours ending at 1 p.m. EST. Heavier rainfall during the period
included 0.37 inch at Newport, Ore., and Olympia, Wash.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 31
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 87 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
The early-morning low for the nation was 3 degrees above zero at
Montpelier, Vt.
   The forecast for Thursday called for snow in the Rockies. Rain,
possibly including severe thunderstorms, was predicted across the
Plains and much of the Missouri, Mississippi and Ohio valleys,
stretching as far as Alabama. There will also be rain in northern
Maine and the northern Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures will be in the upper 30s and 40s in the upper
Great Lakes and Mississippi Valley, the Dakotas, the Rockies, and
northern Maine; in the 50s and 60s from southern Maine across
Maryland, the lower Great Lakes region, the central Mississippi
Valley, middle Plains and the northern half of the Pacific Coast;
the low 80s in western Florida and from western Louisiana across to
southern Arizona, and in the 70s in most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
