<HEAD>Jury Hears Rereading of Internal Injury Testimony</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with jury recessing for the
evening. PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `The jurors ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in the ``preppie murder'' trial of a
man accused of strangling a teen-ager during sex in Central Park
deliberated a seventh day Wednesday, rehearing testimony about the
autopsy on the woman.
   The jury was interested in the internal injuries revealed by the
autopsy performed by Dr. Maria Alandy, associate medical examiner
in New York City. She testified about injuries to Jennifer Levin's
mouth, neck, head and internal organs.
   The jury deliberated until early evening and will return
Thursday morning.
   The jurors apparently were trying to discern how badly Miss
Levin, 18, was beaten and how much physical force it would take to
cause the injuries. A day earlier, their request focused on how
long Miss Levin had to be choked to produce pinpoint hemorrhaging
on her eyelids.
   The prosecution contends Robert Chambers punched Miss Levin
before strangling her in a rage. The defense contends the death was
accidentally caused when he yanked her backward during rough sex,
as Chambers said in a videotaped statement to police.
   After the reading of the testimony, jurors spent several minutes
sitting in the jury box speaking with one another before returning
to deliberations, which is highly unusual.
   Chambers, 21, is accused of second-degree murder in the death of
Miss Levin on Aug. 26, 1986.
   The jury, which got the case last Thursday, could also convict
Chambers of the lesser crimes of first- or second-degree
manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide.
</TEXT>
