<HEAD>Federal Judge From Mississippi Reports To Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EGLIN AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Walter L.
Nixon of Mississippi reported to federal prison Wednesday to begin
serving a five-year sentence for perjury.
   Nixon, 59, is the second federal judge convicted of crimes while
in office. He has refused to step down and continues to draw his
$89,500 annual salary.
   Last week, House Judiciary Chairman Peter W. Rodino Jr., D-N.J.,
introduced a resolution to impeach him.
   Nixon was convicted in 1986 of lying to a grand jury
investigating whether he tried to influence a local drug case
involving the son of man with whom he had business dealings. He was
sentenced to two concurrent five-year terms.
   The U.S. Supreme Court on Jan. 19 refused to review Nixon's
appeal.
   The first federal judge convicted in office, Harry E. Claiborne
of Nevada, was impeached and removed 1{ years ago. He was convicted
of tax evasion.
