<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Pool     03-23 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Pool,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Using New Soviet Bomber In Gulf War, Sources Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Pyle of The Associated Press is a member
of the Pentagon media pool in the Persian Gulf.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By Richard Pyle</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE USS SAMUEL B. ROBERTS IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The
Iraqi air force has begun using a second type of Soviet-built
bomber on its forays against Iranian oil shipping in the Persian
Gulf, U.S. naval officers said Wednesday.
   The supersonic TU-22, a twin-jet aircraft known in NATO's
military lexicon as Blinder, apparently carries only iron bombs
instead of the air-to-surface missiles that are on Iraq's other
attack aircraft in the gulf.
   The U.S. officers, who spoke on condition of not being
identified, also said Blinders operating over the gulf fly at about
450 mph. That is faster than other Iraqi warplanes but less than
the aircraft's top speed of 900 mph.
   One officer said it was possible that the Blinders were flying
training missions to prepare for regular action against Iranian
tankers.
   This guided-missile frigate observed several of the Soviet
bombers in action during a recent 14-day assignment in the northern
gulf.
   The officers wouldn't indicate whether the flights began before
or after a visit to Baghdad by an American military delegation last
month. The meeting was set up to discuss the problem of Iraqi
aircraft flying down the gulf in a manner that appeared to pose a
threat to U.S. warships.
   The talks were known to have dealt with flights by Iraq's
French-built F-1 Mirages and Soviet-made T-16 Badgers, both of
which are armed with anti-ship missiles.
   Many U.S. officers have expressed concern that the flight
patterns of the Iraqi aircraft could lead to another mistaken
attack such as that which devastated the frigate Stark last May 17,
killing 37 of its crew.
   As the Roberts sailed toward the Strait of Hormuz on Tuesday, an
Iraqi warplane ventured further ``down the pipe'' than usual _
posing no threat. But far enough for a call from the ship's combat
information center to interrupt the skipper's dinner.
   The plane veered eastward toward Iran before it reached the
point at which Cmdr. Paul X. Rinn said he would have ordered a
precautionary increase in alert status.
   On Wednesday, the Roberts went to what Rinn called a ``modified
condition zebra,'' an upgrading of damage-control precautions, when
it entered waters about 20 miles from Abu Musa, a small island that
Iran uses as a base for gunboat attacks on gulf shipping.
   U.S. military sources in Washington say Iran has recently begun
installing launch platforms for its Chinese-made Silkworm anti-ship
missiles on the island.
   Rinn, a native New Yorker who now lives in Summerville, S.C.,
told members of a Pentagon news media poll that there has been no
change in Navy procedures around Abu Musa, and there was no
evidence of the Silkworms having been placed on the island.
   ``We've always been careful around Abu Musa because it's a base
for the Iranian speedboats,'' he said.
   Iranian gunboats, on the lookout for war-related materials bound
for archenemy Iraq, were heard conducting their usual challenges of
commercial vessels as to their cargoes and destinations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 2243EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Uganda     03-23 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uganda,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government, Rebel Group Reach Peace Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major rebel group appears ready to sign
a peace agreement drafted during a week of talks in northern
Uganda, the government newspaper and sources said Wednesday.
   Ugandan soldiers and the rebel Uganda People's Democratic Army
have observed a cease-fire since negotiations began last Thursday
at Gulu, a town 170 miles north of Kampala, the government paper
New Vision reported.
   ``We are coming out fully to join the government,'' said Mike
Kilama, chief rebel negotiator. ``We are coming to join hands with
the NRA to work and rebuild our nation.''
   Uganda's army is called the National Resistance Army, the name
Yoweri Museveni gave it during a five-year bush war that gained him
the presidency two years ago.
   A proposal drafted in the negotiations says the army will accept
rebels who are found not to have taken part in atrocities under
previous regimes, sources reported.
   Reports from the sources and in New Vision said the agreement
excludes politicians. Among them are Otema Allimadi, who was prime
minister under former President Milton Obote and directed the rebel
army from London.
   New Vision said the peace agreement was to be signed within days
and the rebels were assembling at Lukome, 8 miles north of Gulu.
   They consist almost entirely of soldiers from the previous
national army, which Museveni's forces drove into southern Sudan at
the end of the civil war. The rebel army began its insurgency in
August 1986.
   Rebel spokesmen say there are 7,000 insurgents, but the
government puts the strength at 3,000. More than half a dozen rebel
groups operate in Uganda, but the Uganda People's Democratic Army
is the most professional.
   Museveni declared a six-month amnesty in which rebels would be
allowed to surrender. It expires at the end of March, and Museveni
said Tuesday he was reluctant to extend it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
