<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 2244EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IBPChairman     03-23 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBP Chairman,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Won't Seek Perjury Charges Against IBP Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee has decided against
seeking perjury charges against the chairman of the nation's
largest meatpacker for testifying falsely last year that only one
set of injury records was kept at its Dakota City, Neb.,
packinghouse.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of the House Government
Operations Committee's subcommittee on employment and housing, said
that although the testimony by IBP Corp. Chairman Robert Peterson
was misleading, the panel will not ask the Justice Department to
prosecute him.
   Peterson, testifying before the panel last May, denied charges
from the United Food and Commercial Workers union that the company
was keeping two sets of injury logs _ one for internal use and the
other to be shown to government inspectors _ at its Dakota City
plant.
   Afterwards, the company sent the subcommittee a 28-page
statement again denying there were two sets of records. Later,
however, Peterson wrote Lantos a letter saying that he had learned
that two sets of logs were in fact kept.
   At a subsequent hearing last September, IBP officials said their
earlier testimony was based on misunderstandings between the
plant's medical director and a vice president of the company.
   ``While some of the explanations offered by top IBP officials
strained credibility or were incongruent and raised serious
questions, there is insufficient evidence to warrant referring the
matter to the Justice Department for perjury proceedings,'' Lantos
said Tuesday.
   He made the statement in presenting the subcommittee's report on
the Occupational Safety and Health Administration's handling of the
IBP case to the full 39-member Government Operations Committee.
   Committee officials said they expect that report to be released
within the next two weeks.
   IBP, then a subsidiary of Occidental Petroleum Co., and the UFCW
were engaged in a bitter lockout turned strike at the Dakota City
plant during the subcommittee's first hearing.
   As the result of proddings from the union, OSHA initiated a
thorough inspection of the plant and subsequently fined IBP more
than $2 million for a series of health, safety and record
violations.
   At the time, it was the largest fine ever levied by OSHA. IBP
has contested the OSHA charges and is appealing the fine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 2246EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     03-23 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Agreement Almost Complete, Except Two Vital Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texts for an Afghan peace settlement have been
sent to lawyers for finishing touches but there still is no
agreement on two essential issues, sources close to the Geneva
negotiations said Wednesday.
   The sources said one question still open was whether the current
Afghan government or another would oversee implementation of the
deal. The other is the future of aid to Afghanistan from the Soviet
Union, which now has an estimated 115,000 soldiers in the country
helping fight Moslem insurgents.
   Moscow and its Communist allies in Kabul say both issues are
outside the scope of the Geneva talks and raising them with a third
country _ Pakistan in this case _ would constitute interference in
Afghanistan's internal affairs.
   Diego Cordovez, the U.N. mediator, was said to be confident a
third problem could be resolved by compromise language. That
problem arose last week when Abdul Wakil, the Afghan foreign
minister, accused Pakistan at a news conference of creating new
``complications'' by reviving an old border dispute.
   It concerns the Durand Line, a boundary between Afghanistan and
British India agreed upon in 1893. It was accepted by Pakistan
after independence in 1947, but Afghanistan claimed an area south
of the line.
   Pakistan's chief negotiator in Geneva, acting Foreign Minister
Zain Noorani, told reporters on the same day Wakil made his
allegations that his delegation ``never raised any question as to
the Pakistani-Afghan border.''
   He said the border was a ``non-issue'' and Pakistan accepts the
passage in the agreements requiring the parties ``to refrain from
violations of the existing internationally recognized boundary
between the two countries.''
   Pakistan acts as spokesman for the Afghan guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
