<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0806 03-23 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0806,0834</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accountant Disputes Mecham's Claim That He Didn't Nead Loan From
Fund</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs with UPDATE with later testimony,
including accountant saying dealership was in deep trouble, picking
up 8th graf pvs, `Donna Carlson...'. DELETES 12th graf pvs, `Asked
by...'., and last 3 grafs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham's auto dealership would
have been overdrawn and unable to meet its payroll if he hadn't
borrowed $80,000 from a state fund, an accountant testified at
Mecham's impeachment trial Wednesday.
   The testimony contradicted Mecham's claim that he didn't need
the money and that he borrowed it in July solely to help the state
earn higher interest than it was receiving on the money.
   An accountant hired by the prosecution to analyze the financial
records of Mecham's company indicated the money was badly needed.
   ``Unless these funds had been paid from the protocol fund,
Mecham Pontiac would have had an overdraft the following Wednesday
in excess of $60,000,'' said Randall Sorensen, referring to the
payday following the loan.
   The Senate is investigating allegations Mecham misused the
funds, which were raised by his inaugural committee but transferred
to the protocol fund because of a state law barring use of such
contributions to pay campaign debts.
   Sorensen took the stand after former Mecham chief of staff James
Colter acknowledged he filled Mecham's request for the $80,000 loan
to his car dealership without checking the company's financial
condition.
   When Sen. Manuel Pena suggested to Colter, who left the Mecham
administration in the fall, that Mecham Pontiac was overencumbered
when the loan was taken, Colter said: ``If that's so, it's a bummer
deal. But it was repaid, so I guess it wasn't a bummer deal.''
   Prosecutor Paul Eckstein noted that Mecham testified before the
House that his company did not need the money to pay the bank for
overdue loans on cars.
   However, Sorensen said Mecham Pontiac paid First Interstate Bank
$81,309 owed for six cars on July 17, 1987 _ the same day that the
$80,000 loan was received.
   On cross-examination, Mecham's lawyer, Jerris Leonard, suggested
that the Mecham car dealership had assets that could have been
converted to cash when needed. But Sorensen said he saw no records
indicating such assets.
   Leonard also said the dealership had a net worth of $4.25
million. But Sorensen said some of the figures he saw indicated
otherwise. He did not elaborate.
   Prosecutors had said they would show that Mecham Pontiac was in
deep financial trouble and ``desperately needed the loan'' to
survive.
   In his statement Tuesday, Leonard said of Mecham's loan: ``The
governor is going to tell you he did it for one purpose and one
purpose only, to try to improve the earnings of the fund.''
   The governor's lawyers had objected vehemently to testimony
about the dealership's financial condition but were overruled.
   Before the trial recessed for the day, former Arizona Attorney
General Jack LaSoto testified that he analyzed state laws relating
to the Mecham loan and found it was improper.
   He said it was clear that money placed in the governor's
protocol fund became public money intended for promoting Arizona's
image.
   Also Wednesday, Mecham's former legislative aide testified she
quit because she was worried that ``people could possibly go to
jail'' if the loan was discovered.
   Donna Carlson, who was the subject of an alleged death threat
investigated earlier in the trial, testified she and other Mecham
staffers believed the fund could be used only to ``promote the
interests of the state of Arizona.''
   In addition to charges of obstructing the investigation of an
alleged threat against Ms. Carlson and of misusing state funds,
Mecham is accused in the impeachment trial of concealing a $350,000
campaign loan.
   Ms. Carlson described a conversation with Colter late last
summer which she said involved both loans.
   ``Mr. Colter was extremely upset,'' said Ms. Carlson. ``He said,
`I don't think the governor understands the magnitude of the debt.'
... He said, `I had to loan him $80,000 out of the protocol fund.'''
   ``I believe I came out of my chair,'' Ms. Carlson said. ``I made
a remark ... that people could possibly go to jail for something
like that.''
   Witnesses have said that Ms. Carlson was the subject of an
alleged death threat just before she was called to testify before a
grand jury about Mecham's campaign finances.
   The first-term Republican governor also faces an April 21
criminal trial on felony charges of concealing the campaign loan.
Mecham, the first U.S. governor to face an impeachment trial in six
decades, also faces a recall election May 17.
   During intensive quizzing by senators, Colter insisted he never
tried to cover up the protocol fund loan to the dealership even
though it was never recorded in the fund's check register.
   ``I'm a poor record-keeper,'' he said.
</TEXT>
