<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ConfiscatedCaviar     03-23 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Confiscated Caviar,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs Confiscates $1 M in Caviar, Arrests Caviar Dealers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs agents seized $1 million worth of caviar in
three states and arrested two men on charges of importing the
delicacy in violation of an embargo on Iranian goods, authorities
said Wednesday.
   About 3,400 pounds of Iranian caviar were flown into Miami in
counterfeit Russian caviar tins and repacked in Iranian tins, said
Customs Service spokesman Michael Sheehan.
   Gerald Stein, 49, of New York City and Patrick Bachelier, 38, of
Miami were charged with violating a 1987 presidential ban on
imports from Iran.
   The caviar was seized March 15 at Caspian Caviar Co. in Miami,
Iron Gate Caviar Co. in New York City and Epicurean International
Inc. in Rockville, Md., Sheehan said.
   ``The caviar was in fact falsely labeled in Western Europe in
order to circumvent the embargo,'' Sheehan said. ``After the cavier
was released by customs, Bachelier would transfer the caviar into
Iranian tins, which he had imported separately.''
   Bachelier, who owns Caspian Caviar, said Wednesday, ``I'm
innocent. It's a mistake.''
   He said he imported some Iranian caviar under a permit issued to
a person he declined to identify. The rest of the caviar was
genuine Russian caviar, he said.
   Stein is president of Iron Gate Products, a wholesaler, and is
author of ``Caviar! Caviar! Caviar!'' A published report last year
said his company supplies Macy's department stores.
   Telephone calls to Iron Gate Products went unanswered Wednesday.
   Stein is scheduled for an appearance in federal court in Miami
on April 5 and Bachelier was arraigned March 16. They face up to 16
years in prison and $150,000 fines if convicted.
</TEXT>
