<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Rape-Lawmaker     03-23 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rape-Lawmaker,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freind Says Pregnancy Doubtful From Rape; Doctors Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Legislature's chief abortion foe said
the odds of a rape victim getting pregnant are ``one in millions
and millions and millions'' because the trauma causes a ``certain
secretion'' that kills sperm.
   Doctors specializing in reproduction dismissed the claim, made
by Republican Rep. Stephen Freind, as nonsense.
   Freind, who made the assertion during an interview on a Hanover
radio station earlier this month, said Tuesday he stands by the
claim and will provide medical documentation to support it in about
a week.
   Gov. Robert P. Casey has said he will sign a bill that requires
victims of rape or incest to report the crimes to be eligible for
government funding of abortions.
   In a debate with Barry Steinhardt of the Philadelphia branch of
the American Civil Liberties Union, Freind said, ``It is almost but
not quite impossible to become pregnant on the basis of rape. The
odds are one in millions and millions and millions. And there is a
physical reason for that.
   ``Rape, obviously, is a traumatic experience,'' he said. ``When
that traumatic experience is undergone, a woman secretes a certain
secretion, which has a tendency to kill sperm.''
   ``There's no basis for that. That's nonsense,'' Dr. Richard
Depp, chairman of the department of obstetrics and gynecology at
Thomas Jefferson University in Philadelphia.
   Dr. Luigi Mastroianni Jr., director of the division of human
reproduction at the Hospital of the University of Pennsylvania in
Philadelphia, said Tuesday: ``Boy. If I could find out what that
(secretion) was, I'd use it as a contraceptive.''
   Mastroianni, a past president of the American Fertility Society,
said: ``There is no such secretion.''
   He said Freind's statements ``reflect a lack of concern for
women who have been victimized by rape'' by dismissing the act as
not having consequence.
   Freind has been trying for years to get strong anti-abortion
laws through the Legislature.
</TEXT>
