<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraPoll     03-23 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Poll,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS-Times Poll Finds Americans Reluctant to Help Contras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Americans believe President Reagan should
not have sent troops to Honduras last week, according to a CBS
News-New York Times poll released Wednesday.
   Thirty-five percent of the participants in the survey conducted
between Friday and Tuesday said the troops should have been sent,
52 percent said they should not have been, and 13 percent said they
did not know.
   The poll asked respondents if they were more concerned about the
United States getting into a war in Honduras or about a Communist
takeover in the area.
   It found that 53 percent were more worried about getting into a
war and 37 percent about a Communist takeover, while 4 percent said
the factors were equal and 2 percent said they were worried about
neither. Four percent said they did not know.
   When asked if President Reagan should pardon Oliver North if he
is convicted of theft, fraud and conspiracy charges in the
Iran-Contra affair, 43 percent said yes, 43 percent said no and 14
percent said they did not know.
   The poll also found that 48 percent of those interviewed did not
think the United States should be giving military aid to the
Contras while 39 percent said the aid should be given and 13
percent said they did not know.
   When asked if Vice President George Bush is hiding something the
public ought to know about the Iran-Contra matter, 51 percent said
he is, 28 percent said he is not and 21 percent said they did not
know.
   A total of 1,654 people were interviewed for the poll, which has
a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percent.
</TEXT>
