<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Politics     03-23 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Politics,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian President Hails Constitutional Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Sarney on Wednesday
hailed the decision to keep the presidential system of government,
but some Brazilians wondered how long Sarney himself would be be
allowed to keep the office.
   Lawmakers writing a new constitution ended a year of political
uncertaintly Tuesday by deciding to have a president, rather than a
prime minister, as chief of government.
   ``It's a victory for the nation. It is not a personal victory,''
said Sarney, who has complained that uncertainty about the
country's political direction was a factor in Brazil's economic and
social ills.
   Sarney told reporters, ``This decision was better for the
country. Congress understood that.''
   Lawmakers decided 344-212 to have a presidential system of
government. Legislators who argued in favor of parliamentarism said
a prime minister was a modern alternative and a protection from
military leaders, who have made it clear they favor a presidential
system.
   Sarney said parliamentarism ``would bring chaos and threaten
democracy,'' an indirect reference to possible government
intervention by the military.
   Lawmakers also voted a five-year term for the presidential
office, another victory for Sarney.
   But whether Sarney can serve that long should be known in about
a month, when lawmakers are to vote on the remaining length of
Sarney's tenure.
   His term likely will be the last item voted on by the 559
legislators rewriting an authoritarian constitution. The present
constitution was handed down without a vote in 1969 by a military
junta that seized power in a 1964 coup. Brazilians haven't voted
for president since 1960.
   The country's leftist faction and most Brazilians, according to
polls, would like to see Sarney's term reduced by one year, from
five to four.
   But some Brazilians said trimming a year off Sarney's term is
harder now, after Congress voted to give the office of president a
five-year term.
   ``It would be hateful to have other presidents with five years
and reduce Sarney's to four,'' said Communications Minister Antonio
Carlos Magalhaes.
   The lawmakers' vote was preceded by heavy lobbying by Sarney and
his supporters.
   Jornal do Brasil, the influential daily of Rio de Janeiro,
condemned the ``methods used'' to obtain victory and criticized
Sarney for not keeping a promise to step down in four years.
   ``The intervention of the government was obscene,'' said Rep.
Ronaldo Cezar Coelho of the Brazilian Democratic Movement Party.
   Indirectly elected in an electoral college election, Sarney was
running mate on a liberal ticket headed by Tancredo Neves. Neves
died before taking office and Sarney became president in March 1985.
   As former leader of the military-backed party, Sarney was a
compromise candidate to appease the outgoing generals.
   The Neves-Sarney team was to be a transitional marriage to
smoothly lead South America's largest country to democracy. But
under three years of Sarney, Brazil has had its highest inflation
rate in history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0233 </DOCNO>
