<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ConstitutionExhibit     03-23 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Constitution Exhibit,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exhibit of U.S. Constitution History Will Be Displayed in Bar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMIDON, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The church was unavailable and the doors on
other buildings are too small, so a traveling exhibit on the U.S.
Constitution will be displayed at the Horse Around Bar when it
reaches town next month.
   ``People are kind of enthused about it,'' said bar owner Galan
Hanson, who added that he was surprised when he was asked to be
host of the display in his building's garage.
   The exhibit on the Constitution's bicentennial, mounted on large
panels that can't be squeezed through an ordinary door frame, is
making the rounds of all 53 counties in North Dakota and is due in
Slope County on April 12-16.
   Folks here say Amidon is believed to be the smallest county seat
in the nation. The 1980 census listed the population as 43, but
Hanson thinks that overstates the case. ``There are 29 people who
live here all the time,'' he said.
   The door-frame problem ruled out Amidon's courthouse and its
school, and the only church in town with big enough doors couldn't
work the state-sponsored exhibit into its schedule.
   ``We came up with the idea that they have large enough doors (at
the Horse Around Bar),'' said Lois Anderson, county superintendent
of schools.
   Hanson's business is a former gas station and auto shop. The
exhibit will be in the shop area, separated by a wall, so visiting
schoolchildren will be spared the sight of anyone downing a brew
while they ponder the Founding Fathers.
   ``We'll just have to move some things around,'' Hanson said.
``I'll have to move my pickup out.''
   The tavern will be the most unusual place the exhibit has been
displayed, said John Schmaltz of the state Department of Public
Instruction, which helped create the exhibit.
   ``We've been booking it primarily in schools, public libraries,
shopping malls and, in some cases, courthouses,'' he said. ``But in
the town of Amidon, it's going to be in the Horse Around Bar.''
</TEXT>
