<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>L. Michael Gray</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L. Michael Gray, a gospel singer who appeared
in Broadway musicals and performed with Stevie Wonder, Phoebe Snow
and Billy Preston, died Saturday of a pulmonary embolism. He was 35.
   Gray began singing gospel songs in Los Angeles church choirs as
a boy. He was the singing voice for the cartoon character ``Fat
Albert.''
   Gray appeared on Broadway in ``Your Arms Too Short to Box With
God'' and the ``The Wiz.'' He also was a back-up singer to Eddie
Kendricks and Connie Stevens.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Bessie Heard</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McKINNEY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bessie Heard, who endowed her hometown
with a wildlife sanctuary and natural science museum, died Tuesday
at age 101.
   More than 40,000 visitors each year come to the Heard Natural
Science Museum and Wildlife Sanctuary, which Miss Heard endowed in
1964. The non-profit museum and sanctuary are funded by the Bessie
Heard Foundation, membership dues, tuition fees, gift shop sales
and contributions.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Jimmy Jacobs</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Jacobs, a handball great, boxing historian
and a central figure in heavyweight champion Mike Tyson's career,
died Wednesday of pneumonia at age 58.
   Jacobs was a 9.8 100-yard dash runner, a championship skeet shot
and a basketball player good enough to be invited to an Olympic
tryout.
   Jacobs became one of the greatest handball players in history,
winning six U.S. Handball Association singles championship and
being part of the USHA championship doubles team four times.
