<BYLINE>Robert McCarney</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert P. McCarney, an anti-establishment
conservative who led several successful drives to cut state taxes,
died Wednesday of pneumonia and heart failure. He was 76.
   McCarney made his first campaign in 1964, when he ran
unsuccessfully for the GOP gubernatorial nomination. He won the
1968 GOP primary but lost in the general election.
   McCarney led referendum drives that overturned tax packages
passed by the Legislature in 1963 and 1965. In 1976, he sponsored a
successful initiative measure that cut the state sales tax from 4
percent to 3 percent. Two years later, he sponsored a measure that
cut state income taxes by a third.
