<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     03-23 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Rebel Leader Calls For Aquino Rebellion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb explosion injured 16 people
Wednesday in a department store in southern Davao City on Mindanao
island and a larger bomb was defused in the same building, police
said.
   The bomb exploded shortly before midnight in a building that
also houses an office of the government's passport bureau, said
police Sgt. Dominado Balicoco.
   He said those hurt were passers-by hit by flying glass. Balicoco
said police found a larger explosive device later in the same
building and defused it.
   It was the second bombing in a major Mindanao island city in two
days. On Tuesday, two air force sergeants were killed when they
tried to defuse bombs found at Andrews Air Force Base in Zamboanga
City, 270 miles west of Davao.
   Police said they did not know who planted the bombs, but there
was speculation Moslem rebels were responsible. Both Davao and
Zamboanga are largely Christian cities, but Mindanao is the
stronghold of the 5 million-strong Moslem minority.
   The leader of the nation's largest Moslem rebel group called on
Wednesday for an uprising against President Corazon Aquino and said
her government was planning ``to resume genocide in our homeland.''
   Nur Misuari, head of the Moro National Liberation Front, claimed
in a telephone interview with radio station DZXL that the
government wanted to wipe out Moslems seeking autonomy on Mindanao
and other southern islands.
   He spoke from Amman, Jordan, where he was attending the annual
meeting of foreign ministers of the 46-nation Organization of
Islamic Conference.
   The government had no immediate comment on Misuari's charge.
   Fighting between Moslem rebels and the government has claimed
more than 50,000 lives since 1976, by official count, but has been
reduced to only occasional skirmishes in recent years.
   The military said eight people were killed Tuesday when gunmen
believed to be from the Moro National Liberation Front attacked a
marine detachment on Basilan island.
   Defense Minister Fidel Ramos predicted less trouble with Moslem
rebels in Mindanao because the Islamic conference rejected the
Moslem group's bid for membership, indicating it considers the
rebellion strictly a Philippine matter.
   But Misauri denied the conference rejected his group's
application.
   Jordan's foreign minister, Taher Masri, the conference chairman,
told reporters Tuesday the group was not qualified for membership.
   ``They are not a state and therefore their status cannot entitle
them to become'' a member, Masri said.
   The Islamic conference has been mediating the Philippine Moslem
conflict since shortly after rebel factions began a secessionist
war on Mindanao and the Sulu island chain in late 1972.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
