<2ND_LINE>AM-Swaggart Radio,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swaggart-Owned Radio Station Must Pay $28,000 in Back Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONROE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Wednesday ruled that a radio station
owned by Jimmy Swaggart Ministries owes $28,000 in back taxes to
the city of Shenandoah.
   Swaggart Ministries, based in Baton Rouge, La., had claimed
KJOJ-FM qualified as a place of worship and was therefore tax
exempt, but city officials said it owed $64,043 in real estate and
personal property taxes from from 1980 to 1987.
   The state District Court jury decided 10-2 that the ministry
should pay $28,000 because only half the building qualifies as a
church. The other half was real estate and leased property, the
jury said.
   Shenandoah City Manager Natalie Kelly said City Council will
consider an appeal.
   Swaggart's ministry has been rocked by allegations Swaggart
hired a prostitute to pose nude for him.
   Michael Darlow, representing the city of Shenandoah, had told
jury: ``What happens if you grant Jimmy Swaggart Ministries a
religious exemption? What if a restaurant opens up and has passages
from the Bible in its menu and says they're a place of religious
worship?''
   ``We have to stop somewhere. I suggest the place to stop is here
and now,'' Darlow said.
   Swaggart Ministries attorney James Bradford argued the ministry
is asking to pay real estate taxes only on the half of the building
not used for the radio station. He said the ministry should receive
a full tax exemption on personal property related to the second
floor of the building, which houses the station.
</TEXT>
