<HEAD>Age Discrimination Suit Settled Out of Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with quote from salesman, attorney for
dealership unavailable. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A used-car salesman fired over what his boss
said were his loud and ugly sport coats said Wednesday he wore a
pink one to sign an agreement settling his age-discrimination suit
against the dealership.
   ``I was going to wear the pink sport coat on the first day of
the trial,'' said 62-year-old Lee Grant, who sued Darby Buick of
Sarasota. Contacted at another used car lot where he now works, he
said, ``I believe I have proved my point.''
   The suit, which had become known in courthouse circles as ``The
Dress of A Salesman,'' was to go to trial in U.S. District Court on
Wednesday.
   Grant's lawyer, Nancy Donnellan, said the terms of the agreement
require that the amount of the settlement be kept secret. The two
sides are awaiting an order by Judge Wendell A. Miles officially
dismissing the suit, she said.
   ``I wanted those sports coats vindicated,'' said Ms. Donnellan.
``They aren't really that bad.''
   Telephone calls Wednesday to the office of William Sizemore,
Darby's attorney, were not returned.
   Grant had claimed he was forced out of his job because of age in
1985, even though with 30 years experience he was the top salesman.
   At the start of 1984, Grant said, the average age of 13 salesmen
at Darby was 50. Between January 1984 and August 1985, he said, the
average had been reduced to 38.
   Sizemore contended Grant was discharged ``based on his
behavior'' at the car lot.
   Grant said he was fired after C. Conrad Darby Jr. had taken over
management the dealership from Darby's father in 1983 and started a
``new image'' campaign. He said he was told to wear sports coats
for a more professional look.
   After forcing Darby to put the policy in writing, Grant said he
bought jackets he described as pale pink and rainbow plaid. The
latter, he said, has every color in it and matches gray slacks or
green, or red or blue.
   Rather than promote the new image, Grant was being stubbon,
Sizemore said in court documents.
   ``One jacket was multicolored ... and the other was a loud
Fuchsia color,'' he said.
   Sizemore said Grant had other iritating habits, such as
catnapping at work. Grant said he only took a few winks, a habit he
acquired when the elder Darby was in control.
</TEXT>
