<1ST_LINE>a a PM-ReligionRoundup Adv25   03-23 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 25,0636</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs March 25, or thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Churches can be effective partners in helping
the poor, but ``we cannot go it alone,'' says Auxiliary Bishop John
H. Ricard of Baltimore.
   Testifying recently for the U.S. Catholic Conference before a
House subcommittee, he said churches and other private groups have
labored valiantly to take up the slack caused by erosion of
government programs.
   But he said the private sector can't substitute for the
``essential responsibility'' of the government.
   Increased church efforts, he said, are ``a desperate attempt to
feed hungry people when others have abandoned their
responsibility,'' but ``we cannot pretend that soup kitchens and
shelters'' are sufficient.
   ``They cannot substitute for a national commitment to end hunger
and invest our common resources to feed the hungry,'' he added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Methodist Commission on Religion
and Race says a nationwide movement to make English the official
language of the United States is a ``new form of racism''
   The Rev. Yolanda Pupo-Ortiz, a commission staff member, said
that on the surface the ``English only'' movement appears harmless,
but ``its real purpose is to make a legal base for discrimination.''
   Supporters of the movement contend that multilingualism
perpetuates divisions. Thirty-two states have introduced
constitutional amendments to recognize English as their official
language.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop Herbert Chilstrom, head of the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, told a meeting of
presidents of Lutheran Collegs:
   ``The first thing you can expect from the church is money. The
second thing you can expect is not much of it.''
   There are 52 Lutheran colleges in the country.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A delegation of Protestant and Roman Catholic
leaders from Mozambique, which suffers from drought, hunger and
brutal civil strife, has appealed to Americans for relief and
development aid.
   ``Anything withheld for political or ideological motives simply
means we are allowing people to die in front of us just because we
are unsure of their political preferences,'' the churchmen said.
   They said an estimated 4.5 million people in Mozambique are
threatened by starvation, that about 100,000 have been killed by
roving anti-government ``bandidos'' and more than 2 million people
displaced as refugees.
</TEXT>
