<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Methodist Commission on Religion
and Race says that a nationwide movement to make English the
official language of the United States is a ``new form of racism''
   The Rev. Yolanda Pupo-Ortiz, a commission staff member, said
that on the surface the ``English only'' movement appears harmless,
but ``its real purpose is to make a legal base for discrimination.''
   Proponents of the movement contend that multilingualism
perpetuates divisions. Thirty-two states have introduced
constitutional amendments to recognize English as their official
language.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Churches can be ``effective partners'' in
helping the poor, but ``we cannot go it alone,'' says Auxiliary
Bishop John H. Ricard of Baltimore.
   Testifying recently for the U.S. Catholic Conference before a
House subcommittee, he said churches and other private groups have
labored valiantly to take up the slack caused by erosion of
government programs.
   But he said the private sector can't substitute for the
``essential responsibility'' of the government.
   Increased church efforts, he said, are ``a desperate attempt to
feed hungry people when others have abandoned their
responsibility,'' but ``we cannot pretend that soup kitchens and
shelters'' are sufficient.
   ``They cannot substitute for a national commitment to end hunger
and invest our common resources to feed the hungry,'' he added.
</TEXT>
