<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0006EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DeltaSuit 1stLd-Writethru f0139 03-23 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Suit, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0139,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Exec's Estate Gets $7.95 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with second jury award in
Florida suit; and to recast to CLARIFY that both man and wife died
in crash. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `We don't...'. ADDS 4 grafs with
detail on second case.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of an IBM executive in a 1985 airplane
crash deprived him of more than $6 million in earnings, according
to a federal jury that awarded $7.95 million to the estates of the
man and his wife.
   Attorneys for Delta Air Lines immediately moved to set aside the
verdict, delivered Monday night after five hours of deliberations
in the case brought by the estate of Philip D. Estridge, 47, of New
Canaan, Conn., and his wife, Mary Ann, who also died in the crash.
   Tuesday, another IBM executive who lost a daughter in the crash,
and claimed his career was damaged by his emotional reaction to
that loss, won a $3.5 million damage judgment against Delta in a
case that was tried in West Palm Beach, Fla. The flight originated
in Fort Lauderdale.
   Attorney Lee Kreindler, who represented the Estridge estate,
said the sum awarded in the New York Case was a record for
compensatory damages in a wrongful-death suit. The breakdown was
$6.25 million for Estridge's loss of earning; $750,000 for loss of
enjoyment of life; and $100,000 for mental anguish.
   For the estate of Mrs. Estridge, the jury awarded $750,000 for
loss of enjoyment of life; and $100,000 for mental anguish. The
couple's three daughters had sought $25 million for Estridge and $5
million for Mrs. Estridge.
   ``We don't think anything could have happened any better, and
we're definitely relieved it's over,'' said Evelyn Eubanks, one of
the daughters. ``It doesn't make it better, but it helps us to live
with it.''
   Estridge, who received much of the credit for moving IBM into
the personal computer market, and his wife were among 137 people
killed when a Lockheed L-1011 crashed on approach at Dallas-Fort
Worth International Airport on Aug. 2, 1985.
   IBM Chairman and Chief Executive John F. Akers testified at the
trial that there was ``a strong possibility'' Estridge would have
become one of the company's six senior executives.
   Those executives make an average of $350,000 per year, with an
additional $150,000 per year in IBM stock which cannot be sold
until retirement. Shortly before his death, Estridge was named
overseer of IBM's worldwide manufacturing operations at a yearly
salary of $240,000.
   Akers also testified there was a competitive market for computer
executives and Estridge could have moved to another company
offering more money.
   Although the trial was held in New York City, the award was
reached under the law of Estridge's home state of Connecticut to
allow for the salary projection figures, Kreindler said.
   Delta lawyer John Sabetta declined to comment on the award, but
asked U.S. District Judge John E. Sprizzo to set the jury award
aside shortly after it was announced. Legal briefs on that motion
are due May 21.
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry referred calls to the company's
insurance carrier, U.S. Aviation Underwriters, and had no other
comment. A U.S. Aviation spokesman, Bob Albert, was in a meeting
and unavailable to comment.
   In the Florida case, a federal jury deliberated less than two
hours before awarding Dennis and Gayle Zarnt of Boca Raton $3.5
million for the death of their 15-year-old daughter, Julie, who
coincidentally was aboard the same flight as the Estridges.
   IBM executives testified in videotaped depositions that the
girl's death left Zarnt, a member of the management team
responsible for the introduction of the original IBM-PC, an
emotional ``basket case'' unable to continue what had been an
outstanding career.
   Delta attorney Howard Barwick, who had argued to the jury that
an award of about $500,000 would be adequate, declined to comment
on the verdict. The Zarnts' attorney, Robert M. Montgomery Jr.,
said he expected Delta would appeal. He had sought $5 million in
damages.
   Much of IBM's development of the personal computer was done at
Boca Raton, and the Estridges had formerly lived there.
</TEXT>
