<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-23 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0536</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher postage rates, including a 25-cent
charge for first-class letters, will take effect April 3, the
Postal Service says.
   The new rates, announced Tuesday, reflect higher costs of
delivering mail, said John L. Griesemer, chairman of the Postal
Service Board of Governors.
   The board set the effective date for the sweeping series of new
rates recommended by the independent Postal Rate Commission earlier
this month. Rates were last changed in February 1985, when the
price of a first-class stamp rose to 22 cents from 20 cents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident stockholders dropped their
opposition to Texaco Inc.'s financial reorganization plan as a
federal judge opened a hearing on whether to implement the proposal.
   Texaco, the nation's third largest oil company, announced
Tuesday that the plan was overwhelmingly supported in a vote by
shareholders. Some 96 percent of the 181 million shares voted
backed the plan, which would allow the company to emerge from
bankruptcy court protection.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Howard Schwartzberg heard comments
on the plan from various parties, and recessed the hearing until
today.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. has sweetened its bid for
Federated Department Stores Inc. and proposed a friendly merger
with the retailer.
   Campeau raised its two-tier, all-cash offer to approximately $73
a share, or $6.53 billion, on Tuesday from $68 a share, or $6.18
billion.
   At the same time, Campeau extended the deadline for expiration
of its offer until midnight EST April 4, when a competing $6.3
billion tender offer by R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. that Federated has
accepted is also due to expire.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co. has offered $1.72
billion to acquire Lucky Stores Inc. of California in a deal that
would create one of the nation's largest supermarket and discount
drug chains.
   The $45-per-share bid announced Tuesday for Lucky Stores came
some 16 months after Lucky derailed a hostile takeover attempt by
New York investor Asher Edelman.
   The latest unsolicited offer sent Lucky's stock soaring by
$14.50 a share to $46.37{ on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black & Decker Corp. has withdrawn its
$77-a-share bid for American Standard Inc., halting the bidding war
over the plumbing giant.
   Tuesday's action permits a $78-a-share leveraged buyout of
American Standard, spearheaded by Kelso & Co. and valued at $2.45
billion, to go forward.
   Under the agreement, Kelso will pay Black & Decker $25 million
for withdrawing its bid, as soon as Kelso begins purchasing stock
under its tender offer or acquires at least 20 percent of American
Standard's shares in any other transaction.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. has rejected a revised cash tender
offer of $56 a share, or about $1.6 billion, from a takeover
company formed by Britain's Brian Beazer and the U.S. investment
firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Koppers Chairman Charles R. Pullin said Tuesday that the
Koppers' board believes remaining independent ``is a superior
alternative to accepting'' the revised offer from Beazer's BNS Inc.
</TEXT>
