<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0525</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Merv Griffin has raised his bid
for hotel and casino operator Resorts International Inc. by $70
million to $295 million.
   The new offer disclosed Tuesday is for $45.73 per share, more
than twice the $22 per share that his rival bidder, real estate
tycoon Donald Trump, is proposing to pay for the portion of the
company he doesn't already own.
   Trump, who is Resorts' chairman, controls 88 percent of the
company's voting power. Trump's lawyer, Jack Nusbaum, said Tuesday
that Trump would be willing to withdraw his own offer for Resorts
under certain conditions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for major durable
goods fell 1.8 percent in February, the government says.
   But analysts said Tuesday that the second consecutive monthly
decline in durable goods orders _ which matched the 1.8 percent
decline in January _ had not shaken their belief that manufacturing
will be a bright spot in the economy this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal fuel-economy standards will cause
thousands of traffic deaths next year by discouraging the use of
safer, larger cars, two researchers say.
   A study released Tuesday by Robert W. Crandall of the Brookings
Institution in Washington and John D. Graham of the Harvard School
of Public Health in Boston said fuel-economy regulation
``inevitably leads to smaller, lighter cars that are inherently
less safe'' than bigger cars.
   Meanwhile, the Transportation Department told Congress that
passenger cars sold in the United States got 28.2 miles per gallon
last year overall, up 0.2 miles per gallon from the previous year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three zeros may mean nothing by themselves, but
leaving them off the end of a number may cost the nation's largest
insurer about $11 million.
   Prudential Insurance Co. of America is offering the payment to
settle claims resulting from a clerical error in which a lien it
held was listed as worth $92,885 instead of $92,885,000.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Howard Buschman III heard closing
arguments on the proposed settlement Tuesday and is expected to
rule within several days.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight states have filed suit accusing
dozens of insurance companies of conspiring to create the liability
insurance crisis, making coverage unavailable or too costly for
many governments and businesses.
   Texas Attorney General Jim Mattox said Tuesday that the suits
alleged that eight American property and casualty insurance
companies, along with other industry representatives, plotted to
create the liability insurance crisis beginning around 1984.
   David Ostwald, a vice president of the Insurance Services
Office, which is named in the suit, called the charges ``unfounded
and meritless.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished narrowly mixed Tuesday as the Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials fell 0.99 point to 2,066.15.
   Bond prices were narrowly mixed and short-term interest rates
edged up.
   The dollar finished mixed against most major currencies.
   Platinum future prices surged, petroleum futures prices finished
mostly higher, wheat and soybean futures prices rose but corn
slipped.
</TEXT>
