<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     03-23 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices have turned mixed in
moderate trading, with crude oil falling sharply on the final day
of trading in the April contract.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for April
delivery of West Texas Intemediate, the benchmark U.S. crude,
settled at $16.09 per 42-gallon barrel Tuesday, down 40 cents from
Monday. The contract had fallen 9 cents on Monday.
   Traders attributed the decline largely to technical factors
stemming from the imminent expiration of the April contract, which
traded for the last time on Tuesday. The May contract for WTI rose
6 cents to $16.37 a barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale heating
oil closed up 0.75 cent at 46.15 cents per gallon, after rising
0.35 cent Monday. Unleaded gasoline, which increased 0.12 cent on
Monday, gained 0.21 cent to 46.32 cents a gallon on Tuesday.
   Richard Redoglia, a trader for Merrill Lynch Energy Futures,
said prices were supported by speculation that a pending weekly
report from the American Petroleum Institute would show a reduction
in crude oil stock levels.
   He said the market generally ignored the cancellation of a
Tuesday news conference by Rilwanu Lukman, president of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, that was expected to
have focused on stabilizing sagging oil prices.
   ``No one expected him to say anything of great importance
anyway,'' Redoglia said.
</TEXT>
