<DOCNO> AP880323-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated Bjt   03-23 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated, Bjt,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campeau Boosts Offer, Proposes Friendly Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Down but not out of its battle for Federated
Department Stores Inc., Campeau Corp. has launched a counterattack:
a sweetened buyout offer and a proposal for a friendly merger.
   Campeau's move on Tuesday appeared to give it back the edge it
recently lost to R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. in the high-stakes campaign
to acquire the Cincinnati-based retailer.
   Campeau raised its two-step, all-cash offer to approximately $73
a share, or $6.53 billion, from $68 a share, or $6.18 billion.
Under the new offer, Campeau said it would pay $82 each for 70.5
million Federated shares and $37 for the remainder of Federated's
89.5 million outstanding shares in a subsequent merger.
   Campeau also extended the expiration of its offer to midnight
EST April 4, when Macy's competing $6.3 billion offer is to expire.
   Campeau, a Toronto-based developer, also proposed to Federated's
board of directors an alternate friendly merger under which it
would pay $73 a share for 70.5 million shares in a tender offer and
$73 for the remaining shares following the merger.
   Federated has agreed to merge with Macy, which is offering
$77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million Federated shares, for a
total of $5.4 billion. Macy would exchange shares in the merged
company and issue convertible debt securities for the remainder of
Federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares.
   Federated stock was up $2.37{ to $69.25 a share in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading Tuesday. Campeau announced its
sweetened offer an hour before the end of the session.
   Campeau had been expected to sweeten its offer or propose a
friendly deal after the company lost two rounds in court to
invalidate Federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense.
   Campeau contended its bid could not go forward while the pill
was in effect, leaving Macy with the upper hand following the court
rulings.
   The defense makes a takeover prohibitively expensive by allowing
Federated shareholders to buy more of the company's stock at a
steep discount.
   It was not immediately clear how a simultaneous expiration of
both offers would affect the application of the pill, over which
Federated has sole discretion.
   ``That's not something we can really comment on at this point,''
said Jim Sluzewski, a Federated spokesman.
   Nancy Raeside, a Campeau spokeswoman, said the company would
continue its legal battle to strike down the defense.
   On Monday, a federal judge rebuffed Campeau's proposal that he
remove the pill in exchange for Campeau extending its tender offer
to expire simultaneously with Macy's offer.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand said the pill would remain in
place at least until Federated makes a final recommendation to its
shareholders, Ms. Raeside said. On Friday, Sand denied Campeau's
request to invalidate the pill.
   Before Sand's ruling, analysts had given Campeau's all-cash
offer the edge over Macy's cash-and-stock bid. But Campeau appeared
to regain the advantage with its sweetened offer, said Edward
Johnson, an analyst with Prescott Ball & Turben Inc.
   Johnson said Federated shareholders likely would jump to take
advantage of the higher price in the first stage of Campeau's
offer. ``It puts Campeau's bid ahead and leaves the ball up to
Macy's,'' he said.
   Macy had no immediate comment on Campeau's move, said Maureen
Milano, a spokeswoman for the retailer.
   Federated spokesman Sluzewski said if the Federated board
received a revised offer from Campeau, the directors would consider
it. He said the board was scheduled to meet this week, but would
not confirm that the revised offer would be on the agenda.
   In a letter to the Federated board, Campeau proposed that a
Campeau-Federated merger be structured along lines similar to the
retailer's agreement with Macy.
   Campeau said it also would continue fighting Federated's
agreement to pay Macy millions of dollars in fees if the
Macy-Federated deal falls through.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0636EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LuckyTakeover Bjt   03-23 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lucky Takeover, Bjt,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeover Target Praised For Management, Marketing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lucky Stores, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucky Stores Inc., a takeover target for
the second time in two years, is highly regarded in the supermarket
industry for its quality management and shrewd marketing practices.
   ``The company is on a roll,'' analyst Jonathan Ziegler of Sutro
& Co. Inc. said Tuesday after American Stores Co. made an
unsolicited $45 a share, $1.72 billion buyout that sent Lucky's
stock soaring.
   ``I think American wants Lucky's management as much they want a
stronger foothold in California,'' Ziegler said.
   Lucky said from its headquarters in Dublin, 30 miles east of San
Francisco, that it was not prepared to comment on the surprise
offer.
   But investors reacted quickly, sending Lucky's stock climbing
$14.50 a share to $46.37{ Tuesday in heavy trading on the New York
Stock Exchange. The rise above American Stores' offer could
indicate speculators believe the bids will go even higher _ some
analysts say $50 a share is not out of the question.
   If successful, the acquisition by Salt Lake City-based American
Stores would create the nation's largest supermarket chain.
   Lucky Stores, the nation's No. 6 grocery retailer, has 480
stores and had $6.4 billion in 1987 sales. American Stores, the
third biggest, has 1,600 stores and $14.1 billion in sales.
   The bid for Lucky came just over a year after takeover
strategist Asher Edelman formally dropped a hostile takeover
attempt, in return for the company's agreement to $2.8 million of
his legal costs.
   Lucky thwarted Edelman partly by selling off non-grocery
divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures that make it
difficult but not impossible for an unwanted suitor to grab the
company.
   ``A lot of people were looking to see how the restructured
Lucky's would wind up,'' said Ron Rotter, an analyst for Morgan,
Olmstead, Kennedy & Gardner in Los Angeles.
   ``They're seeing a very healthy company that got out of its one
link, the Midwest, and is left with very strong market shares in
much of the country,'' he said.
   In its defensive restructuring, Lucky Stores closed its popular
Gemco department stores and sold other non-grocery divisions,
shedding thousands of employees in the process.
   Industry observers say the slimming gave company management the
impetus to make long-needed structural changes that have been
beneficial in the long run.
   The ``poison pill'' anti-takeover measure adopted during the
Edelman battle clash limits the voting power of any shareholder who
acquires more than 10 percent of Lucky's stock.
   Today, the company is a major force in the discount supermarket
business. Its main competitors are Oakland-based Safeway _ the
nation's largest grocery chain _ in Northern California and Von's
and Ralph's in Southern California.
   ``The one thing that makes them (Lucky's) successful is they
have a clearly defined identity as the every-day, low-price
leader,'' said Rotter. ``Even the competition will admit that they
are the king at that.
   ``Other stores are constantly shifting what their identity is,''
Rotter said.
   If successful, American Stores is expected to merge its weaker
Alpha Beta grocery chain in California with Lucky's stores,
according to Ziegler.
   ``I think it makes a lot of sense for American Stores, and
Lucky's management would get a chance to shake up Alpha Beta,'' he
said.
   If the Dublin-based chain fights the bid, its might attempt a
leveraged buyout or to seek a ``white knight'' friendly suitor to
make a more attractive offer. But Lucky Stores, which had been
exploring a possible acquisition of Ralph's and further expansion
in the food retailing business, may not be able to stand on its own
through a second takeover battle, analysts said.
   Until Tuesday, the company's stock had been creeping up
gradually since the October stock market crash. It stood at $35 a
share last Oct. 1, then fell to $21 before recovering to the levels
it held before the American Stores offer.
</TEXT>
