<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ResortsInternational Bjt   03-23 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Resorts International, Bjt,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Says He Would End Resorts Bid If Griffin Doesn't Seek His
Stock</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Resorts-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unexpected twist, real estate developer
Donald Trump has offered to end his bid for Resorts International
Inc. and back a rival offer by entertainer Merv Griffin _ but only
if Griffin agrees only to seek stock with lesser voting rights than
that owned by Trump.
   ``Mr. Trump's position is quite simple,'' his attorney, Jack
Nusbaum of New York said Tuesday. ``If Mr. Griffin wishes to buy
the (other) stock and become Mr. Trump's silent partner, God bless
him.''
   Griffin _ who raised his cash offer for Resorts by $70 million
to $295 million on Tuesday _ quickly rejected Trump's proposal as
``ludicrous,'' said spokesman Mark Gill.
   ``We are trying to buy the entire company,'' Gill quoted Griffin
as saying. ``We aren't interested in fooling around with portions
or in sparring on the board with Mr. Trump.''
   Trump, who is Resorts' chairman, controls 88 percent of the
company's voting power by owning nearly all of its 752,000 Class B
common shares, which have 100 votes each.
   The company also has 5.7 million Class A common shares with one
vote each. Trump owns none of those shares.
   Nusbaum said if Griffin amended his offer to seek only the Class
A stock, Trump would withdraw his bid and recommend that
shareholders accept Griffin's.
   Griffin on raised his cash bid for all of the company's stock to
$45.73 per share, from his initial offer of $35 per share made last
week.
   Trump is offering $22 per share for the Resorts stock he doesn't
already own, principally its Class A shares.
   Resorts' Class A stock price jumped $3.62{ to $32.25 on Tuesday.
That is up from $21.87{ before Griffin began his overtures.
   The entertainer's privately-held investment concern, Griffin
Co., said it decided to boost its offer after spending the weekend
studying Resorts appraisal documents released late Friday by Trump,
a New York-based real estate developer.
   Those documents show a $1.3 billion appraisal of Resorts
properties, including a when-completed value for its luxurious but
troubled Taj Mahal hotel-casino in Atlantic City, N.J.
   Resorts, which is based on North Miami, Fla., has operations in
New Jersey and the Bahamas.
   The documents also say the appraiser would be willing to support
a $550 million bank mortgage loan secured by Resorts. That is the
amount Trump has said will be needed to complete the Taj Mahal,
whose estimated total price has ballooned to $938.5 million
currently from $535 million four years ago.
   A $500 million suit Griffin filed Monday in New York federal
court accused Trump of failing to disclose ``material facts,''
including the $1.3 billion appraisal, to Resorts shareholders in
making his offer. It also accused Trump and Resorts directors of
breaching fiduciary duty by refusing to consider the Griffin offer.
   Because Griffin's offer is contingent on getting the backing of
Trump and Trump has repeatedly said he won't agree to that
condition, Resorts' board has declined to pursue Griffin's
proposal, saying it is moot.
   Griffin's offer also hinges on Trump agreeing to terminate a
five-year management contract worth an estimated $100 million to
operate Resorts' properties. Trump also has spurned that condition.
</TEXT>
