<DOCNO> AP880323-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-Construction     03-23 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Construction,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Construction Companies Want Meeting With U.S. Firms Over
Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese construction companies have proposed a
meeting with their U.S. counterparts to help defuse tension over a
construction trade issue causing serious friction between their
respective governments, according to industry officials.
   Officials of the Japan Federation of Construction Contractors
said Tuesday it sent a letter proposing the meeting in response to
an unofficial approach recently made by the International
Engineering and Construction Industries Council (IECIC) in the
United States.
   The Japanese move came following last week's breakdown in
negotiations over the U.S. demand that Japan allow U.S. companies
to participate in various construction projects in Japan.
   The United States has given Japan two weeks in which to come up
with a satisfactory response, or face retaliation.
   Last week, the Japanese government advised U.S. Commerce
Secretary William Verity that it was ``working hard in order to
present a further substantive offer'' and a fresh round of talks
was expected to start in Washington this week.
   According to officials of the construction federation, the
letter noted the dispute has been escalating and the two nations'
differing viewpoints may have arisen from a ``perception gap.'' The
two trade rganizations should hold a private-sector meeting and
find the ways of cooperating to defuse the tension, the letter
stated.
   Officials said construction companies in other countries had
strong interest in gaining access to the Japanese market, where
projects worth more than 50 trillion yen _ about $393 billion at
current exchange rates _ are undertaken annually.
   The federation last May established a special office to handle
queries from other countries on legal and other procedures for
taking part in construction projects in Japan, and reportedly
received more than 30 queries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AmericanStandard Bjt   03-23 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-American Standard, Bjt,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black & Decker Withdraws American Standard Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hostile suitor Black & Decker Corp. has dropped
its bid for American Standard Inc., allowing the target company's
$2.45 billion leveraged buyout to go forward.
   Black & Decker's announcement Tuesday that it would drop its
months-long pursuit of American Standard followed a bizarre turn of
events that halted trading in the company's stock for several hours
for no apparent reason.
   American Standard agreed last week to a $78 a share leveraged
buyout led by the investment firm Kelso & Co., thwarting the rival
$77 a share, $2.4 billion bid from Black & Decker.
   Under the agreement reached Tuesday with American Standard, the
Towson-based tool and appliance manufacturer withdrew its hostile
tender offer and agreed not to purchase American Standard stock
until Kelso had an opportunity to pursue the leveragd buyout.
   Kelso will pay Black & Decker $25 million for withdrawing its
bid, and Black & Decker reserved the right to mount another
takeover of American Standard if Kelso terminated its offer or
failed to acquire shares by May 2.
   ``Seventy-seven (dollars) was our top price,'' said Barbara
Lucas, a Black & Decker spokeswoman. Ms. Lucas also said Black &
Decker initially had thought Kelso would be unable to finance its
proposal, but tht apparently was not the case.
   An American Standard spokeswoman said the company had no comment
on the agreement.
   Earlier Tuesday, the New York Stock Exchange halted trading in
Black & Decker and American Standard shares for three hours in
anticipation of an announcement by Black & Decker that never
materialized.
   NYSE Vice President Richard Torrenzano said Black & Decker
``initiated a call'' to the exchange and ``shared with us
information concerning the American Standard bid which materially
could affect the price of their stock.''
   But after trading was halted at 10:46 a.m. EST, several
conversations took place between Black & Decker and exchange
officials before it was determined that no announcement was
forthcoming.
   The exchange also conferred with American Standard, ``who
advised us that it knows of no reason why trading in its stock
should not resume,'' Torrenzano said. The exchange resumed trading
trading in both stocks at 1:43 p.m. EST.
   The stock exchange most often halts trading when announcements
that could affect a company's stock price are anticipated.
Typically, however, trading is only suspended for about 30 minutes
while news is being disseminated, Torrenzano said.
   It was unclear immediately whether the unusual turn of events
would provoke an investigation by market regulators such as the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   On the day, American Standard shares dipped 12{ cents to $76.62{
per share on the NYSE. Black & Decker rose 37{ cents to $20 a share.
   Black & Decker made its initial offer of $56 a share in late
January, and sweetened it several times in response to rejections
by American Standard.
   American Standard, a New York-based plumbing and air
conditioning equipment maker, several weeks ago proposed a
defensive recapitalization aimed at making the company a more
expensive takeover target by loading it up with new debt.
   Wall Street analyst Cornelius V. Sewell said the buyout led by
Kelso would leave American Standard with a ``some very heavy debt.''
   ``They will presumably have a negative book value,'' said
Sewell, of Argus Research Corp. in New York.
   Sewell speculated that American Standard was likely to sell its
transportation products division, valued at about $600 million, to
help pay off buyout costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
