<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koppers Rejects Latest Offer From Beazer-Shearson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. has spurned a sweetened $1.6
billion cash buyout offer from British investor Brian Beazer and
the investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and said it still
was pursuing alternative plans to remain independent.
   ``The board continues to believe that the company remaining
independent is a superior alternative to accepting your offer,''
Chairman Charles R. Pullin told Beazer in a letter released Tuesday
by Koppers.
   The Beazer-Shearson group raised its offer on Sunday to $56 per
share from $45 per share for the Pittsburgh construction materials,
paving services and chemicals company.
   Pullin also declined Beazer's invitation to negotiate a friendly
merger.
   Koppers stock declined 50 cents to $57 a share Tuesday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Koppers announced earlier it was considering a recapitalization
plan that might include a special cash dividend to shareholders,
along with equity interest in the recapitalized company. Such a
program would make Koppers a more expensive takeover target because
of the debt it would incur to make the cash payment to shareholders.
   Koppers said two major banks, which it declined to identify,
have offered to arrange $1.125 billion in credit to fund the
recapitalization.
   Koppers has also said it might sell all or part of the building
materials and paving services businesses sought by Beazer.
   The British investor has indicated he might settle for just
those parts of Koppers. Previously, he said he would sell the
chemicals operations if BNS succeeded in the hostile tender offer
it launched March 3.
   BNS holds 1.6 million, or 7.3 percent, of Koppers' outstanding
common shares.
</TEXT>
