<HEAD>Dollar Down In Quiet Trading; Gold Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major currencies in
quiet early trading in Europe today. Gold prices rose.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar closed at 127.15 yen, up 0.08 yen from Tuesday's close. But
later, in London, the dollar was quoted lower at 126.92 yen.
   ``The trading was quiet in the absence of market-affecting news
and notable movements among participants,'' said Ken Iiya of the
Bank of Tokyo in Japan.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.6928 West German marks, down from 1.6935; 1.3940
Swiss francs, down from 1.4015; 5.7540 French francs, unchanged;
1.9003 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9015; 1,252.90 Italian lire,
down from 1,253.25; and 1.2455 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2468.
   In London, the dollar also fell against the the British pound
which was quoted at $1.8357, more expensive than $1.8300 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $449.60 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $448.75. At mid-morning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $450.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $449.75 at noon, up from $448.50
late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 19 cents an ounce to close at
$452.06 bid.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.48 a troy
ounce, up from late Tuesday's $6.46.
</TEXT>
