<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-23 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Higher Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar, which fell sharply against the Japanese
yen Tuesday, recovered slightly today, while stock prices also
rebounded moderately in Tokyo trading.
   After opening at 126.91 yen, the dollar edged up and closed at
127.15 yen, the day's high, up 0.08 yen from the close of 127.07
yen on Tuesday, when the dollar fell 1.28 yen.
   ``The trading was quiet in the absence of market-affecting news
and notable movements among participants,'' said Ken Iiya of the
Bank of Tokyo.
   The market also was nervous about possible intervention by the
Bank of Japan to support the dollar, he said.
   Japan's central bank reportedly bought dollars to prop up the
sagging U.S. currency when it fell to near 126.90 yen Tuesday,
traders said.
   The prevalent market view is that the dollar lacks strength,
Iiya said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Average of 225 selected
issues, a 123.51-point loser Tuesday, gained 52.48 points, or 0.2
percent, closing at 25,895.23.
   ``The afternoon trading was not active as corporate investors
took a cautious attitude, waiting for any market-affecting news,
such as the U.S. consumer price index for February, which will be
released later in the evening,'' said Toshihisa Haruumi of Wako
Securities.
   Most buy orders centered around large-capital issues, such as
steels and heavy electricals, and they boosted the overall volume
of trading, he said.
   The volume of first section trading today was a heavy 1.5
billion shares, up from 1.1 billion shares Tuesday.
   Besides major heavy industries, chemicals and papers were
popular. Shipbuilding issues, pulps and many issues of securities
companies and banks also rose.
</TEXT>
