<1ST_LINE>u f PM-StampPrices     03-23 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stamp Prices,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historical Mail Costs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Postage Rates Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a rundown of the historical cost of
mailing a first-class letter in the United States.
   In the first half of the 19th century the cost of sending a
single sheet of paper 40 miles or less was between 6 cents and 8
cents, with the cost rising by distance. Letters going 400 miles
and over cost 25 cents to send, per sheet of paper.
   By the middle of that century postage stamps were introduced,
along with standard rates regardless of distance traveled. These
started at 2 cents per half-ounce in 1863, rising to 3 cents in
1883.
   In 1885, the current first-class standard based on one-ounce was
started. The one-ounce rates since then have been:
   July 1, 1885: 2 cents.
   Nov. 3, 1917: 3 cents.
   July 1, 1919: 2 cents.
   July 6, 1932: 3 cents.
   Aug. 1, 1958: 4 cents.
   Jan. 7, 1963: 5 cents.
   Jan. 7, 1968: 6 cents.
   May 16, 1971: 8 cents.
   March 2, 1974: 10 cents.
   Dec. 31, 1975: 13 cents.
   May 29, 1978: 15 cents.
   March 22, 1981: 18 cents.
   Nov. 1, 1981: 20 cents.
   Feb. 17, 1985: 22 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880323-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0745EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TransitionStamp     03-23 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transition Stamp,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`E' Stamp to Mark Rate Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Postage Rates Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the new postage rates take effect April
3, Americans will be using special ``E'' stamps on an interim basis.
   The stamps were printed bearing the letter E, instead of the
amount of postage, because the new first-class rate was not known
in time for printing of the millions of stamps needed for a new
rate to take effect.
   The E stamps will represent 25 cents postage.
   In addition some post offices should have supplies of the
25-cent stamp featuring the portrait of adventure writer Jack
London, which was introduced last year.
   And most offices have supplies of 1-cent, 2-cent and 3-cent
stamps to combine with current 22-cent stamps to reach the new
quarter rate.
   Undenominated stamps have been used four times in the past,
although the basic design of the stamp has changed.
   The A, B, C and D stamps all showed the head of an eagle, each
in a different color.
   The E stamp carries a multi-colored space-based image of the
planet with the word Earth printed beneath.
   The stamp also carries the notation ``Domestic'' since it can be
used only for mail within the country. Mail traveling to other
nations requires stanps that show their denomination.
</TEXT>
