<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru f0051 03-23 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0051,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fourth-quarter GNP Rose Sharply, February Consumer Prices Up A Bit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS New 5th graf, In a ... third quarter, to UPDATE with
report on corporate profits. Picks up 5th graf pvs, In its ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy grew at a brisk 4.8 percent annual rate in the
final three months of 1987 while February consumer prices were
modestly higher, indicating that inflation was under control, the
government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said the gross national product, the
broadest measure of economic health, grew from October to December
at the fastest clip in about two years.
   It was the second upward revision in GNP growth. A month ago the
government put GNP growth at 4.5 percent, up from a 4.2 percent
original estimate made in January immediately after the quarter
ended.
   Today's revisions showed more strength than previously believed
in such key sectors as consumer spending, business investment and
U.S. exports.
   In a second report, the department said U.S. corporations'
after-tax profits rose 1.6 percent in the fourth quarter, the
poorest showing since profits fell 3.7 percent in the first quarter
of 1987. Profits were up 5.5 percent in the third quarter.
   In its report on inflation, the Labor Department said that last
month's consumer prices rose a modest 0.2 percent due to lower food
and energy costs.
   Food prices fell 0.3 percent after rising 0.3 percent in
January. Energy costs, which had fallen 0.7 percent in the
preceding month, fell 0.6 percent last month.
   So far this year, consumer prices have been increasing at a rate
of 3.2 percent. That compares to the moderate 4.4 percent rate for
all of 1987 and the scant 1.1 percent 1986 increase.
   On Tuesday, the Commerce Department said that orders to U.S.
factories for durable goods _ items expected to last at least three
years _ fell 1.8 percent in February to a seasonally adjusted
$111.4 billion, following an identical decline in January.
   In other economic news on Tuesday, the Dow Jones average of 30
industrial stocks fell 0.99 point to 2,066.15; the dollar was mixed
against other major currencies; and bond prices were little changed
in light trading.
   February marked the first time since the spring of 1986 that
durable goods orders declined for two consecutive months.
   But some economists maintained that manufacturing companies
still were enjoying good business because the weaker dollar has
boosted export demand.
   Cynthia Latta, an economist with Data Resources Inc., said that
while new orders fell in February the total backlog of unfilled
orders rose 0.7 percent, the 12th consecutive monthly increase.
   ``This backlog suggests that factories can keep humming along
for a while even though new orders dropped,'' she said.
   Still, analysts said, the back-to-back declines showed
businesses were cutting back on orders in the early part of 1988 in
an effort to get control of bulging inventories. Inventories
swelled at the end of 1987 while consumer demand fell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
