<DOCNO> AP880323-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0932EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-LuckyStores Bjt   03-23 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lucky Stores, Bjt,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Stores Offers $1.74 Billion For Lucky Stores</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucky Stores Inc.'s stock soared $14.50 a
share Tuesday after the major California supermarket chain received
a $1.74 billion tender offer from American Stores Co.
   If American Stores' $45-a-share bid is successful, it would
create the nation's largest grocery store chain. In heavy trading
on the New York Stock Exchange, Lucky's stock surged to close at
$46.375 a share. American Stores stock fell $2.62{ a share to
$57.87{.
   Officials at Lucky's headquarters in Dublin, Calif., would not
discuss the offer except to say company bylaws contain a ``poison
pill'' anti-takeover provision, which limits the voting power of
any shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of Lucky's stock.
   Company officials noted in a statement that the limited voting
rights provision, which expires Dec. 22, may not be waived by the
company's board.
   Lucky, the nation's sixth largest grocery retailer, has 480
stores while American Stores, the third biggest, has 1,600 stores.
   In a letter to Lucky Stores Chairman John M. Lillie, American
Stores Chairman L.S. Skaggs said he would combine American's Alpha
Beta stores with Lucky's operation under the Lucky name.
   The letter, released Tuesday, praised Lucky's management and
marketing strategies and invited Lucky executives to stay on if the
deal is completed. Lucky's headquarters also would remain at
Dublin, Skaggs said.
   Officials at Salt Lake City-based American Stores would not
provide further details of their unsolicited offer and had no
comment beyond a brief press release, said senior vice president
Michael Miller.
   Recent rumors have suggested that American Stores itself may be
a takeover target, according to an analyst here who said his
company has extensive dealings with the company.
   Under that scenario, the bid for Lucky could be a defensive move
to make an acquisition of American Stores prohibitively expensive,
said the analyst, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``If American Stores doesn't get this acquisition, it puts the
spotlight on them. They may be more open to takeover than before,''
he said.
   Analysts agreed the Lucky-American Stores combination makes
sense.
   Susan C. Schmierer, a retail analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., noted that the two companies operate in the same
general geographic areas and that both want to increase their
presence in California.
   ``I don't see any reason why it couldn't go through, given the
right kind of management finesse by American,'' she said.
   The bid for Lucky comes 16 months after takeover strategist
Asher Edelman formally dropped his hostile bid for the company in
return for Lucky's agreement to pay $2.8 million of his legal costs.
   Lucky thwarted Edelman partly by selling off non-grocery
divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures that make it more
difficult for an unwanted suitor to acquire the company.
   American Stores' most recent acquisition occurred in 1984 when
it took over Jewel Companies Inc., a Chicago-based grocery, drug
and convenience store chain, for $1.1 billion.
   The acquisition expanded American Stores' operations from just
over 1,000 retail outlets to 1,700 stores in 40 states and boosted
sales to about $15 billion a year.
   The company is organized into three divisions. The Skaggs
division operates supermarkets in the western United States;
American Superstores runs stores in the Midwest and the East; and
Osco Drug Stores operates stores nationwide, according to Value
Line Investment Survey.
   Store names include Acme, Jewel, Star, Buttrey, Skaggs, Skaggs
Alpha Beta and Osco Drug Stores.
   Lucky, with annual sales of about $7 billion, operates about 480
supermarkets and food centers in the West, Midwest and Southwest,
principally in California and Arizona.
</TEXT>
