<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1101EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Banks-Redlining 1stLd-Writethru   03-23 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banks-Redlining, 1st Ld-Writethru,0598</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 8th graf pvs, Despite a, to CORRECT Ms. Cincotta's
title.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many banks seem more willing to lend money to
poor countries abroad than to take a chance on redeveloping poor
neighborhoods in their own area, community representatives are
telling Congress.
   ``We're saying, `Look ... you lend billions of dollars across
the border and you can't lend to our community that is on this side
of the border,''' said Tony Reyes, mayor of San Luis, Ariz., a town
of 2,000 near Mexico.
   ``I don't think that is fair,'' he told the Senate Banking
Committee, which is reviewing compliance with the Community
Reinvestment Act of 1977.
   The law requires banks to lend in their depositors'
neighborhoods and prohibits ``redlining,'' the practice of denying
loans to an entire neighborhood based on the race or economic class
of its residents.
   It gives regulators the authority to block banks with poor
records from opening new branches or merging with other
institutions.
   ``Redlining hasn't disappeared,'' Sen. William Proxmire, the
committee chairman, said Tuesday. ``Neighborhoods are still
starving for credit. Too many bankers still think the grass is
greener elsewhere.''
   He noted that an estimated $5 billion in loans have been made in
poor neighborhoods as a result of the act, but said, ``That $5
billion pledged to developing neighborhoods is peanuts compared to
the $100 billion loaned to developing countries.''
   Despite a rating system by regulators that gives the vast
majority of banks high marks for their anti-redlining efforts, the
actual performance of most is poor, said Gale Cincotta, executive
director of the National Training and Information Center, a Chicago
community group.
   ``Hundreds of census tracts in low-income America did not
receive a penny in mortgage loans,'' she said.
   Proxmire, D-Wis., said that 97 percent of all lenders pass
Community Reinvestment Act reviews with flying colors and only
eight of 40,000 applications from banks seeking to merge or expand
have been denied in the past 10 years.
   ``How is it that so many neighborhoods are continuing to fail,
while so many lending institutions are continuing to pass?'' he
asked. ``This record ... raises questions about whether the
examination process has succeeded.''
   Allen J. Fishbein, general counsel of the Center for Community
Change, a Washington organization that provides training for
neighborhood groups, said progress in enforcing the law during the
late 70s has ``been virtually undone as a result of agency
indifference over the past five or six years.''
   Ms. Cincotta complained that bank examiners, in effect, rely on
community groups to enforce the law for them by filing complaints.
   She said that although examiners are well trained at judging the
financial soundness of a bank, many are poorly schooled in judging
a bank's fair housing or equal opportunity record.
   Jane Uebelhoer, legislative representative of ACORN (Association
of Community Organizations for Reform Now), said Congress should
revamp the regulators' rating system so that banks with poor
records get poor marks.
   The committee, which is reviewing enforcement of the act with an
eye toward possibly toughening it, planned a second session today
to hear from federal bank regulators.
   The House Banking Committee has discussed attaching provisions
strengthening the Community Revinvestment Act to legislation
primarily aimed at granting banks new investment powers.
   The Senate committee has already passed its version of that bill
but could go along with the House provisions if senators are
convinced by testimony this week that changes are needed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
