<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Scotus-EstateTax     03-23 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Estate Tax,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rules Against Estate Tax Exemption for Some Public
Housing Notes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled today that short-term
notes used to finance public housing projects are not exempt from
federal estate taxes.
   The 8-0 ruling was a victory for the Reagan administration,
which said more than $260 million in federal tax revenue was at
stake.
   The dispute stems in part from a 1937 law Congress enacted to
stimulate local financing of housing projects. The act allowed
public housing agencies to issue tax-free obligations called
``project notes.''
   For some 47 years, it was assumed the law exempted the notes
from federal income tax but not from federal estate tax.
   But a federal judge in Illinois ruled in 1984 that the notes
were exempt from estate taxes as well. The decision touched off
widepsread efforts to market project notes and prompted those who
had paid estate taxes on the notes to seek refunds from the
government.
   Within months of the Illinois ruling, Congress enacted the
Deficit Reduction Act of 1984 that included a provision making the
project notes subject to estate, gift and inheritance taxes.
   The law took effect on June 19, 1984.
   Heirs to people who died before that date said the law cannot be
applied retroactively and they sought refunds from the government
for estate taxes they paid on project notes.
   But today the Supreme Court said the project notes have been
subject to the estate tax all along, even if the 1937 law did not
make that explicitly clear.
   Justice William J. Brennan, in his opinion for the court, said
the 1937 act was designed to exempt the project notes ``only from
the normal tax'' _ that is federal income tax and surtaxes that
were in effect at the time.
   ``Exemptions from taxation are not to be implied. They must be
unambiguously proved,'' Brennan said. ``On the rare occasions when
Congress exempted property from estate taxation it has generally
adverted explicitly to that tax rather than generically to `all
taxation.'''
   He said it would not make sense for Congress to grant special
exemptions to the project notes without stating it explicitly since
the purpose of such an exemption would be to attract investors.
   ``If Congress really wanted to create an especially broad tax
exemption for project notes ... one would expect it to do so
notoriously enough to attract investors, not surreptitiously enough
to evade detection for half a century,'' Brennan said.
   He added that today's ruling made it unnecessary for the
justices to decide whether the 1984 budget reduction law chould be
applied retroactively.
   The ruling reverses lower court decisions granting estate
exemptions to project notes.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy did not take part in the ruling.
   The case is U.S. vs. Crocker National Bank, 86-1521.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
