<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed to
slightly higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   One analyst called traders ``gun-shy.'' That proved an accurate
description as soybeans opened strongly, but then turned
surprisingly calm.
   Traders said there was a lack of follow-through buying after
contract highs were set Tuesday for new-crop months in soybeans.
   Wheat, meanwhile, was firm on talk of export business with India
and the Soviet Union.
   On the open, wheat was 1{ cents to 2\ cents higher, with the
contract for May delivery at $3.09 a bushel; corn was unchanged to
{ cent higher, with May at $2.07 a bushel; oats were \ cent lower,
with May at $1.69} a bushel; and soybeans were } cent lower to 1
cent higher, with May at $6.44 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures prices were mostly lower at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle opened .40 cent lower to .02 cent higher, with April
at 74.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle .05 cent to .25 cent lower,
