<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks slipped this morning in moderate trading,
which brokers attributed to an overwhelming lack of buying interest
and confusion about the market's overall direction.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which barely budged in
slack trading Tuesday, fell 8.13 points to 2,058.02 by noon on Wall
Street.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 0.26 to 151.26. The
American Stock Exchange's market value index rose 0.52 to 299.32.
   Losing stocks narrowly outnumbered gainers on the NYSE, with 697
down, 623 up and 501 unchanged. Volume totaled 81.58 million shares
in the morning session, vs. 65.3 million Tuesday morning.
   ``We're just standing here,'' said William King, head trader at
Nikko Securities Co. International in New York. ``You need money to
take stocks up, and the money's not there.''
   Blue-chip stocks were widely lower. IBM fell 1{ to 111|, Procter
& Gamble fell 1\ to 80], McDonalds fell } to 44], Bethlehem Steel
fell | to 21~, Sears fell } to 38 and Boeing fell 1 to 47{.
   As in recent sessions, takeover-related trading was the most
active area. Lucky Stores, target of a $45-a-share acquisition
offer from American Stores, rose 1} to 48{ after surging 14{ on
Tuesday when the offer was announced.
   Among other rumored and actual speculative takeover stocks,
American Standard fell ] to 76\, Moore McCormack rose 1\ to 38],
Pillsbury fell 1\ to 44{, and Gillette rose 1] to 40].
   Airline stocks were widely higher, reflecting a decline in oil
prices that could reduce fuel costs. Allegis rose 1| to 86[, AMR
rose { to 44~ and Delta rose | to 52.
