<1ST_LINE>a f BC-France-Cows Adv26-27   03-23 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-France-Cows, Adv 26-27,0732</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 26-27 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Genetic High Technology Down on the Farm</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR13 of March 21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FIONA GLEIZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   That cow munching in a Normandy meadow may not be
all that she seems. Her father might be Bubba from Rising Sun, Md.,
and her grandfather the famed American bull Pawnee Farm Arlinda
Chief.
   Such international hybrids are the result of artificial
insemination and embryo transfer, two genetic breeding techniques
now gaining favor on European farms.
   Glossy pinups of champion bulls were a feature of the recently
ended annual Agriculture Show in Paris, catching the eye of French
farmers eager to improve the quality of their herds.
   ``Paris Special Offer _ Low-Cost Embryos'' read the sign on
another stand.
   The breeding methods offer Common Market farmers a way to
improve the quality of their production without adding to Europe's
burgeoning surplus of milk.
   Farmers who have slaughtered cows for meat to stay within milk
quotas imposed by the European Economic Community are hoping to
maintain production levels in the future with fewer animals.
   ``One high-quality cow is cheaper to feed than two which produce
the same quantity of milk,'' said a French technical adviser to
World Wide Sires, Inc. of Hanford, Calif.
   Artificial insemination involves taking semen from a bull and
injecting it into a cow. The technique differs from embryo transfer
in that no eggs are removed from a cow and fertilization takes
place in the womb. With embryo transfer, an egg is fertilized in a
test tube and later implanted in the womb.
   Exhibitors interviewed at the Agriculture Show said the United
States and Canada have the best genetic stock in dairy cattle, and
there is an active trans-Atlantic market in frozen sperm and
embryos.
   ``World Wide Sires has 10 million Holsteins at nine cooperatives
in the U.S.,'' said Ginny Barker, one of the company's regional
marketing directors. ``It's a huge genetic pool.''
   The black and white Holstein cow, which was shipped from Germany
to the United States between 1850 and 1900, is the most popular
milking cow worldwide.
   ``In France alone, it makes up 90 percent of the dairy herd,''
said Gerard Andre, director of a French cattle exporting company.
   ``And nearly all French dairy cows have American Holstein
blood,'' he said.
   It might seem ironic that European herds are being upgraded with
North American imports of a European breed.
   The World Wide Sires representative explained that American
breeders had aimed for specialized high-yielding dairy cows.
   ``But European farmers had stuck with dual-purpose beef and milk
producers, such as the Normandy cow,'' he said.
   Not everyone agrees that artificial insemination is the best
technique for getting the right kind of animals. The British
company Heine Brothers is promoting embryos.
   ``Our market is in commercial embryos for the everyday farmer,''
said Richard Price, Heine's livestock manager.
   ``At the moment farmers are using artificial insemination. We
say our embryos will take over,'' he said.
   When beef cattle are killed in the slaughterhouse, the ovaries
are taken from the carcasses and the eggs removed. They are
fertilized in vitro, then implanted in sheep's womb to mature for
six days before being taken out and frozen.
   These embryos, from beef strains such as the Limousin, are
implanted in the wombs of Holstein cows, in a simple operation.
   Mike Keeble, marketing manager of Heine said ``a farmer has the
best of both worlds with this technique, because in the same herd
he will have some good beef animals and his super-efficient
Holsteins for milking.''
   ``By introducing these embryos, we can change a whole herd,'' he
said.
   Heine is looking outside Europe for new markets and hopes its
embryos will be used to build up cattle herds in countries such as
Ethiopia and Saudi Arabia.
   ``Many people in African and Arab countries are unable to drink
milk after they are 5 years old,'' said Keeble. ``But their
stomachs can take yogurt and they want to eat more meat.''
   ``So we can build up dual-purpose herds, which provide milk for
yogurt and beef, reducing the need for goat or camel meat,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 26-27</NOTE>
