<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Intel-Micron     03-23 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Intel-Micron,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intel To Sell Micron Memory Chips, Gets Stock Warrant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intel Corp. said today it will sell computer
memory chips made by Micron Technology Inc. and has received a
warrant to buy stock in the Boise, Idaho-based chip maker.
   The deal with Intel, one of the nation's biggest independent
chip makers, should give Micron some long-term stability in the
volatile business.
   Micron is one of only two U.S. companies, along with Texas
Instruments Inc., that have withstood competition from Japan to
continue producing the common chips known as dynamic random access
memories, D-RAMs.
   The computer and electronics industry has been hampered in
recent months by a severe shortage of computer memory chips. The
Intel-Micron deal will initially apply only to 256K D-RAMs, the
generation of chips that is gradually being replaced by the more
powerful 1-megabit D-RAMs.
   Intel, which dropped out of the D-RAM business several years
ago, said it received a warrant from Micron to purchase 600,000
shares of Micron stock at an exercise price of $19.37{ a share.
That would represent less than 3 percent of Micron's stock.
   Micron's stock rose to $21.12{ a share in over-the-counter
trading by midday Wednesday from its close of $19.75 a share
Tuesday.
   Intel said it would sell Micron chips under the Intel label and
would use Micron chips in its own products, such as circuit boards.
   ``Micron's alliance with Intel allows us to broaden our customer
base, and strengthens our ability to expand and compete in the
worldwide D-RAM market,'' Joe Parkinson, Micron's chairman, said in
an announcement.
   Intel's vice chairman, Robert Noyce, said the deal would help
Intel as well as ``support a key U.S. supplier of D-RAMs.''
</TEXT>
