<2ND_LINE>BC-Wards Expansion,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wards to Add 225 Stores in Next 5 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retailing giant Montgomery Ward & Co. will
celebrate its soon-to-be-granted independence from parent Mobil
Corp., by opening 225 stores over the next five years.
   Ward Chairman Bernard F. Brennan said Tuesday the expansion will
cost the nation's ninth-largest retailer about $150 million a year.
   The new stores will be additions to existing markets and the
majority will be specialty shops featuring home, audio-video,
apparel or automotive products.
   Only 10 of the new shops will contain all four product specialty
shops under one roof. Slightly more than half of Wards' 316 stores
nationwide already have been converted to the specialty-store
format.
   An investor group headed by Brennan has agreed to acquire the
company from parent Mobil for $3.8 billion. The transaction is
expected to be completed in May.
   Wards said earlier this month the acquisition would not result
in the sale of any of its stores or a reduction in its
72,000-member work force.
   Brennan said the only unit Wards' acquirers planned to sell was
its credit card operation.
</TEXT>
