<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-BAT     03-23 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-BAT,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BAT Industries Posts 15.3 Percent Profit Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC, the British conglomerate whose
U.S. interests include the retailer Saks Fifth Avenue and Brown &
Williamson Tobacco Corp., said its fourth-quarter pretax earnings
fell 15.3 percent because of the weak dollar and the October stock
market crash.
   BAT, which recently made an unsolicited $4.5 billion offer for
Farmers Group Inc. of Los Angleles, said it had pretax earnings of
433 million pounds, or $792 million, down from 511 million pounds
in the same period a year earlier.
   The company did not provide any further quarterly figures. It is
not required to do so under British law.
   For the full year, pretax earnings edged up 0.07 percent to
1.394 billion pounds from 1.393 billion pounds in all of 1986.
   Net income totaled 751 million pounds, down 13.5 percent from
868 million pounds in 1986. BAT had 36 million pounds in
extraordinary charges in 1987, and extraordinary gains of 75
million pounds in 1986.
   Sales for the year fell 10 percent to 17.2 billion pounds from
19.2 billion pounds.
   The stock market crash reduced investment appreciation income
from the company's Eagle Star financial services subsidiary to 47
million pounds in 1987 from 149 million pounds in 1986.
   Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field's, two of BAT's retailing
businesses in the United States, were affected by difficult trading
conditions, especially in the fourth quarter, the company said.
   In addition, BAT said its total 1987 pretax profit would have
been 192 million pounds higher if exchange rates had remained at
1986 levels.
</TEXT>
