<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks were mixed today in moderate trading,
which brokers attributed to an overwhelming lack of buying interest
and confusion about the market's overall direction.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which barely budged in
slack trading Tuesday, rose 1.82 points to 2,067.97 by 3 p.m. on
Wall Street.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues rose 0.12 to 151.64. The
American Stock Exchange's market value index rose 0.63 to 299.43.
   Gaining and losing stocks were about even on the NYSE, with 719
up, 711 down and 504 unchanged. Volume totaled 137 million shares
with an hour of trading left.
   ``We're just standing here,'' said William King, head trader at
Nikko Securities Co. International in New York. ``You need money to
take stocks up, and the money's not there.''
   Some traders said the market's confusion reflected conflicting
economic news. Evidence of relatively tame inflation reported by
the government suggested interest rates will not rise significantly.
   At the same time, the government revised the fourth-quarter
gross national product growth rate upward to 4.8 percent,
suggesting that the economy is healthier than previously believed
and therefore implying higher inflation and rising interest rates.
   Blue-chip stocks were widely lower. IBM fell 1[ to 112, Procter
& Gamble fell 1 to 80|, McDonalds fell | to 44{, Sears fell { to
38\ and Boeing fell 1 to 47{.
   Texaco rose 1] to 46~. A federal judge approved the oil giant's
bankruptcy reorganization plan.
   As in recent sessions, takeover-related trading was the most
active area. Lucky Stores, target of a $45-a-share acquisition
offer from American Stores, rose 2\ to 49 after surging 14{ on
Tuesday when the offer was announced.
   Among other rumored and actual speculative takeover stocks,
Textron surged 4] to 29|, Philips Petroleum rose } 1| and Gillette
rose 2{ to 41{.
