<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 1607EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   03-23 0873</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0905</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Slows in February, GNP Growth Revised Upward for 4th
Quarter 1987</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS ultimate graf pvs, bgng: In yet, with three new grafs to
add real earnings report. Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government delivered two welcome pieces of
economic news on Wednesday: Consumer prices rose just 0.2 percent
in February and the economy in late 1987 expanded at the liveliest
pace in nearly two years.
   Falling energy and food prices in February helped restrain the
rise in the Labor Department's Consumer Price Index after a 0.3
percent increase in January.
   For the first two months of the year, prices increased at an
annual rate of 3.2 percent _ much better than last year's moderate
4.4 percent inflation.
   In a separate report, the Commerce Department said the U.S.
economy grew at a brisk 4.8 percent annual pace in the final three
months of last year. It was the second upward revision in the
fourth-quarter GNP, estimated a month ago at 4.5 percent and in
January at 4.2 percent.
   The department said better-than-expected performance in exports,
consumer spending and business investment led to the latest
revision, which pushed growth for the year to a rate of 4 percent,
compared with 2.2 percent growth in 1986. It was the biggest annual
increase since a 5.1 percent rise in 1984.
   The 4.8 percent fourth-quarter growth followed a 4.3 percent
growth in the July-September quarter and was the fastest quarterly
growth rate since an increase of 5.4 percent in the first three
months of 1986.
   Recent economic reports have shown an economy that rebounded
quickly from last October's stock market collapse. Analysts see
little likelihood of an election-year recession.
   ``One of the best kept secrets in economic circles these days is
that the Reagan administration is going to end with a bang, not a
whimper, as the economy makes a successful transition to an
export-led economy,'' President Reagan said in a speech to the
American Business Conference.
   Meanwhile, his spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, hailed Wednesday's
reports: ``Inflation remains under control, the economy is doing
well, the Reagan miracle holds.''
   Food prices fell 0.3 percent in February, erasing a 0.3 percent
gain in January. Fruits and vegetables led the way with a 4 percent
tumble. Lettuce prices, which more than doubled at the end of 1987,
dropped 25.1 percent in February.
   Energy prices fell 0.6 percent, with falling gasoline prices
more than offsetting increases in household fuels.
   At-the-pump gasoline prices fell 1.7 percent in February, the
third consecutive decline. Gasoline prices have fallen 5.9 percent
in six months.
   Heating oil and other household fuels were up 0.6 percent;
natural gas and electricity prices rose 0.5 percent.
   ``There is at this point no indication of any major widespread
acceleration of inflation,'' said Lawrence Chimerine, chairman of
the Wefa Group, a Philadelphia-area economic forecasting service.
   Competition in retailing contributed to the favorable inflation
performance, Chimerine said. ``Stores have been holding down price
increases.''
   Items other than food and energy were up a modest 0.2 percent in
February.
   Still, there remained pockets of inflation, particularly in
service industries. Medical care services were up 0.7 percent in
February, while ``other services'' rose 0.6 percent.
   ``There are some chronic price problems in the economy,'' said
Sandra Shaber, senior economist for the Futures Group, a Washington
management consultanting firm. ``These increases in health care are
not going to go away.''
   ``But if we continue to get a break on food and energy prices,
that certainly is good news,'' she added.
   However, Allen Sinai, chief economist for the Boston Co., said
the ``big issue is whether these good results we are getting so far
this year are transitory or permanent. Food and energy price
declines are reversible almost any time.''
   In other February price movements:
   _New automobile prices rose 0.3 percent.
   _Clothing prices fell 0.3 percent.
   _Alcoholic beverage prices rose 0.9 percent.
   Last month's seasonally adjusted 0.2 percent gain in the CPI was
equivalent to a compounded annual inflation rate of 2.1 percent,
Labor Department analysts said.
   The February increase left the overall index at 116.0, meaning
that a hypothetical selection of goods costing $100 during a
1982-84 base period would have cost $116.00 last month.
   Unlike other figures in the report, the overall index is not
adjusted for seasonal fluctuations.
   The Labor Department recently changed its base period. Had the
former computation been used, the February consumer price index
would have been 347.4 compared with a 1967 base of 100.
   That means the same selection of goods would have cost $13.00
more last month than in February 1987, when the CPI was 334.4.
   In two other economic reports:
   _The Commerce Department said after-tax corporate profits shot
up 8.4 percent in 1987 to $137.4 billion after declining the year
before. Analysts credited the turnaround in profits to the weaker
dollar, which has boosted U.S. sales overseas, and to subdued labor
wage demands.
   _The Labor Department said Americans' average weekly earnings,
after discounting for inflation, edged up 0.2 percent in February.
It was the second monthly advance, matching an identical 0.2
percent January increase, but it still left Americans'
inflation-adjusted earnings 0.7 percent below where they were a
year ago.
</TEXT>
