<2ND_LINE>AM-BankAmerica,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BankAmerica Denies Takeover Rumor That Pushed Stock Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp., whose stock jumped 6 percent
in active trading Wednesday, denied rumors that it may be the
target of a takeover by a Japanese bank.
   BankAmerica stock closed up 62.5 cents at $11.125 a share in
heavy New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Dan Dorfman, appearing on CNN's ``Moneyline'' program Tuesday
night, said he had heard a rumor that a Japanese bank may be
interested in acquiring part of all of BankAmerica.
   BankAmerica said in a statement from its headquarters in San
Francisco that there was ``no basis for the rumors.''
   Dorfman said Wednesday from his office at USA Today, where he
works as a columnist, that he ``emphasized the word rumor'' and
mentioned the rumor to explain the heavy dealing in BankAmerica
stock on Tuesday.
   Analysts quickly disputed the claim.
   ``It's unlikely,'' said Mark Alpert, an analyst with Bear,
Stearns & Co. ``There have been plenty of opportunities in the past
for Japanese banks to take a position in BankAmerica, and nothing
has occurred.
   ``It doesn't mean it can't happen, but it's unlikely,'' he said.
   Likewise, Rodrigo Quintanilla of Argus Research Corp. said that
while only West German and Japanese institutions are in a financial
position to take on the huge banking company, ``I still don't
consider it to be a takeover target.''
</TEXT>
