<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Smoking-Airlines     03-23 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoking-Airlines,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>To Smoke or Not to Smoke: Two Cases in Point</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Northwest-Smoking, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines' new smoking ban hits the
air-travel market at a time when anti-puffing campaigns are gaining
momentum, but it may revive a debate that snuffed out a pioneer of
smoke-free flying.
   Muse Air Corp. of Dallas tried and failed to establish itself as
the nation's only no-smoking airline in 1985.
   The effort _ which offered passengers discounted tickets if they
turned in their cigarettes at the gate _ was scrapped when the
airline was purchased later that year by Southwest Airlines Co. for
$65 million.
   While the regional carrier had begun to draw its identity from
its no-smoking policy, its research showed the practice was chasing
away as many as 35 percent of potential passengers.
   Surveys revealed that fliers find ``price, convenience and
service more important than non-smoking'' in choosing an airline,
Muse spokeswoman Shari Cohen said at the time.
   She said Muse may have been a bit ahead of its time by banning
smoking and that the pioneer role may have hurt.
   Even now, in the wake of the federal government's move to ban
smoking on all air flights lasting less than two hours, some
militant smokers are holding fast.
   The Great American Smoker's Club of Dallas is scheduled to make
its grand entrance on April 22, a day before the government's ban
goes into effect. The group, founded by two businessmen, aims to
evade the ban by charging a membership fee.
   For $25 a year or $40 for a family, smokers can join the club
and pay the same fares Southwest charges to fly from Dallas' Love
Field to Austin, Houston, New Orleans, Oklahoma City, San Antonio
and Tulsa.
   The club is leasing several planes from Las Vegas-based Royal
West Airlines, said club president Glenn Herndon, who estimated the
startup cost at $2 million.
   ``We want to offer cigarette smokers a choice to continue their
right to smoke,'' he said. ``To fly on a plane nowadays, smokers
are treated like second-class citizens and must sit on the back
rows. When the smoking ban begins, we want to offer smokers an
alternative _ and, hopefully, make some money.''
   Herndon said the club's target is to serve 63 cities from five
hubs with 60 planes within two years.
   By the way, non-smokers will be allowed on board, but they will
have to be ``tolerant,'' the club says.
</TEXT>
