<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   03-23 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Makers Report Mid-March Sales Declines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic car sales fell slightly in mid-March
despite a selling surge at Chrysler Corp., automakers reported
Wednesday.
   Analysts said an earlier flurry of higher-than-expected sales
due to incentives and a stock-crash rebound appeared to be tapering
off.
   The eight companies that make autos in the United States sold
189,245 cars in the eight sales days from March 11-20, down from
217,939 in nine sales days in the comparable 1987 period. The daily
sales rate was down 2.3 percent.
   Sales of domestically made light trucks totaled 109,509, down
from 115,684 in the year ago period but still a 6.5 percent
increase in daily sales.
   Combined domestic car and light truck sales totaled 298,754,
down from 333,623 for mid-March 1987 but up 0.7 percent on a daily
basis.
   Sales of foreign-made cars are reported at the end of the month.
   Domestic sales were at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6.4
million for the mid-March period.
   That would indicate a decline from the industry's 7.1 million in
domestic sales in 1987. For the prior 30 days, however, sales ran
at an 8.1 million seasonally adjusted annual rate.
   ``It looks like sales are beginning to drop back down to a more
expected level,'' said Chris Cedergren, auto analyst at J.D. Power
& Associates in Westlake Village, Calif.
   Jeannette Garretty, an analyst at the Bank of America in San
Francisco, said sales surged prior to the mid-March period as
consumers reacted to incentives and made purchases put off due to
caution after the October stock market crash. ``Now it is going to
start to settle down,'' she said.
   Industry leader General Motors Corp. sold 92,173 domestically
made cars in the March 11-20 period, down from 105,438 in the
comparable 1987 period. The daily sales rate was off 1.7 percent.
   Ford Motor Co. auto sales of 54,186 were down from 67,672 in the
year-earlier period, and down 9.9 percent on a daily basis.
   Chrysler car sales jumped to 30,801 from 31,699 in the same
period in 1987, up 9.3 percent on a daily sales basis, aided by
strong sales of Chrysler New Yorker and Landau luxury models, the
company said.
   Chrysler's domestic light truck sales jumped even more, totaling
24,691, up from 20,987 in the year-earlier period and up 32.4
percent in daily sales.
   It was the eighth straight period of rising car sales at
Chrysler, said Tom Pappert, group vice president for sales. ``We
are clearly going into the spring selling season with momentum on
our side.''
   GM also was a gainer in truck sales with an eight-day total of
45,376, up from 43,515. The daily sales rate was up 17.3 percent.
   Ford light truck sales sagged to 36,812, from 49,164 in the
year-earlier period. The daily sales rate fell 15.8 percent.
   Market shares of the Big Three automakers changed only slightly
from the year-earlier period, with GM capturing 48.7 percent,
compared with 48.4 percent; Ford accounting for 28.6 percent, down
from 31.1 percent, and Chrysler moving up to 16.3 percent from 14.5
percent in the year-earlier period.
   Aggressive incentives paid off for some Japanese companies
manufacturing cars in the United States. Honda's sales of 7,270
represented a 9.8 percent increase in its daily sales rate.
   Volkswagen of America sold 1,034 U.S.-made cars, down 12.5
percent from 1,330 a year earlier.
   The Big Three U.S. automakers accounted for 93.6 percent of U.S.
sales of U.S.-made cars.
   ``We continue to be pleased with the strength of the market,''
said C.N. Moore, vice president in charge of customer sales and
service at GM.
</TEXT>
