<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GrolierTakeover     03-23 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grolier Takeover,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grolier Board Rejects Unsolicited Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn., (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grolier Inc. said Wednesday its board
had rejected as inadequate a $415 million takeover bid from French
publisher Hachette SA, and said it has talked with others who may
be interested in making a rival proposal.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Grolier's stock rose 12{ cents a
share to close at $26.50, a price that was well above the
$21-a-share bid from Hachette.
   ``The rejection of a $21 bid when the stock was at $26 was no
great shock,'' said Jane Gilday, managing director of McKinley
Allsopp Inc. in New York. ``Grolier made it clear there are other
bidders and they're committed to maximizing shareholder value.''
   Grolier said its board of directors was unanimous in rejecting
as inadequate the unsolicited takeover offer from Hachette.
   ``In this regard, representatives of Grolier have had
preliminary contact with several parties who have indicated an
interest in making a proposal to acquire the company,'' Robert B.
Clarke, chairman and chief executive, said in a statement. Clarke
did not name the companies.
   Grolier said that if it is unable to negotiate an acquisition of
the company on satisfactory terms, it will look at other
alternatives such as a leveraged buyout or a financial
restructuring.
   ``I think the next move is that Grolier will now entertain these
other bids,'' Gilday said. ``And, Hachette could raise its bid.''
   Hannah Bruce, vice president of Tucker Anthony & R.L. Day in New
York, said, ``The way the stock market has reacted throughout this
whole two weeks, it appears the market feels Grolier will be worth
more.''
   Danbury-based Grolier is a publisher of encyclopedias, reference
and educational books and children's books, and owns a film
processing firm. It earned $22.1 million on sales of $424.2 million
in 1987. The company has 7,300 employees in 20 countries.
   Hachette, France's biggest publisher, said last week that it was
offering $21 a share in cash for the 95 percent of Grolier's
roughly 19.5 million shares that it did not already own.
   Bruce said Grolier has a strong management team and credited the
company's turnaround in the last decade to Clarke.
   ``The company was near bankruptcy in the late 1970s, Clarke came
in as chairman and he rebuilt it. He divested all non-publishing
activity and structured the enclopedia group,'' Bruce said. ``The
company is very strong. ... Earnings are growing 30 percent-plus a
year.''
   She said the company has some ``very attractive pieces,''
including its adult and childrens' book clubs.
   ``They basically sell their products to parents with young
children,'' she said. ``They have a strong customer base.''
</TEXT>
