<FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 2137EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KCSouthern     03-23 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-KC Southern,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kansas City Southern Questions Motives Behind Takeover Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas City Southern Industries Inc.
said Wednesday that a proposed buyout effort by a New York
developer may be designed to stimulate trading in the company's
stock and to draw attention to the developer's previously-disclosed
plan to win two board seats.
   The railroad, data processing and financial services company
noted that Howard Kaskel, the New York developer, had simply
proposed talks toward a possible negotiated merger in his letter to
the company this week.
   It said the letter did not contain an offer to shareholders, and
does not state that financing for any transaction has been obtained.
   In the letter, Kaskel proposed buying the 89 percent of the
company's 11.1 million shares that his group doesn't already
control for $60 a share in cash. Such a transaction would be worth
about $590 million.
   ``The letter appears to be an effort to stimulate trading in the
Kansas City Southern Industries' stock and perhaps to publicize
Kaskel's previously announced plan to nominate two persons for
election to the Kansas City Southern Industries' board of
directors,'' the company's statement said.
   A call was placed after business hours to Kaskel's lawyer for
comment, but the lawyer could not be reached.
   Wall Street has indicated skepticism about whether an offer will
be forthcoming. In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Kansas
City Southern fell $2 a share to $54.50 on Wednesday.
   ``If Mr. Kaskel, as a large shareholder, wishes to nominate an
individual ... we would certainly be pleased to consider such a
person,'' Kansas City Southern President Landon H. Rowland was
quoted as saying in his company's statement.
   The statement said the ``on-again, off-again efforts of the
Kaskel group to thwart Kansas City Southern Industries' proposed
acquisition of the Southern Pacific ... are viewed by management as
inconsistent with the best interests of the company and its
stockholders.''
   Rowland said earlier in the week that the KCSI board would
consider the Kaskel proposal at a special meeting, but declined to
say when the meeting would be held.
</TEXT>
